<FILEID>AP-NR-12-06-89 0139EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Ethiopia-Famine     12-06 0235</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ethiopia-Famine,0241</SECOND>
<HEAD>Up To Four Million of Ethiopians Said To Face Possible Starvation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crop failure in civil war-plagued Ethiopia
threatens up to four million people with a famine worse than the
mass starvation of five years ago, the 24-nation Organization for
Economic Cooperation and Development says.
   ``The situation in the coming months risks being more serious
than in 1984-85,'' when 1 million Ethiopians starved to death, said
Joe Wheeler, president of the Paris-based organization's Committee
for Aid and Development.
   Food shortages stemming from crop failure are aggravated by
difficulties in distributing emergency aid across combat zones in
northern Ethiopia, Wheeler said Tuesday after the committee's
annual meeting on world development aid.
   The committee called on the world community to help get aid
through to hard-to-reach regions.
   Wheeler said several regions controlled by forces opposed to
Ethiopia's government are no longer producing enough food to feed
their populations.
   The Marxist government must overcome its traditional reluctance
to open up contact to rebel-held areas if the civilian population
is to have any chance of surviving 1990, Wheeler said.
   ``It's often possible to persuade governments to permit certain
actions for humanitarian reasons,'' he said. ``It's essential to
get food across the lines.'' Wheeler said similar problems had been
overcome in neighboring Sudan.
   The Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development's
members include all NATO nations, Japan, and neutral countries such
as Austria, Finland and Switzerland.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891206-0007 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-06-89 0130EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Education Bjt   12-06 0613</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Education, Bjt,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>NEA, Urban Schools Seek Input Into National Education Goals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TAMARA HENRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As the nation's governors try to meet a
self-imposed deadline for developing national education goals,
leaders of education groups are moving to have some impact on the
finished product.
   Keith Geiger, president of the National Education Association,
proposed Tuesday that federally financed preschool programs for
poor youngsters integrate nutrition, prenatal care and health
screening.
   Early childhood education should be the primary focus of the
nation, Geiger said in an interview two days before Thursday's
meeting of the Education Task Force of the National Governors'
Association,
   And while preschool was included in its recommendations, a
second education group, the Council of the Great City Schools, said
the first priority should be to improve urban schools.
   The council said 30.4 percent of all poor children in the United
States are enrolled in only 50 urban school systems and the teacher
shortage in urban schools is 2{ times greater than the national
average.
   Geiger and council leaders _ President Larry Zenke and Director
Samuel Husk _ will present their ideas on national performance
goals for education at the task force meeting. The governors' group
has been working since the idea was approved in September at the
education summit between governors and President Bush.
   All 50 governors will convene in late February to put on the
finishing touches.
   In a Dec. 1 letter to the task force co-chairmen, Geiger
suggested the goals ``be both ambitious and specific: ambitious
enough to demonstrate that America's leaders understand the depth
of the problems schools face, specific enough to enable Americans
to hold government accountable.''
   Husk said the council's board of directors decided in early
November to strongly recommend that national goals contain specific
targets, outcomes and measures from each area; interim goals to be
met along the way; program and funding strategies at all levels and
plans for incentives and accountability.
   The Council of the Great City Schools is an organization of 45
urban school districts that concentrates on the concerns of city
schools.
   ``Urban educators have proven their ability to improve our
schools with limited resources, however, the time has come for
governments, businesses and our communities to provide the monetary
resources to support efforts to fulfill our commitment to quality
education for all children,'' Husk said.
   ``No child should be allowed to fall through the cracks,''
Geiger said. ``Every child should arrive at school physically,
intellectually, emotionally and socially able to learn.''
   Head Start has been touted as the most successful preschool
program financed by the federal government. About 1,300 Head Start
programs operate around the country, providing education and health
and nutrition services to about 20 percent of the impoverished
preschoolers who are eligible.
   Bush recently signed a law to increase spending for the Head
Start program this fiscal year by $147 million to $1.6 billion.
   But the NEA estimated about $6.3 billion is needed to serve all
eligible children ages 3 through 5.
   Both the NEA and council offered similar proposals they want
incorporated into the national performance goals. For example, both
called for safe, disciplined and drug-free schools. The council
also suggested there should be specific steps to be taken by
distillers, tobacco and firearms manufacturers to reduce youth
access to their products.
   The groups also called for a reduction in the dropout rate.
   The NEA proposed providing a fully qualified teacher for every
classroom, with salaries and benefits competitive with other fields
that require comparable skills, preparation and responsibility.
   The council suggested the goals target specific number or
percentages of teachers needed by 2000 to better reflect the racial
characteristics of students.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
