<FIRST>r w PM-Forum-Keating     12-06 0681</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Forum-Keating,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>S&amp;L Scandal Hits Donations to Voter Registration Groups</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two liberal voter registration groups that
took money from Charles J. Keating, a central figure in the savings
and loan scandal, have seen contributions dry up, officials of the
organizations say.
   Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., one of five senators under
investigation by the Senate ethics committee, played a role in
soliciting money from Keating for both groups, said Murray Flander,
his spokesman.
   One group, The Forum Institute, will suspend operations Jan. 1
because the links to Keating have prompted so much turmoil, William
Jeffress, the group's lawyer, said Tuesday.
   ``Given all the proceedings, given the involvement of Cranston,
and Keating, the board thinks it's best they suspend operations on
Jan. 1,'' Jeffress said.
   The other group, the Center for Participation in Democracy,
based in Los Angeles, is not ``actively soliciting resources,''
according to Cruz Reynoso, chairman of the board. The center's
future will be discussed at the next board meeting, Reynoso said.
   Reynoso, a former California Supreme Court justice and also a
member of the Forum Institute's board, said the bad publicity
surrounding Keating has ``made it very difficult to raise money.''
   Meanwhile, The New York Times reported today that federal law
enforcement authorities are investigating whether both groups
violated their tax-exempt status by instructing employees to
register more Democrats than Republicans.
   Cranston denied that in an interview with the Times, saying
voter registration drives were ``carefully done in accordance with
legal requirements.''
   Keating, a Phoenix millionaire who headed the American
Continental Corp. and its subsidiary, the Lincoln Savings and Loan
Association, contributed $325,000 over two years to the institute,
Jeffress said.
   Keating also gave $400,000 to the center, a group set up by
Cranston's son, Kim, with his father's help, to register new voters
in Western states.
   The Lincoln failure, the subject of numerous federal and state
investigations, is expected to cost taxpayers $2.5 billion, the
largest single thrift collapse.
   The Forum Institute was created in 1981 by Robert Stein, a
philanthropist and paid consultant to the Democratic Party until
October. Cranston and Stein frequently worked in tandem to raise
money for voter registration, an issue in which both men were
interested, Flander said.
   Flander said Cranston, who has a personal passion for
registering new voters, traveled around the country raising money
for his cause, including money from Keating.
   ``As far as Alan is concerned, this is a good cause,'' Flander
said, adding that Cranston first met Keating either in 1985 or 1986.
   Cranston sought money from Keating for the Forum Institute, the
Center for Participation in Democracy and USA Votes, a project of
Stein's company, New Dimension Resources Inc., Flander said.
   New Dimension paid for more than a dozen trips for Cranston to
travel around the country raising money for voter registration
drives in 1988, according to Cranston's financial disclosure forms.
   Stein refused in two telephone conversations to answer any
questions about his involvement with Cranston or Keating. He said
he wanted the controversy to subside before he talked about his
projects.
   The non-profit, tax-exempt Forum Institute is an organization
that ``gives grants to groups that encourage voter participation
and public education,'' according to records filed by with the
Internal Revenue Service.
   The Forum Institute raised $2.1 million in 1988, about $300,000
more than the previous year, the group's IRS records show. Among
the grants the institute handed out were a total of roughly
$305,000 in 1987 and 1988 to the Center for Participation in
Democracy.
   The Forum Institute also gave about $800,000 to the Organizing
Institute of Pacific Grove, Calif., a group that trained registrars
for the center.
   Other forum grants went for a variety of projects, ranging from
clear air to youth activities.
   Cranston, along with Sens. Dennis DeConcini, D-Ariz., Donald
Riegle, D-Mich., John Glenn, D-Ohio, and John McCain, R-Ariz., are
under investigation by the Senate ethics committee for accepting
campaign contributions from Keating while at the same time
intervening with federal regulators seeking to curb Lincoln's
lending practices. The senators have denied they did anything
illegal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
