<FIRST>r w PM-BarbaraBush     12-06 0384</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Barbara Bush,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mrs. Bush Plugs Salvation Army Bell Ringers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Barbara Bush, giving a plug for the Salvation
Army as several local shopping malls shut it out this holiday
season, said all shopping centers should welcome the annual bell
ringers.
   ``It just wouldn't be Christmas without that bell ringing,'' the
first lady said Tuesday as she dropped $10 into the Salvation Army
kettle inside the entrance to the upscale Mazza Gallerie mall.
   She decided to lend her support when she read a newspaper story
about a large number of local shopping malls that are excluding the
annual solicitation on the grounds that they bar all groups from
soliciting.
   ``I am a great fan of the Salvation Army, so I wanted to come
out and tell you what great work I think you do,'' Mrs. Bush told
Salvation Army volunteer Evelyn Barnes and Col. Jack Waters,
commander of the regional Salvation Army division.
   Waters said about a third of the shopping malls in the
Washington metropolitan area bar the annual holiday solicitation by
the bell ringers _ about double the rate of refusals in other parts
of the country.
   He said more than 125,000 people came to the local Salvation
Army for assistance last year, and this year already has seen more
requests.
   Mrs. Bush said all shopping malls should allow the Salvation
Army to set up its kettles during the Christmas season. Asked what
message she would give to those who refuse, she said she had none
but wanted only to praise the ones that do cooperate.
   ``I'm saying this mall is a great mall,'' she told reporters.
   ``I can't possibly think of Christmas without the Salvation
Army. I can't think of disasters without the Salvation Army,'' she
said referring to the organization's work for victims of natural
disasters. ``I can't think of the needy without the Salvation
Army.''
   The organization said that last year it raised $600,000 in its
kettles throughout the capital region, and about $100,00 of that
will be lost due to malls that are barring the kettles this year.
   After stopping at the Salvation Army kettle, Mrs. Bush did some
Christmas shopping in Neiman-Marcus department store.
   She bought toys and clothes for her grandchildren, said her
press secretary, Anna Perez.
</TEXT>
