<FILEID>AP-NR-12-06-89 0141EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Summit-Afghanistan     12-06 0663</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Summit-Afghanistan,660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Support for Najibullah Blocked Political Headway at Malta
Summit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union will continue supporting the
pro-Moscow leader of Afghanistan despite President Bush's
insistence at the Malta summit that President Najibullah's ouster
would hasten settlement of the war in that country, according to
U.S. officials.
   Bush described Najibullah as ``unacceptable'' to U.S.-backed
Moslem guerrillas, but Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev said
he was a national figure who was gaining popularity in the country,
the officials said Tuesday.
   Bush and Gorbachev were unable to break new ground at their
superpower summit to end the conflict between government and Moslem
forces in Afghanistan even though the last Soviet troops departed
in February.
   The dispute, which surfaced in an exchange between Bush and
Gorbachev on the Soviet cruise ship Maxim Gorky on Sunday, stood in
sharp contrast to the mostly positive results of the shipboard
meeting.
   A parallel disagreement over Central America was disclosed by
Bush and Gorbachev at a windup news conference Sunday.
   ``I can't say there are no differences between us,'' Bush told
reporters without making any direct reference to the war in
Afghanistan.
   He stressed their differences over Soviet arms supplies to
leftist rebels in El Salvador. Bush insists anti-aircraft missiles
and other weapons were being delivered by Cuba and Nicaragua, but
Gorbachev said he did not know how the arms got to the Farabundo
Marti National Liberation Front that is at war with the Salvadoran
government, U.S. officials told The Associated Press at the summit
meeting.
   Regional conflicts have proved to be the most resistant to
U.S.-Soviet reconciliation. By contrast, Bush and Gorbachev set as
targets arms control accords to limit nuclear, conventional and
chemical weapons.
   Sibghatullah Mojaddedi, the head of the U.S.-backed Afghan
resistance, met with Bush at the White House before the Malta
summit and said he wanted high-altitude anti-aircraft weapons to
use against Soviet bombers.
   He also expressed hope that Bush would tell Gorbachev to drop
Soviet support for the ``puppet regime and the communist
government'' in the Afghan capital of Kabul.
   ``Unfortunately, the free world thinks that the Russians have
withdrawn completely from Afghanistan,'' Mojaddedi said. ``Still,
the Russians are bombing our people, the mujahedeen, from their own
territory.''
   The Soviet Red Army rolled into Afghanistan in December 1979 to
back a Marxist government against Moslem guerrillas in a war that
had broken out a year earlier.
   The last of the Soviet troops were withdrawn in February, but
U.S. intelligence sources claim Moscow has increased U.S. aid to
Najibullah's government to $300 million to $400 million a month.
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III, at his meeting in Jackson
Hole, Wyo., in September with Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A.
Shevardnadze, complained about the arms shipments.
   The Soviets responded that the United States, by sending the
guerrillas a reported $500 million in arms annually via Pakistan,
was violating the Geneva accords signed last year that secured the
Red Army withdrawal from Afghanistan.
   U.S. humanitarian aid to the rebels and refugees in Afghanistan
and Pakistan amounts to $130 million a year. U.S. officials decline
to acknowledge on the record that any American arms are being sent
to the insurgents.
   At the summit, Bush told Gorbachev the Marxist president must
relinquish power before there could be a political settlement of
the war. The president told Gorbachev that Najibullah ``has to
go,'' said the U.S. officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   In another troubled area, the Middle East, the summit talks
produced no apparent discord.
   U.S. officials said Gorbachev appealed for a warmer American
stance toward Yasser Arafat, the chairman of the Palestine
Liberation Organization, and said he had ``gone out on a limb'' to
seek peace with Israel.
   Bush urged Gorbachev to understand Israel's concerns over the
PLO. Although the two leaders reached no agreement, Bush concluded
the Soviets were making a ``positive contribution'' to efforts to
resolve the Arab-Israeli dispute and the war in Lebanon.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
