<DOCNO> AP891206-0013 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-06-89 0200EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-SoftMoney     12-06 0696</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soft Money,710</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group Says Parties Abused Legal Loophole in Campaign Spending</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   National and state officials of both major
political parties deny a study group's charge that they pumped
money exempt from federal regulation into last year's presidential
campaign.
   In a report issued Tuesday, the Center for Responsive Politics
said Republican and Democratic parties in nine battleground states
received $28.5 million in so-called ``soft money'' donations not
covered by federal limits.
   Included in the total were contributions of more than $7.5
million from the Democratic National Committee and more than $2
million from the Republican National Committee.
   ``Anyone can see there was wholesale erosion of our campaign
finance laws during last year's presidential campaign,'' said Ellen
Miller, executive director of the center, a bipartisan group that
studies campaign finance.
   But the parties say the center is taking a one-sided view of
campaign spending.
   Leslie Goodman, spokeswoman for the Republican National
Committee, said the report ``really ignores the fact that ... we
operate on two levels, under federal laws and under state laws.''
   Ginny Terzano, a spokeswoman for the Democratic National
Committee, said: ``They sort of want to federalize the process,
which is not going to be realistic. When you put money into state
parties, that's a state issue and the state has to deal with that,
and they don't want federal involvement.''
   Texas Democratic Chairman Bob Slagle, contacted in Dallas, said,
``Those folks in Washington, D.C., are looking through the wrong
end of the telescope, and I don't know if a microscope would help.''
   Slagle said the Democratic party in Texas, which has not been
carried by a Democratic presidential candidate since 1976, is more
interested in protecting its state and local candidates from a
Republican sweep than in promoting a presidential candidate.
   Slagle's Republican counterpart, Fred Meyer, said his party uses
contributions that are exempt from federal limits for research,
recruitment and training of candidates and for administrative
functions.
   But Ms. Miller said the group found ``obvious patterns of
questionable soft money giving. No wonder voters have so little
confidence in our politicians when they are sabotaging our laws
like this.''
   Ms. Miller said the group concluded soft money was used toward
the presidential race because 11 individuals and eight businesses
each contributed more than $100,000 in the nine states and 42
percent of the money came from out-of-state sources including the
two national political parties. Also, much of the money was given
in key presidential states and about a third of the money was given
in the last four weeks.
   Although corporations and labor unions are barred from
contributing directly to campaigns for federal office, and
individual contributions are limited, they may make unlimited
contributions in most states for state and local campaigns, party
building and voter drives.
   This is called ``soft money'' and is not supposed to be used in
campaigns for federal office. The center wants such contributions
brought under federal control.
   The study covered 7,098 contributions by individuals,
corporations, unincorporated businesses, trade associations and the
Democratic and Republican national committees to state parties in
California, Colorado, Florida, Illinois, Missouri, Pennsylvania,
North Carolina, Texas and Washington.
   Individuals gave $9.2 million to Republican state parties and
$1.8 million to Democratic state parties. Corporations gave nearly
$6.5 million, almost of a third of it to the Republican parties.
   Soft money contributions to Republican parties from all sources
came to $16.7 million and to $11.8 million for Democratic parties,
according to the study. Republicans received more than Democrats in
all states except Texas and Pennsylvania.
   California had the largest infusion of soft money, $5.8 million
to the Republican party and $4.4 million to the Democrats.
   Other state totals were: Florida, $4.7 million; Illinois, $4.4
million; Texas, $3.2 million; Colorado, $2.1 million; Missouri,
$1.5 million; Washington just under $1 million; Pennsylvania
$883,000 and North Carolina $345,286.
   ``The bottom line is we do not go above the law or Federal
Election Commission regulations when we are putting money into
states for various races,'' Ms. Terzano said. ``We put our money
into the state, and we use it and the money is directed according
to FEC regulations.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
