<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Industrialist Armand Hammer is receiving an
honorary degree Thursday from the University of South Florida,
which is sending a delegation thousands of miles to hand him the
award.
   The group headed to Moscow on Tuesday to award Hammer a
doctorate of humane letters.
   ``This is the first time an American citizen has received a
degree from an American university in the Soviet Union,'' said Bob
Clodius, president of the National Association of University and
Land Grant Colleges in Washington.
   University of South Florida President Francis Borkowski said the
award recognizes Hammer's humanitarian, cultural and philanthropic
contributions.
   ``Armand Hammer has been perhaps the single most influential
American in the Soviet Union,'' Borkowski said. ``He has
contributed to glasnost and perestroika. That's why we are giving
him the degree in the Soviet Union.''
   Hammer, the 91-year-old chairman of Occidental Petroleum Corp.,
has been an unofficial business envoy to the Soviet Union since
1921. He has used his influence to allow U.S. doctors and rescue
teams to travel to the Soviet Union to aid in the Chernobyl nuclear
accident and the Armenian earthquake.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NORTH CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress' oldest member offered
the secret of a long life as he marked his birthday: a good diet
and exercise.
   ``If a person follows that, then they will have a chance to live
a happier life and help humanity,'' said Sen. Strom Thurmond, R-S.C.
   Thurmond, who turned 87 Tuesday, said he watches his diet and
exercises 50 minutes each morning, doing calisthenics, lifting
weights and riding a stationary cycle.
   He said he also tries to keep an optimistic outlook on life.
   He came to this city just northwest of Charleston with U.S.
Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner to announce a $32 million
emergency grant for repairs to highways damaged by Hurricane Hugo.
