<FIRST>r a PM-Nielsens     12-06 0285</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nielsens,0296</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cosby Helps NBC Win Sweeps</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bill Cosby and the rest of NBC's Thursday
night lineup helped the network win the ratings sweeps for November.
   November is one of four months in which the size of a network's
audience is used to determine an affiliate's advertising rates.
   NBC placed six shows, its Thursday programs plus ``The Golden
Girls'' from Saturday, in last week's top 10, according to the A.C.
Nielsen Co.
   NBC's average prime-time rating for the week was 15.4. ABC's was
13.2 and CBS' 11.6. Each rating point represents the percentage of
the nation's 92.1 million households tuned to a show.
   NBC leads for the season with 15.0 to ABC's 13.4 and CBS' 12.3.
   NBC's ``The Cosby Show'' was first, followed by NBC's ``Cheers''
and a Thursday night preview of its comedy series ``Ann Jillian,''
which is slated for Sunday nights. ABC's ``Roseanne'' was fourth.
Others in top 10: NBC's ``Dear John,'' NBC's ``The Golden Girls,''
CBS' ``Murder, She Wrote,'' NBC's ``L.A. Law,'' CBS' ``60 Minutes''
and ABC's ``The Wonder Years,'' tied.
   The NBC Monday night movie, ``Little White Lies,'' starring Miss
Jillian and Tim Matheson, was 17th for the week. ABC's ``Hallmark
Hall of Fame'' presentation of ``The Shell Seekers,'' starring
Angela Lansbury, tied for 22nd with NBC's ``Night Court.''
   The lowest-rated network show was ABC's ``Living Dolls.''
   Among the evening news shows, ABC's ``World News Tonight'' was
first for the ninth straight week, including two ties with CBS. Its
lead over the second place news show is the largest since the ABC
news show began in 1952. ABC was first last week with 11.5, CBS had
10.3 and NBC 10.2.
</TEXT>
