<FILEID>AP-NR-12-06-89 0229EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-Non-stopDiplomacy 1stLd-Writethru aibly.It'sinmyblood
12-06 0717</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Non-stop Diplomacy, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0418,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: Bush Has His Own Style</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf, `Bush has ...,' to fix spelling of word `traveled';
SUBS 6th graf, `So far ...,' to insert dropped word; SUBS final graf to
end with period sted comma. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   From engaging Mikhail Gorbachev in the stormy
Med to taking Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak to the ballpark or
picking up the phone for a chat with the pope, President Bush's
brand of diplomacy is personal and non-stop.
   Bush has traveled to 14 countries as president. And, according
to White House statisticians, he has held 105 separate one-on-one
meetings with presidents, prime ministers and kings.
   Just home from his meeting with the Soviet leader at Malta and
with NATO allies in Brussels, Bush is getting ready to embark on
yet another foreign trip _ a meeting next week with French
President Francois Mitterrand on the Caribbean island of St. Martin.
   True to Bush's whirlwind style, he'll squeeze that trip into one
day, leaving Washington early in the morning and returning late at
night.
   Those leaders Bush can't get around to meeting this year he'll
just have to phone _ or meet next year.
   So far on the 1990 calendar there's a drug summit in Latin
America in February, an expected trip to Australia and one to
Africa being considered. A 23-nation summit in Vienna to sign an
arms treaty has been proposed by Bush, and at some point there's
bound to be a Moscow summit.
   Bush conducts diplomacy like he plays golf: he rushes from one
event to the next. When he isn't personally entertaining them, he's
reaching out to touch world leaders by phone.
   In the days before his waterlogged summit with Gorbachev, Bush
met with British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher and Canadian
Prime Minister Brian Mulroney and called the other 13 NATO allies
by phone, according to press spokesman Bob Hall. He also called the
leaders of Japan, Korea and Israel to discuss the summit.
   To discuss the issue of U.S. hostages being held in Lebanon,
Bush made a transatlantic phone call to Pope John Paul II last
summer. Bush met the pope during a visit to Italy in May.
   Bush works quickly to try to establish a personal rapport with
world leaders. He took Mrs. Thatcher for a ride in a golf cart,
escorted Mitterrand through the woods and over the rocks at his
oceanfront home in Maine and took a somewhat bewildered Mubarak by
presidential helicopter to a Baltimore Orioles baseball game.
   He has invited Mrs. Thatcher, Prince Charles and Mexican
President Carlos Salinas de Gortari to the presidential retreat at
Camp David, Md.
   He persuaded Danish Prime Minister Poul Schlueter and his wife
to visit him in Kennebunkport, Maine, on their honeymoon visit to
the United States.
   And he showed off the Smithsonian's Air and Space Museum to
Jordan's King Hussein.
   ``He has used the personal touch much more than most past
presidents,'' said deputy press secretary Alixe Glen.
   Even though the summit with Gorbachev was curtailed and
logistics disrupted by a fierce storm, the two met long enough for
Secretary of State James A. Baker III to declare: ``There's a
potential for real chemistry here between these two leaders.''
   Of his meeting with Gorbachev, Bush said: ``The emotional part
of it is hard to describe for me because I'm not the most
articulate emotionalist. But I just can't have asked for a better
ambiance, a better feel from the meetings, even though the
differences are acute in some areas.''
   Gennadi Gerasimov, the Soviet spokesman, paid Bush an indirect
compliment, suggesting he was far better prepared than former
President Reagan. Gerasimov joked that Bush had left his ``thick
reference book somewhere else, I guess on another ship.''
   Stephen Hess, a senior fellow at the Brookings Institution who
specializes in the presidency, said Bush's ability to establish
personal relationships with world leaders ``turns out to be
extremely useful.''
   ``The agenda of the world is involving the American president
very deeply and probably will for the rest of Bush's term,'' Hess
said.
   Anyway, Hess added, even though Bush claimed he wanted to be the
education president, ``what he really wanted to be all along was
the `international-affairs president.'''
</TEXT>
