<FIRST>r w PM-Supercollider     12-06 0301</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Supercollider,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>$1 Billion Construction Contract Narrowed To Three Groups of Firms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three teams of firms remain in the running for
a $1 billion contract to manage engineering and construction of the
$5.9 billion supercollider, say industry and congressional
officials.
   Officials said a final decision on the contractor would be made
next year. The award would be the largest single contract involved
in building the super collider, a 53-mile underground ring where
scientists would test theories about the building blocks of the
universe by smashing together atomic particles.
   The offices of Rep. Joe Barton, R-Texas, and Sen. Phil Gramm,
R-Texas, announced the three finalist teams late Tuesday and said
they had been chosen from a field of 14 competitors.
   ``The fact that these invitations have already been made
indicates that the SSC program is right on schedule,'' said Barton,
whose district includes the superconducting supercollider site.
   Officials representing some of the firms involved confirmed
their selection late Tuesday, and said their companies had learned
of the decision from the Energy Department. Confirmation from DOE
was not immediately available.
   The finalist teams were identified as: Fluor-Daniel, the
construction arm of Fluor Corp. of Irvine, Calif., and ICF Kaiser
Engineers Inc. of Oakland, Calif.; Parsons, Brinckerhoff, Quade and
Douglas Inc. of New York City, MK Ferguson Co. of Cleveland, a
subsidiary of Morrison Knudsen Corp. of Boise, Idaho, and CRSS of
Houston; and a joint venture of Daniel, Mann, Johnson and
Mendenhall of Los Angeles and Bechtel National Inc. of San
Francisco.
   Jess Hawley, a spokesman for Morrison Knudsen, said University
Research Associates, a management and operations entity working on
behalf of the Energy Department, would employ the chosen contractor.
   Congress this year appropriated $225 million to begin initial
construction of the SSC.
</TEXT>
