<FILEID>AP-NR-12-06-89 0230EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-BloodDisorder     12-06 0343</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Blood Disorder,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cases Linked to Suspect L-trytophan Still Rising</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of reported cases of a sometimes
fatal blood disorder linked to the nutritional supplement
L-tryptophan is up to 720, federal health officials say.
   While the federal Centers for Disease Control in Atlanta
continues to investigate cases reported by state health
departments, the Food and Drug Administration is testing samples of
the substance and making sure it remains off store shelves and
stopped in U.S. ports.
   As of Tuesday, 720 cases from 48 states, the District of
Columbia and Puerto Rico had been reported to the CDC. One death
has been reported and others are being investigated.
   Only Alaska and South Dakota have reported no cases.
   The CDC has established a link between the nutritional
supplement and eosinophilia-myalgia syndrome, which is marked by
severe muscle and joint pain, swelling of the arms and legs, skin
rash and sometimes fever.
   L-tryptophan, an amino acid, is found naturally in many foods.
Some people take supplements of L-tryptophan to treat
sleeplessness, depression, premenstrual syndrome, stress and other
problems.
   The Food and Drug Administration said it has been detaining all
L-tryptophan shipments, including bulk supplies of the supplement,
at U.S. ports as a follow-up to its Nov. 17 request for a
nationwide recall of L-tryptophan tablets, capsules and caplets.
   The investigation has not established whether L-tryptophan
itself or some contaminant introduced during manufacture or
distribution is causing the syndrome. The FDA said it has collected
several hundred products and has begun to analyze them for possible
evidence of chemical or microbial contamination.
   FDA investigators recently visited L-tryptophan manufacturing
plants in Japan, a leading supplier of the supplement to U.S.
manufacturers. Japanese officials have been cooperating with
American investigators, the FDA said.
   The CDC's initial analysis of data on 85 cases shows most of
those who developed the syndrome were women taking between 1 and 2
grams per day of L-tryptophan, the FDA said. The daily intake of
the supplement ranged from 150 milligrams to 18 grams.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891206-0024 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-06-89 0242EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Salvador     12-06 0650</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salvador,0672</SECOND>
<HEAD>Connecticut Woman Charged with Terrorism, Vows to Prove Innocence</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American woman in whose
backyard police say they found a large rebel ammunition cache
declared before being driven off to jail, charged with terrorism,
that she would prove her innocence in court.
   Jennifer Casolo, 28, was charged Tuesday under the country's
terrorism law with possession of weapons of war, she and her
lawyer, Salvador Ibarra, said as the emerged from the new downtown
judicial complex.
   Ms. Casolo had made a sworn deposition to military Judge
Guillermo Romero in a closed, four-hour session. If convicted, she
faces 20 years in prison.
   ``I'm being taken to the women's prison. It's a place I've taken
many delegations, a place where I've interviewed many prisoners. I
guess now I'll be on the other side,'' she told reporters as she
left the judge's chambers.
   Romero avoided reporters and there was no indication when the
case would go to trial.
   A native of Thomaston, Conn. and a former Seattle resident, Ms.
Casolo has represented Christian Educational Seminars in El
Salvador for nearly five years. The San Antonio-based organization
arranges fact-finding tours for Americans, including congressmen.
   She denies collaborating with leftist guerrillas, who have been
fighting a 10-year-old war against a succession of U.S.-backed
governments and last month turned the capital into a combat zone
with their largest offensive ever.
   Ms. Casolo says she knows nothing of the more than 20,000 rounds
of assault rifle ammunition, explosives and detonator caps police
say they found buried behind her house on Nov. 25. She rented the
house three months ago, she says, and has been traveling much of
the time since then.
   Members of the military and the rightist administration of
President Alfredo Cristiani have accused clergy and church workers
of sympathizing with and even aiding the rebels.
   During last month's offensive, six Jesuit priests were murdered
during a nighttime curfew by men said by a witness to have been in
uniform. Elements connected to the military are widely believed to
be responsible.
   Former U.S. Attorney General Ramsey Clark, who came to help in
Ms. Casolo's defense, says deportation is probably the easiest way
out for her. But Ms. Casolo says she wants to face the charges.
   ``The accusations against me are false,'' she told reporters
Tuesday. ``This is a first step and the rest will be decided by the
long judicial process here.
   ``Let us prove our innocence publicly. We're not going to go
behind the scenes,'' she said.
   Wearing a white blouse and beige skirt, she appeared tired but
in good spirits when she talked with reporters before and after
meeting with the judge. Ms. Casolo had spent 10 days under arrest
at National Police headquarters, where she said she spent evenings
singing hymns and reading the Bible with other prisoners and talked
about scripture with her wardens.
   ``I have faith in all the people who have written me letters, in
their prayers,'' Ms. Casolo said before being driven off to prison.
   ``I can't say I have faith in the system to find me innocent.
But I believe my innocence will shine through.''
   Clark, who left the country on Tuesday, said he would return to
help with the trial. He said he believed her chances for acquittal
were good.
   Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., said charging Ms. Casolo was a
mistake and vowed to continue his efforts to win her release.
   ``I believe the prosecutors in the Casolo case have made a
terrible mistake _ a regrettable mistake,'' Dodd said in a
statement late Tuesday. ``But this is only one step in a judicial
process, and I believe the truth will out. As long as it takes, I
will continue to work for Jennifer Casolo's release.''
   Dodd is chairman of the Western Hemisphere subcommittee of the
Senate Foreign Relations Committee.
</TEXT>
