<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     12-06 0210</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0216</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stocks Hit Another High, Dollar Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The key index on the Tokyo Stock Exchange ended at
yet another high Wednesday, while the dollar rose marginally
against the Japanese yen.
   The dollar ended at 143.75 yen, up 0.07 yen from Tuesday's close
of 143.68 yen. The currency opened at 143.72 yen and ranged between
143.65 yen and 143.76 yen.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 160.12 points, or 0.43
percent, ending the day at 37,654.29, a new high. It had gained
190.30 points for a previous record closing Tuesday.
   The index fell quickly in early trading and lost nearly 200
points as major investment trust companies sold issues for
profit-taking, said Tomoyuki Morimoto, a dealer with New Japan
Securiies Co.
   ``Major securities companies didn't want further rises in the
index,'' he said.
   But other investors reversed the Nikkei's downswing as they
started buying issues as part of arbitrage deals between the spot
and futures markets, Morimoto said.
   In currency dealings, the dollar-yen rate moved narrowly in the
absence of fresh market-affecting news, foreign exchange traders
said.
   The majority of market players were awaiting the release of the
U.S. unemployment figures for November, due out Friday in
Washington, said a Bank of Tokyo trader, speaking anonymously.
</TEXT>
