<DOCNO> AP891206-0026 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-06-89 0310EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-EastGermany-MovingAhead     12-06 0802</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-East Germany-Moving Ahead,0825</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Keeps Moving Despite Fall of Communists</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-East Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEST BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite a country in chaos, East German
leaders have managed to make more diplomatic breakthroughs with
West Germany in the last two days than in the last two decades.
   A planned summit, the establishment of a hard currency fund for
tourists, and agreements on trade, transportation and the
environment all have defied the turbulence at the top.
   The accomplishments testify both to the stubborn resolve of
those Communists still in power to keep the country working, and to
West Germany's decision to act quickly while East Germany is
overwhelmed by events.
   Two East German Communist leaderships have fallen in less than
two months, so one might expect the wheels of government and
diplomacy to have slowed.
   But in East Germany's case, the tumult has actually accelerated
an orderly effort to close gaps and work together on projects of
mutual interest.
   Under the terms of an agreement reached between the two Germanys
on Tuesday, West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl will visit East
Germany on Dec. 19.
   Kohl will meet Communist Premier Hans Modrow in Dresden, rather
than in the capital of East Berlin, to avoid de facto recognition
of the sovereignty of East Germany.
   The West German leader's refusal to travel to East Berlin was a
condition that Erich Honecker, who led East Germany for 18 years
until his mid-October ouster, found unacceptable.
   Kohl's chief of staff, Rudolf Seiters, met with Modrow on
Tuesday in talks that made progress in a broad array of issues
concerning both states.
   Seiters and Modrow issued a joint account of their talks,
describing them as productive and businesslike and ticking off an
impressive list of accomplishments.
   The thorniest issue settled was providing East German tourists
with convertible currency for trips to the West.
   West Germany has traditionally offered 100-mark gifts, about
$54, of ``welcome money'' to East German arrivals once each year
because East Germany only would convert the equivalent of $8 a day
for travelers.
   Seiters announced that the West German budget for welcome money
next year, $405 million, was being handed over to East Berlin to
contribute to a hard-currency pool for tourists.
   Modrow explained that under the agreement, East German adults
will be entitled to receive up to $108 per year in hard currency,
and parents can receive another 100 West German marks for each
child under 14.
   East Germany, in turn, has agreed to drop a mandatory exchange
rule that required West Germans visiting the Communist state to
convert to East German marks (at an unfavorable rate) at least
$13.50 for each day they were in the country.
   West Germans also will no longer need visas to enter East
Germany after Jan. 1, when the new currency exchange system also
takes effect.
   The governments further agreed to study transit improvements
between their states and Bonn promised to help East Germany upgrade
its outmoded and overwhelmed telephone network.
   Agreements were reached on joint efforts to improve
environmental protection in East Germany _ one of Europe's most
polluted nations. Expanded rail links between the countries also is
to be explored.
   Modrow also said East Germany would boost its trade with West
Germany by $16.2 million next year.
   Kohl told reporters in Brussels, Belgium, on Monday that he
planned to follow through on his intent to visit East Germany
before Christmas despite the resignation Sunday of Communist Party
chief Egon Krenz, the full party Politburo and the 163-member
Central Committee.
   ``I will meet with Premier Modrow and whoever is elected party
leader at the special congress,'' he said at a press conference
following the gathering of NATO leaders.
   A special party congress is set for Dec. 15-17 at which a new
leadership is to be named. In the interim, a 25-person panel is
running party affairs, and Modrow as government leader is empowered
to handle diplomatic affairs.
   The Communists face widespread opposition both from grass-roots
movements that want a share of power and from several small parties
that used to vote with the Communists as a bloc but now are
exercising relative independence.
   Kohl has unveiled a 10-point plan for improving ties with East
Germany that aims at eventual reunification, and he drew some
support for the endeavor from President Bush at the NATO meeting.
   West Germany may be intensifying its contacts with East Germany
in the absence of a clear party leadership in belief that the
government structure, which includes 11 non-Communist ministers, is
more capable than the Communist hierarchy of entering into
agreements that the public will support.
   Modrow is a member of the Communist Party, but has long
advocated democratic changes and enjoys more support among East
Germans than any other party figure.
</TEXT>
