<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtonInBrief     12-06 0415</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington In Brief,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Health Officials: Climate Changes Threaten to Spread Disease</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While changes in the Earth's climate threaten
to encourage the spread of diseases like rabies, the changes may
also damage the human body's ability to fight them, health
officials are warning.
   A conference on ``Global Atmospheric Change and Public Health''
was told Tuesday that potential problems stem both from the
increase in ultraviolet radiation, as the protective ozone layer in
the stratosphere is damaged, and from climate warming, which many
scientists believe is occurring in a so-called Greenhouse effect.
   Ultraviolet radiation, already known to cause skin cancer, also
has a major effect in reducing the response of the human immune
system, said Dr. Raymond Daynes of the University of Utah.
   At the same time the immune system damage is being threatened,
warming of the climate could lead to the spread of diseases
currently limited by the climate, said Dr. Robert E. Shope of the
Yale University School of Medicine.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Measure Signed by Bush Protects Nevada Wilderness</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More land in Nevada would be protected from
development, timber harvesting and mineral exploration under
legislation that has been signed into law by President Bush.
   The measure, signed Tuesday, creates 733,400 acres of protected
wilderness in Nevada and opens another 2.4 million acres to
multiple use under the management of the Agriculture Department.
   The legislation puts a total of 2 percent of the state's land
under wilderness protection, preventing development and such uses
as timber harvesting, mineral exploration or intrusion by campers
in vehicles.
   However, the legislation protects existing grazing rights for
ranchers on the wilderness land, and low-level military flights
over four of the new wilderness areas, a White House spokesman said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Safety Panel: School Bleachers at Risk of Collapsing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Certain indoor school bleachers are at risk of
collapsing because of poor maintenance and improper operation,
school officials are being told.
   The Consumer Product Safety Commission warned school
administrators nationwide Tuesday that bleachers should be
routinely inspected and maintained at least twice a year.
   In addition, only trained personnel, not students, should be
used to operate the bleachers, the commission said in a statement.
   The commission said recent collapses of school gymnasium
bleachers prompted the warning, which involves manual, telescoping
bleachers made from 1966 to 1979 by Michigan-based Interkal and
sold under the trade names ``Brunswick,'' ``Vecta'' and
``Interkal.''
   The commission said 16 collapses since 1978 have produced back,
arm, leg and ankle injuries.
</TEXT>
