<FILEID>AP-NR-12-06-89 0542EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-RocketSmuggling     12-06 0534</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rocket Smuggling,0549</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Year Sentence for Weapons Tech Plot to Egypt, Iraq</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HOWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A rocketry scientist convicted of
trying to ship sophisticated U.S. missile technology to Egypt has
been sentenced to 46 months in prison.
   Abdelkader Helmy, 41, also was fined $358,690 and ordered to
forfeit about a half-million dollars, all part of what prosecutors
said were $1 million in payments dispensed to Helmy by Egyptian
intelligence operatives via Swiss banks.
   ``This is not a cloak-and-dagger espionage case,'' U.S. District
Judge Raul Ramirez said at Tuesday's sentencing. ``This was a case,
to put it bluntly, of greed. ... He thought he would make a lot of
money and thought he would make a favor befall the sovereign nation
of Egypt.''
   Ramirez also credited Helmy for the 18 months he spent in jail
awaiting trial.
   The Egyptian-born U.S. citizen pleaded guilty in June to one
count of illegally exporting about 420 pounds of a carbon-based
material used in the construction of nose cones, rocket nozzles and
other weapons-related machinery. Eleven counts, including money
laundering and conspiracy, were dropped in return for the plea and
his promise to cooperate with prosecutors.
   ``I would like you to consider me as a human being,'' Helmy told
the judge, ``and human beings make mistakes. The United States is
my country and I never intended to hurt it.''
   The material, called carbon-carbon, had been developed in the
United States. It has a low visibility to radar and is heat
resistant. It is used extensively in Stealth aircraft, missiles and
rockets.
   Carbon-carbon is on the federal government's restricted list,
and its export requires a special license.
   An associate of Helmy's, 47-year-old James Huffman of Lexington,
Ohio, was sentenced to 41 months in prison and fined $7,500.
   Ramirez said Huffman, who worked as a representative of the
Hollister-based Teledyne Corp., reportedly used his expertise as a
20-year veteran marketing specialist to help Helmy in the exporting
scheme.
   Ramirez characterized the export scheme as a ``large, complex,
intricate conspiracy'' developed by the Egyptians with financial
backing from Iraq to get sensitive weapons-grade rocket materials.
   He said that had the conspiracy succeeded and the technology and
materials reached the Middle East, Egypt and Iraq had planned to
split the fruits of the scheme.
   An attorney for Helmy, Marcus S. Topel, had claimed his client
was recruited by Egypt's then-defense minister, Lt. Gen.
Abdel-Halim Abu-Ghazala.
   U.S. prosectors said two Egyptian nationals also have been
charged in the case. They are Ahmed Hussam Al-Din Khairat, an
Egyptian army officer who allegedly supervised the export scheme
from a headquarters in Austria, and Fuad Algamal, an Egyptian
colonel. Both are fugitives.
   The federal grand jury indictment also linked two other
Egyptians to the plot _ assistant military attache Abd Elrahin
Elgohary and Egyptian Col. Mohamed Abdalla Mohamed. Both men, who
had been based in Washington, D.C., claimed diplomatic immunity and
were not charged.
   Helmy was a top propulsion scientist at Aerojet General Corp.
near Sacramento.
   Helmy and Huffman were arrested in 1988 after U.S. Customs
agents seized a load of carbon material and other goods from an
aircraft waiting to take off for Egypt from Baltimore-Washington
Airport.
</TEXT>
