<FIRST>r a PM-ActressSlain     12-06 0461</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Actress Slain,0473</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teen Ordered Held for Murder Trial in Slaying of Actress</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A teen-ager charged in the slaying of actress
Rebecca Schaeffer was ordered to stand trial for murder after
testimony from witnesses that included chilling, graphic accounts
of her killing.
   Municipal Judge David Horwitz ordered the trial after a daylong
preliminary hearing Tuesday into the death of the young woman who
starred in the old television series ``My Sister Sam.''
   Robert John Bardo, 19, of Tucson, Ariz., appeared groggy as he
came and went from the courtroom. Public defender Stephen Galindo
said he believed his client was on medication.
   The judge upheld a special circumstances charge _ lying in wait
_ that would allow prosecutors to seek the death penalty if Bardo
is convicted of first-degree murder. Bardo will be arraigned Dec.
11.
   Prosecutors allege Bardo was the gunman who walked up to Miss
Schaeffer's apartment house on July 18 and opened fire when she
came to the door. The 21-year-old actress was struck once in the
chest and died.
   Among the witnesses was Miss Schaeffer's next-door neighbor,
actress Lynne Marta, who revealed that the intercoms in the
apartment house were broken when Miss Schaeffer responded to the
door buzzer by opening the security door.
   She said the young woman could not have talked to the person at
the door to find out who was there.
   ``I heard her pass my door,'' Ms. Marta said. ``In what seemed
like a second there was a blast that sounded like a cannon. The
door shook. The wall shook and the cat went up in the air. I fell
down on the floor.''
   Asked what happened next, the witness, in tears, said: ``I heard
Rebecca's first scream. I got to the phone and dialed 911. ...
Rebecca was moaning and wailing by the time I got to the door.
   ``I opened the little window hatch in the door and there was a
smell I will never forget as long as I live. It was the smell of
gunfire and it was quiet except for this little moaning.''
   Ms. Marta said she stepped into the hallway and called Miss
Schaeffer's name, but no response came. She said she stayed there
until paramedics arrived.
   Other witnesses told how Bardo spent three hours before the
attack clutching Miss Schaeffer's picture to his chest and stalking
her neighborhood in search of her apartment.
   Bardo had gotten her address from a private detective agency, a
witness said.
   In quick succession, five witnesses identified Bardo as the
young man who stalked Miss Schaeffer and was seen running away from
her house moments after gunshots and a scream shattered the calm of
the quiet neighborhood about 10:30 a.m.
</TEXT>
