<HEAD>Temperatures Plunge, Snow Predicted</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Winter tightened its grip today as temperatures continued to
plunge in the North, and snow was predicted in the northern
mountains of Colorado, Wyoming and Utah and in eastern parts of the
Lake Superior snowbelt.
   New England expected colder, windier weather today. Lows of
between 10 and 15 are expected tonight in northeastern New York and
northern Vermont.
   Snow advisories were posted today in the mountains of northern
and central Colorado, northern Wyoming _ where up to eight inches
of snow are possible _ and northern Utah, where up to a half-foot
of snow is predicted by this morning.
   The Great Lakes area expects partly cloudy, blustery weather and
lower temperatures today.
   A high-pressure front is expected to spawn sunshine and colder
temperatures in Wisconsin, the National Weather Service says.
   A cold front Tuesday night spread snow across the central
Rockies. Showers along the front extended from northern California
and southern Oregon to South Dakota and Nebraska. Snow fell in the
higher elevations, while light rain and drizzle prevailed in lower
altitudes.
   Clouds covered much of the Northeast Tuesday, with snow showers
in the Great Lakes region. Freezing rain pelted parts of the upper
Ohio Valley, and an advisory for freezing drizzle was issued for
most of western Pennsylvania.
   In the South Tuesday, sunny and dry weather prevailed. While
high temperatures hovered in the 20s in the Northeast states, the
mercury rose into the upper 60s and 70s across the south-central
states.
   Record temperatures were reported at Lincoln and Grand Island,
Neb., where 50-year-old records were bested with readings of 69.
   Temperatures warmed into the 70s in southern Arizona and crept
into the 70s and 80s Tuesday afternoon in Southern California.
   Tuesday's high temperature for the nation was 90 degrees at
Woodland Hills, Calif.
