<FIRST>r a PM-Parkinson'sDisease     12-06 0265</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Parkinson's Disease,0274</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cell Defect Found in Parkinson's Disease Victims</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scientists say they have detected a blood-cell
defect in people with Parkinson's disease, a link that could help
identify victims before symptoms appear.
   Such timely identification could open the door for earlier
treatment of the disease that afflicts 400,000 Americans.
   The findings, published Tuesday in the Annals of Neurology, are
the product of federally funded research by Dr. William Davis
Parker Jr., Dr. Sally J. Boyson and Janice K. Parks of the
University of Colorado Health Sciences Center.
   Parkinson's is a neurological condition characterized by
gradually worsening tremors, muscle rigidity and weakness _
symptoms blamed on the disappearance of key brain cells.
   The scientists reported finding what appears to be an enzyme
deficiency inside blood cells of Parkinson's patients, suggesting
the disease affects more than just the brain cells it kills.
   In normal cells, the enzyme is used to neutralize so-called free
radicals, the byproducts of oxidation. Free radicals have been
shown, in previous research, to be capable of killing the same
brain cells destroyed in Parkinson's disease.
   Scientists cautioned that the new conclusions offer no immediate
help for people with Parkinson's.
   But the rewards of nailing down the origins of Parkinson's would
be enormous.
   ``It sounds really exciting to me,'' said Dr. Stanley Fahn of
New York's Columbia-Presbyterian Medical Center.
   ``We've got to be cautious,'' added Fahn, who last month
co-authored the results of nationwide trials on the promising
anti-Parkinson's drug deprenyl.
   ``It certainly is a new direction. No one has ever found a
defect like this before,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
