<FIRST>r a PM-RobinHUD     12-06 0425</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Robin HUD,0436</SECOND>
<HEAD>Maryland Escrow Agent Dubbed `Robin HUD' Pleads Innocent in Housing
Scandal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATTY REINERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman dubbed ``Robin HUD'' for her claims she
purchased cars and housing for the needy with stolen federal
housing money has pleaded innocent to embezzlement charges.
   Former escrow agent Marilyn Harrell pleaded innocent in U.S.
District Court Tuesday to charges she embezzled millions of dollars
from the federal Department of Housing and Urban Development.
   Her attorney, public defender Anthony Gallagher, said the
innocent pleas mean ``a total denial of all allegations in the
indictment.'' He refused to comment further.
   Harrell, 46, did not make any statement during or after her
arraignment. She remains free on her own recognizance pending a
trial next month.
   She is accused of embezzling $5.6 million from HUD, making false
statements to the federal government and making false statements in
connection with a loan application. She is one of a dozen escrow
agents suspected of keeping more than $10 million they were
supposed to transfer to HUD.
   U.S. Attorney General Dick Thornburgh has said the case
represents perhaps the largest single theft of government funds
ever charged against an individual.
   Harrell testified before Congress last summer during six months
of hearings into allegations of fraud, mismanagement and political
favoritism at HUD during the Reagan administration.
   She admitted stealing millions and buying 20 homes and nearly 40
automobiles for the needy before anyone noticed, earning her the
``Robin HUD'' nickname.
   Several top officials in HUD's Washington field office, to which
Harrell reported, were fired because of her case and other
allegations of mismanagement.
   Two weeks after Harrell testified, HUD seized her house in
Temple Hills, a Maryland suburb of Washington. The agency also
confiscated several other properties Harrell said she purchased
with HUD money to help charities and homeless families. Harrell is
living with her mother in Fort Washington, also a Washington suburb.
   As an escrow agent, Harrell collected money from the sales of
property that had been foreclosed on by the Federal Housing
Administration. The properties originally had been purchased with
HUD-guaranteed loans.
   Agents such as Harrell earn small commissions for handling the
foreclosures and turn over sales proceeds to the government.
Harrell told Congress that in 1985 she used sales proceeds to cover
a $37,000 shortfall in her business.
   She said that when several months passed without an inquiry from
HUD, she concluded the department was so poorly run that it was
unable to track the millions of dollars in payments due from escrow
agents.
</TEXT>
