<FIRST>r i PM-Ambassador-Bomb 1stLd-Writethru   12-06 0340</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ambassador-Bomb, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0481,0349</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bomb Rocks Residence Of Madrid Envoy</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES thruout with authorities saying damage minimal, attack
likely by grenades. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two missiles were fired at the
home of the Spanish ambassador, causing some damage but no
injuries, police said. It was the fourth attack against Spanish
targets in six weeks.
   Two windows of the 18th-century building at The Hague's stately
Embassy Row were shattered by what appeared to be rocket-propelled
grenades, according to police spokesman Nico Laterveer.
   But the grenades apparently failed to explode, said Laterveer,
adding that the damage to the residence's interior was ``minimal.''
He did not know whether Ambassador Manuel Maria Sassot Canadas was
present at the time of the attack.
   The residence is about 25 yards from the Spanish Embassy.
   There was no immediate claim of responsibility.
   Earlier reports indicated heavier damage. An explosion heard at
the time of the attack was believed to have been caused by the
firing mechanism of the grenades, Laterveer said.
   Dutch army explosives experts were carefully searching a gray
Mazda van parked in front of the building, from which the missiles
could have been fired, Laterveer said.
   ``Immediately after the explosion, a small fire broke out in
that car,'' Laterveer told reporters here.
   Minutes after the incident, police cordoned off the area near
the American and British embassies.
   On Oct. 24, a bomb destroyed the car of the Spanish consul in
Rotterdam. Three days later, two blasts damaged the trade mission
and the labor bureau here. One person was slightly injured in the
latter incident.
   Last month, the Basque terrorist organization ETA claimed
responsibility for those attacks. A statement in a Spanish
newspaper said they were in retaliation for the Netherlands' 1980
refusal to grant entry to three ETA members, who were subsequently
jailed in Spain.
   But today, Laterveer said that that claim had been ``assigned a
low priority'' by Dutch police, noting that the ETA seldom ventured
outside Spain.
   ``We have no idea who the perpetrators are,'' Laterveer said.
</TEXT>
