<FILEID>AP-NR-12-06-89 0710EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Deaths     12-06 1211</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Deaths,1277</SECOND>
<HEAD>No PMs separates moved.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Harland Bartholomew</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harland Bartholomew considered the father of
comprehensive city planning in the United States, died Saturday at
the age of 100.
   Bartholomew helped plan the Washington Metro subway system and
historic Williamsburg, Va. He was appointed to federal planning
committees by three presidents.
   In 1914, Bartholomew became the nation's first full-time city
planner when he went to work for Newark, N.J.
   Two years later he came to St. Louis for a similar job and later
opened up a consulting firm, Harland Bartholomew &amp; Associates,
which now has headquarters in Memphis, Tenn.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Lord Elwyn-Jones</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lord Elwyn-Jones, a prosecutor at the Nuremberg
war crimes trials and Britain's chief legal officer under the last
Labor Party government, died Monday of cancer. He was 80.
   Elwyn-Jones became a lawyer in 1935. He came to national
prominence as a member of the British War Crimes Executive at
Nuremberg in 1945 where he was a prosecutor at the Nazi trials.
   Elwyn-Jones was the senior counsel for the tribunal of inquiry
into the 1966 collapse of a coal slag heap in the Welsh village of
Aberfan that killed 116 children and 28 adults.
   He was also a government adviser during the 1966 crisis brought
on by Rhodesia's unilateral declaration of independence.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Sir John Pritchard</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sir John Pritchard, 68, a leading
international conductor, died Tuesday of lung cancer.
   Pritchard was among Britain's highest-paid, busiest and most
distinguished conductors. He was knighted in 1983 by Queen
Elizabeth II for his contribution to British musical life.
   Admired for his energy and versatility, he studied Russian when
rehearsing Tchaikovsky's ``Eugene Onegin'' for Glyndebourne, the
English opera house.
   Pritchard was chief conductor of the BBC Symphony from 1982
until October and of the Cologne Opera in West Germany from 1978
until this summer.
   He had been musical director of the San Francisco Opera since
1986 and held the same post at Glyndebourne and the Theater de la
Monnaie in Brussels.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Angelo Ruggiero</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Angelo Ruggiero, a friend since childhood of
reputed Gambino crime-family boss John Gotti, died Monday of cancer
at age 49.
   Ruggiero, known as ``Quack Quack'' because of his duck-like
walk, had been a friend of John Gotti's from their early
street-gang days in Queens.
   Ruggiero spent about two years in jail for a manslaughter
conviction stemming from a May 1973 killing at a Staten Island bar.
   In the early 1980s, as a Gambino capo or captain, Ruggiero had
been the unwitting source of much of the government's best
information about the mob. Bugs in his home and wiretaps on his
telephones gave investigators new insight into the Gambino family's
drug dealings, loan sharking and gambling operations.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>George Nardi</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dr. George Nardi, a surgeon and an expert in
pancreatic diseases, died Tuesday of cancer. He was 66.
   Nardi worked at Massachusetts General beginning in 1952 and was
a professor at Harvard Medical School.
   He described the urinary loss of amino acids crucial to the
regrowth of proteins in severe burn victims, and pointed out the
relationship between inflammation of the pancreas and overactivity
of the parathyroid gland.
   In 1974, Nardi was named a fellow of the Royal Society of
Medicine in England. Last year, he received the Order of Cavaliere
of the Republic of Italy.
   A contributor to medical literature with about 200 articles to
his credit, Nardi was also co-editor of all four editions of
``Surgery: Essentials of Clinical Practice,'' a basic surgery text.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Arnold Ordman</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arnold Ordman, who served two terms as general
counsel to the National Labor Relations board and later as an
administrative law judge and arbitrator, died Tuesday of heart
failure. He was 77.
   Ordman was the only person to be NLRB general counsel for two
successive terms. He served in the Kennedy and Johnson
administrations.
   He had joined the agency in 1946 as a member of its legal staff.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Nathan Huggins</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nathan I. Huggins, a Harvard University professor
who was a front-runner in establishing Afro-American Studies as a
discipline, died Tuesday of cancer at age 62.
   Huggins was the W.E.B. Dubois Professor of History and of
Afro-American Studies, and director of the Dubois Institute for
Afro-American Research at Harvard since 1980.
   Huggins wrote several books, including ``Harlem Renaissance,''
nominated for the National Book Award in 1981; ``Slave and Citizen:
The Life of Frederick Douglass;'' and ``Black Odyssey: The
Afro-American's Ordeal in Slavery.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>May Swenson</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BETHANY BEACH, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   May Swenson, whose work is included
in many anthologies and who was a regular contributor to The New
Yorker, died Monday. She was 76.
   Swenson, whose cause of death was unknown, published her first
book of poems, ``Another Animal,'' in 1954. She published nine
volumes of poems. She also wrote for Atlantic Monthly and Saturday
Review magazines.
   Her latest work, ``In Other Words,'' was published three years
ago. She was awarded a $375,000 MacArthur Foundation Fellowship in
1987.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Robert Vidalin</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   French actor Robert Vidalin, known to millions as
the voice of Charles De Gaulle's resistance fighters during World
War II, died Sunday at age 86. No cause of death was given.
   Vidalin, an actor and member of the Comedie Francaise national
theater, gave up his acting in 1939 to join the underground after
the Nazis invaded France.
   Later he joined De Gaulle in London and became one of the
best-known radio announcers on the popular BBC news program, ``Les
Francais Parlent aux Francais'' _ ``The French Speak to the
French.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Edoardo Amaldi</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Edoardo Amaldi, considered one of the fathers of
Italian physics and a pioneer in nuclear research, died Tuesday at
age 81.
   The cause of death was not announced.
   Amaldi was a physics professor at the University of Rome for 41
years.
   He was a driving force in the creation of the Geneva-based
European Council for Nuclear Research, now called the European
Laboratory for Particle Physics. He was secretary general of the
organization from 1952-54.
   From 1958-59, Amaldi was president of the scientific and
technical committee of the European Atomic Energy Community.
</TEXT>
