<DOCNO> AP891206-0045 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-06-89 0716EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Taiwan     12-06 0446</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Taiwan,0461</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Promises More Democratic Reforms After Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNIE HUANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Lee Teng-hui today promised more
democratic reforms after the ruling Nationalist Party's setback in
Taiwan's first multiparty elections, acknowledging a decline in his
party's credibility.
   The Nationalists suffered their worst losses in 40 years in
power in Saturday's balloting. The party lost several key local
county executive posts and garnered 58 percent of the total vote,
down from 70 percent in 1986.
   ``It was a setback for our party as far as our original goal was
concerned,'' said Lee, who also chairs the Nationalist Party.
   ``The decision made by the voters was not a coincidence,'' Lee
told the party's decision-making Central Standing Committee, ``It
indicates the various reform measures undertaken by the government
in recent years had failed to meet the public's expectations.''
   Opposition supporters, meanwhile, ended four days of massive
demonstrations against alleged vote fraud after a recounting of
ballots began at the heavily guarded Tainan District Court in
southern Taiwan.
   During the election and raucous campaign, the opposition party
accused the Nationalists of widespread vote buying and ballot box
stuffing.
   Lee said the government had failed to solve such problems as
worsening crime, social morale and ``the authorities' declining
credibility.''
   ``We must learn our lesson from the setback. We must not
hesitate any more,'' Lee said. ``We are more sure of our way and
will take faster and more positive steps'' toward various political
and other reforms.
   Lee has pushed for the retirement of hundreds of elderly members
who dominate the Legislature. They were elected on the Chinese
mainland before the Nationalists fled Taiwan in 1949 and were
frozen in office to support the Nationalists' claim to be the sole
legitimate ruler of all of China.
   Few have accepted handsome government pensions and filed for
retirement.
   Earlier in Tainan, about 2,000 noisy protesters occupied a
section of a freeway and stopped traffic for an hour as recounts
were stalled by the slow transportation of ballot boxes from eight
villages, police and witnesses said.
   Huang Chin-cheng, chief prosecutor of the Tainan District Court,
said the count would take three days because the process was going
to be monitored by campaign officers of both the opposition and
Nationalist candidates for the county executive post.
   The Nationalist candidate was initially declared the winner.
   On Tuesday, about 10,000 opposition supporters, screaming for a
recount, clashed with police who cordoned off a square next to
county government offices. Several were injured.
   Opposition Democratic Progressive Party Chairman Huang
Hsin-chieh went to Tainan and asked for a recount. The government
initially refused, fearing all other losing candidates would follow
suit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
