<FIRST>r a PM-RapeSentence     12-06 0449</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rape Sentence,0462</SECOND>
<HEAD>Attorney: Florida Woman Vindicated When Rapist Sentenced in Georgia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURAN NEERGAARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The attorney for a Florida woman who lost a rape
case because the jury said she ``asked for it'' says the woman is
vindicated now that her accused attacker has been sentenced to life
in prison in Georgia.
   But attorney Alexander Siegel said Steven Lamar Lord, who
pleaded guilty Tuesday to raping and kidnapping a Decatur woman,
was trying a foolish ploy when he told the judge his plea would
prevent the victim from reliving her trauma in court.
   ``That's like Attila the Hun saying he was sorry for trampling a
few thousand extra people,'' Siegel said in a telephone interview
from his Fort Lauderdale home.
   Superior Court Judge Hilton Fuller of DeKalb County sentenced
Lord, 26, to life in prison for the rape and a concurrent 20-year
sentence for kidnapping the woman at a 24-hour banking machine in
Decatur. In Georgia, those sentenced to life are eligible to be
considered for parole after seven years.
   Court records show that Lord had reportedly told the victim:
``It's your fault. You're wearing a skirt.''
   Lord's attorney, public defender Bill Hankins, told Fuller that
Lord ``regrets very much what has happened to her.''
   Lord was acquitted of rape in October in Fort Lauderdale, Fla.
At that time, the jury foreman, Roy Diamond, said jurors believed
the woman accusing him, who was wearing a white lace miniskirt
without underwear when she was attacked, had ``asked for it.''
   Although Diamond later said he meant she asked for sex and not
rape, the acquittal sparked a national controversy.
   Other jurors then said they were swayed by the woman's calm
demeanor in court compared with the emotional testimony of the
24-year-old Decatur woman who testified in the Florida trial that
Lord raped her at knifepoint.
   ``When the Georgia woman testified, my heart sank,'' said juror
Dean Medeiros. ``But when the other one testified, she didn't
appear to be shaken up. Basically, we didn't believe her story.''
   Betty Grant, president of the Georgia chapter of the National
Organization for Women, said Tuesday night she was ``delighted''
that Lord was finally sentenced.
   ``There's no remorseful awareness here. I hope his sentence
sticks because we know rape offenders do repeat the crime,'' she
said.
   Siegel contended that Lord's guilty plea came because he heard
the Decatur woman's testimony before his hearing in Georgia.
   ``He knew he didn't stand a chance,'' the attorney said.
   Siegel said he had not been able to reach his client with the
news of Lord's plea because her phone was out of order. He said,
though, that she would be ``very relieved.''
</TEXT>
