<FIRST>u a PM-PTLIndictments 2ndLd-Writethru a0508 12-06 0550</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-PTL Indictments, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0508,0561</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Former Jim Bakker Associates Indicted on Perjury Charges</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to reorganize and clarify. Picks up 9th graf,
`Dortch, who....'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL NOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The evangelist who introduced Jim Bakker
to Jessica Hahn was charged along with a former PTL minister with
lying to a special grand jury.
   The federal grand jury on Tuesday charged evangelist John Wesley
Fletcher with one count of perjury for his testimony about how
Bakker was introduced to Ms. Hahn.
   According to the indictment, on Sept. 24, 1987, he denied taking
Miss Hahn to a Clearwater Beach, Fla., hotel to have sex with
Bakker. But, the indictment said, on Sept. 20, 1988, he testified
that he agreed when Bakker asked him, ``Get me a woman.''
   Sam Johnson, a former minister at PTL's Heritage Village Church,
was charged with 12 counts of perjury for his testimony before the
special grand jury. Johnson's testimony focused on a $10,000 loan
he made to former PTL Executive Vice President Richard Dortch that
later went to Ms. Hahn.
   The payment was made Nov. 1, 1984, before the former church
secretary received $265,000 in PTL funds in exchange for her
silence about her 1980 sexual encounter with Bakker in a Florida
motel room.
   ``We don't expect any further PTL-related indictments from this
grand jury,'' said Assistant U.S. Attorney Jerry Miller, who
prosecuted Bakker. He wouldn't elaborate.
   The indictments were issued about three hours after Dortch,
Bakker's former second in command at PTL, testified to the federal
grand jury.
   Dortch, who pleaded guilty in August to fraud and conspiracy for
his role in the PTL affair, had no comment as he left the
courthouse.
   Late Tuesday, Dortch's attorneys filed a motion asking U.S.
District Judge Robert Potter to reduce Dortch's sentence because of
his cooperation with prosecutors.
   Dortch was sentenced to eight years in prison and fined
$200,000. His plea agreement enables the former Assemblies of God
official to remain free until federal authorities no longer require
his cooperation.
   According to prosecutors, Dortch had one of his assistants
deliver $10,000 in an envelope to former PTL board member Aimee
Cortese, who handed over the money to Miss Hahn during a meeting at
a church in New York City in November 1984.
   During his two appearances before the special PTL grand jury,
Johnson said Dortch had asked him for a $10,000 loan, but Johnson
told the panel he could not remember where he got the money,
according to the indictment.
   Johnson could not be reached for comment Tuesday. His secretary,
Pam Jewett, said he was taping a Christmas TV special in the
mountains.
   Fletcher's number wasn't listed in the Durham telephone
directory, so attempts to reach him were unsuccessful.
   Bakker is serving a 45-year term in a federal prison in
Minnesota after being convicted Oct. 5 of fraud and conspiracy.
Bakker is appealing the conviction, but a panel of the 4th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals refused to free Bakker on bond while the
appeal was prepared.
   Bakker was accused of bilking followers who sent him $158
million for partnerships in the ministry entitling them to annual
lodging guarantees. Prosecutors said Bakker diverted $3.7 million
in PTL money to buy expensive homes, cars, jewelry and vacations.
</TEXT>
