<FIRST>r a PM-Philippines-MarcosJr     12-06 0346</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philippines-Marcos Jr,0354</SECOND>
<HEAD>Marcos Jr. Says U.S. Aid to Aquino Could Mean War</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Philippines, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. military support for forces loyal to
Philippines President Corazon Aquino could bring on a civil war,
said the son of that country's former leader.
   ``If the American government brings in firepower to support the
Aquino government, America will be at war with us,'' Ferdinand
Marcos Jr., told columnist Cindy Adams in an interview published
today in the New York Post.
   The United States provided air cover last Friday for the
Philippine military against mutinous soldiers.
   ``The logical extreme if pushed to the limits is America lands
forces and involves itself in our battle. Let there be no mistake.
America will find itself at war with the Philippines,'' he said in
New York.
   ``This is our fight,'' Marcos said. ``The man in the street has
intense resentment towards U.S. airplanes overflying him. It could
push what is now still considered an uprising into full-scale civil
war.
   ``If America comes in to mediate, OK. But, if America tries to
intervene between one group and another _ and, remember, the rebels
are loyal to the United States _ our country will kill the
Americans and each other and violence will escalate,'' he said.
   Mutinereers last week launched the strongest attempt yet to
topple Mrs. Aquino's administration, which has been widely
criticized as indecisive and inept. Mrs. Aquino took over after
Ferdinand Marcos was ousted in 1986.
   Although the Bush administration has defended Aquino as the
Philippines' democratically elected leader, the son of the late
Marcos insisted on ABC's ``Good Morning America'' today that the
anti-Aquino faction could be described as pro-American. ``It's been
quite ironic that the United States has used its military might
against them,'' he said.
   ``It was a dangerous precedent to begin with, which I think was
a serious mistake in judgment on America's part,'' Marcos said.
   ``It will be evident in years to come. The wave of
anti-Americanism that has derived from that move may be felt for
years to come,'' he said.
</TEXT>
