<FIRST>r a PM-LiverTransplant     12-06 0468</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Liver Transplant,0483</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mother: `Feeling Good' After Donating Liver Part to Baby Girl</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLIFF EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was more painful than she expected, but the
woman who gave up part of her liver for her baby girl in the
nation's first living donor liver transplant says she would do it
again.
   ``I feel real good,'' Teresa Smith said Tuesday during her first
public appearance since she and her daughter, Alyssa, underwent
surgery Nov. 27.
   ``I don't feel like a `first,''' she said. ``I feel like any
parent who is looking out for the best interests of her child.''
   ``There was a little more pain than I expected,'' added Mrs.
Smith, 29. ``But this was our best option for Alyssa.''
   Alyssa suffered from biliary atresia, an often-fatal congenital
liver disorder.
   Alyssa remained in serious but stable condition at University of
Chicago Hospitals. ``She still has a lot of hurdles to cross,'' but
the piece of liver transplanted from her mother has shown no signs
of rejection, said Dr. Peter Whitington, director of pediatric
services at the hospital.
   Mrs. Smith told reporters she'd seen her 21-month-old daughter
several times since the weekend, when she had recovered enough to
visit Alyssa for the first time since the operation.
   Much of their time together has been spent sharing books and
getting Alyssa to play with her toys, said the fourth-grade teacher
from Schertz, Texas, near San Antonio.
   Mrs. Smith will be discharged before the weekend, said
Whitington.
   There is a 50 percent chance Alyssa will be released in time for
Christmas, although she will have to remain near the hospital for a
time, he said.
   ``The liver is still not functioning perfectly,'' Whitington
said. ``Right now, she's a little yellow. But all other functions
have pretty much fallen into place.''
   Another pioneering transplant patient, a woman who was given a
heart, liver and kidney, has been upgraded to serious condition and
taken off a ventilator three days after her historic surgery.
   Doctors said Cindy Martin, 26, of Archbald, Pa., was responding
well following the 21{-hour operation that began Saturday at
Presbyterian-University Hospital in Pittsburgh.
   The next living donor transplant candidate probably will arrive
in Chicago in January, Whitington said, and as many as eight of the
operations could be performed through February.
   The second child scheduled for the procedure probably will not
have the operation. Sixteen-month-old Sarina Jones of Millington,
Tenn., near Memphis, who arrived at the hospital Friday, is too ill
to be a good candidate for the operation, Whitington said.
   ``She is every bit as malnourished as an Ethiopian refugee,'' he
said. ``She's a worse physical candidate than she was'' when
doctors first examined her last Friday.
   If she recovers, doctors probably will use a cadaver liver if
one becomes available, Whitington said.
</TEXT>
