<FIRST>u a PM-RiotTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0482 12-06 0552</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Riot Trial, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0482,0563</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Gets Officer's Manslaughter Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with three grafs to UPDATE with deliberations beginning.
Picks up 3rd graf, `Colombian-born Officer...'.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MH2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The fate of a Hispanic policeman accused of
manslaughter in the shooting of a black motorcyclist was in the
hands of the jury today, almost 11 months after the killing sparked
three days of race riots.
   The multi-ethnic jury _ two blacks, one Hispanic and three
non-Hispanic whites _ began deliberations today after almost seven
weeks of jury selection and testimony closely followed by the
city's residents.
   Deliberations began at 9:50 a.m. after the jury received
last-minute instructions from Dade County Circuit Judge Joseph
Farina.
   Colombian-born Officer William Lozano, 31, faces two counts of
manslaughter in the deaths of the motorcyclist, Clement Lloyd, 23,
and his passenger, Allan Blanchard, 24.
   Police and community relations officials have geared up for
possible renewed rioting if Lozano is acquitted. However, they said
the presence of two blacks on the jury _ along with extensive live
broadcasts of testimony and arguments _ may have defused tensions
in neighborhoods that have exploded four times this decade after
police violence against blacks.
   During final arguments, prosecutors said Lozano had no excuse
for shooting Lloyd as the bike sped up an Overtown street while
fleeing a squad car.
   ``It's real hard to believe a police officer could do something
so stupid,'' Chief Assistant State Attorney John Hogan said. ``That
this man, on January 16th, intentionally pulled the trigger and
wiped out two human beings.''
   Defense attorney Roy Black countered by accusing the state of
trying to make Lozano a scapegoat to ease racial tensions.
   ``He's sort of like a pawn caught up in forces beyond his
control,'' Black said.
   Black said defense testimony showed Lozano was about to be run
down by the motorcycle when he fired.
   ``This man discharged his gun for one reason only _ because he
thought he was going to be run over, because he thought he was
going to be killed.''
   If convicted, Lozano could be sentenced to a maximum 30 years on
each manslaughter count.
   Jurors heard from almost 60 witnesses after testimony began Nov.
15. The trial opened Oct. 23, but it took more than three weeks to
seat a jury.
   The shooting occurred on Martin Luther King's birthday as Miami
began a week of celebration leading up to the Super Bowl.
   Within an hour after the shooting, a mob gathered at the scene
in the predominantly black Overtown neighborhood and began pelting
officers with rocks and bottles.
   By the time the violence ended three days later, one looter had
been shot to death, 11 people were wounded by gunfire and 13
buildings were burned down in the Overtown and Liberty City
neighborhoods.
   It was the fourth such riot in Miami in the 1980s. The first
occurred in 1980 after an all-white jury in Tampa acquitted a group
of Metro-Dade policemen accused of beating black insurance
executive Arthur McDuffie to death.
   In 1982, a riot broke out when Miami officer Luis Alvarez
entered an Overtown video arcade and shot and killed Nevell
Johnson, who was black. Two years later, violence broke out again
when Alvarez was acquitted by an all-white jury.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
