<FIRST>r a PM-HighSchoolGift     12-06 0353</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-High School Gift,0362</SECOND>
<HEAD>Businessmen To Give $6 Million to High School for College Scholarships</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINONA, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five businessmen say they are establishing
a $6 million college scholarship fund for graduates of the
200-student Winona Cotter High School, a private Roman Catholic
school.
   ``We wanted to motivate students to try to use more of the
potential we think they all have,'' said one of the businessmen,
Robert Kierlin, a Cotter graduate and president of Winona's
Fastenal Corp.
   ``One of my pet theories as I've gotten older is that no one
performs to 100 percent of their ability,'' Kierlin said. ``It
would be really great if some of the Cotter students got a better
chance to go to a little bit better college than they might
otherwise aspire to.''
   The businessmen also are giving $2 million for construction of
an indoor athletic facility for the school in southeastern
Minnesota. The gifts come one year after they gave more than $5
million for teachers' salaries and other expenses.
   The latest gift means that all current and future Cotter
students could receive money for part or all of their college
expenses.
   The scholarship fund was in part a reaction to a teacher's
observation that many of her students worked after school, said
Kierlin, who with four Fastenal founders arranged for the gift from
the proceeds of a recent stock sale.
   ``We believe in the work ethic, too, but not necessarily during
the school year,'' Kierlin said.
   Fastenal sells threaded fasteners and other industrial and
construction supplies in the Midwest.
   This year's 39 seniors will share about $50,000, but subsequent
larger classes will share about $125,000.
   Educators and philanthropy watchers said the gifts would be
remarkable for U.S. colleges, and is unheard of for a high school.
   ``Eight million dollars is extraordinary, astounding,'' said
Charles Pinto, high school consultant for the Archdiocese of
Chicago, which runs the largest private school system in the
country and the nation's seventh largest school system of any kind.
   ``But what's important is that the money is not being given just
to the school, but to students,'' Pinto said.
</TEXT>
