<FILEID>AP-PX-12-06-89 1048EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-VDTBill     12-06 0216</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-VDT Bill,0220</SECOND>
<HEAD>City Council Votes Protection for VDT Operators</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City Council has approved legislation to protect
the health and safety of more than 12,000 city workers who use
video display terminals.
   The bill is the toughest VDT law in the nation and the first law
of its kind in a major city, according to the New York City Video
Display Terminal Coalition of labor unions and occupational safety
and health groups.
   The bill, approved Tuesday, mandates that VDT operators at city
agencies be given a 15-minute break whenever they are required to
work at a terminal for more than two consecutive hours.
   Under the law, VDT workers with certain medical conditions _
including pregnancy _ would be allowed to obtain transfers. Some
studies have suggested prolonged VDT exposure increases risk of
miscarriage.
   The bill also mandates that lighting and furniture be adjusted
to prevent eye strain and repetitive strain injury to hands and
other parts of the body affected by prolonged VDT use.
   ``We hope New York City's legislation will set a national
precedent for protecting these workers not only from repetitive
strain injuries, but from eye strain, headaches, blurred vision,
and for pregnant women, from hazards that may lead to
miscarriage,'' said Diane Stein, coordinator of the VDT Coalition.
</TEXT>
