<FIRST>r a PM-MissionaryReturns     12-06 0255</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Missionary Returns,0261</SECOND>
<HEAD>Missionary Held In El Salvador Returns Home</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Salvador</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Roman Catholic lay missionary accused of
involvement with Salvadoran guerrillas is back in the United States
after spending the weekend in custody.
   Scott Wright, 38, of San Antonio, was released Monday by
authorities in San Salvador on the condition that he leave the
country. He arrived in San Antonio on Tuesday.
   Wright said he was taken into custody with a Spanish priest and
three Salvadoran lay workers last Friday when uniformed police came
to the parish hall where they were working.
   ``They searched for two hours. They found nothing but some
papers and a few religious relics,'' he said. ``No one ever told us
why it was being searched or why we were being detained.''
   He and the priest were separated from the Salvadorans.
   ``Even handcuffed, blindfolded and made to stand like that for
hours, I believe we received preferential treatment,'' he said with
a wry smile.
   Wright, who spent most of the last three years in El Salvador,
said the Salvadoran government is increasing reprisals against
church workers because they witnessed the effects of recent bombing
in the capital city on civilians and because officials insist they
are aiding the enemy.
   ``The government basically has accused these parishes of
collaborating with the guerrillas. I think that's a false
accusation,'' Wright said. ``The church has opened its doors to
refugees, it has treated the wounded, it's continued to feed the
people, the children, that is its mission.''
</TEXT>
