<FIRST>r w PM-Justice-Pierce     12-06 0375</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Justice-Pierce,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thornburgh Overruled Staff in Ordering Pierce Probe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh overruled a
staff recommendation when he ordered a preliminary inquiry into
allegations of wrongdoing against former Housing Secretary Samuel
R. Pierce Jr., a spokesman said today.
   The Justice Department's public integrity section recommended
against considering whether an independent counsel should
investigate the allegations of political favoritism and perjury
against Pierce, said spokesman David Runkel.
   ``That decision was reversed by the attorney general after his
further personal review,'' said Runkel, confirming an account in
The Washington Post.
   Runkel dismissed suggestions that Thornburgh ordered the
additional inquiry to avoid charges from Congress that he had
scuttled an investigation of a man with whom he sat in President
Reagan's Cabinet.
   ``He was concerned that the issues reviewed needed further
investigation,'' the spokesman said. ``He wasn't convinced by the
public integrity section's point of view.''
   Thornburgh's decision, made last Saturday, triggered a 60-day
preliminary inquiry to determine if he should seek court
appointment of an independent counsel, formerly known as a special
prosecutor, to conduct a full criminal investigation.
   Democratic congressmen alleged last month that Pierce awarded
Department of Housing and Urban Development grants on the basis of
political favoritism and lied under oath during congressional
hearings last spring.
   They cited testimony Pierce gave to the House Government
Operations employment and housing subcommittee that he did not have
``hands-on'' involvement in the award of HUD grants to politically
connected developers.
   The 19 lawmakers, all members of the House Judiciary Committee,
triggered procedures under the independent counsel law by
forwarding their allegations to Thornburgh.
   In response to the lawmakers' request, Thornburgh disclosed
Monday that he had ordered the preliminary inquiry.
   Pierce has denied any wrongdoing but twice refused to give
additional testimony to the House subcommittee, citing his
constitutional right against self-incrimination.
   Pierce's lawyers have contended that the lawmakers had not
provided the Justice Department with any ``specific and credible''
evidence that their client committed a crime.
   The public integrity section, applying that standard as outlined
in the independent counsel law, apparently agreed with that view.
   Earlier this week, Pierce's lawyers expressed confidence that
the preliminary inquiry would not result in the appointment of an
independent counsel.
</TEXT>
