<FIRST>r a PM-MinnesotaAthletics     12-06 0255</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Minnesota Athletics,0261</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administrator Gets 18 Months in Prison for University Theft</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former University of Minnesota
administrator was sentenced today to 18 months in state prison for
stealing $186,000 from the university's Office of Minority and
Special Student Affairs.
   Luther Darville was convicted last month of three felony counts
of theft by swindle.
   He said all the missing money was doled out to needy athletes
and other students on instructions from his superiors, who
testified they had no knowledge of the payments.
   Hennepin County District Judge Patrick Fitzgerald sentenced him
to 18 months in prison on one count, 15 months on the second count
and one year and one day on the third count, to run concurrently,
said the judge's law clerk, John Conley. Darville will get credit
for time already served, nearly four months, Conley said.
   In addition, Fitzgerald sentenced Darville to six months at the
county workhouse for contempt of court, to be served after the
prison sentence.
   ``The position of trust that Mr. Darville had at the University
of Minnesota was violated,'' he said. ``The offenses were committed
with a high degree of planning over an extended and lengthy period
of time.''
   Prosecutor Pete Connors had sought a minimum sentence of 54
months, saying Darville had deceived the very students he was
supposed to be counseling and had made false allegations against
his colleagues.
   Defense attorney James Lawton argued for leniency, noting that
Darville has no previous criminal record and will be deported to
his native Bahamas.
</TEXT>
