<FIRST>u w PM-DrugVerdict     12-06 0546</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drug Verdict,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alleged D.C. Cocaine Kingpin Convicted</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal jury today convicted a 24-year-old
man of operating a $2 million-a-week cocaine-distribution network
in the nation's capital, a verdict that mandates life imprisonment.
   Rayful Edmond III was found guilty of all seven counts against
him after more than four days of deliberations that capped a
12-week trial. Ten co-defendants were convicted of related charges.
   During the 20 minutes that the verdicts were read, the 11
defendants stood impassively before U.S. District Judge Charles
Richey, occasionally glancing down at the floor or shaking their
heads slowly as the guilty verdicts mounted. The jury returned an
innocent verdict on only one of the 23 counts in the indictment.
   Edmond, of Washington, stood stoically throughout the
proceeding, his hands folded in front of him and a serious
expression on his face.
   The charges against him included conspiracy to violate narcotics
laws, employing persons under 18 to possess and distribute cocaine,
traveling across state lines to sell drugs and using a telephone to
set up illegal drug deals.
   Convictions on those counts satisfy a definition of a continuing
criminal enterprise, a crime which carries a mandatory life
sentence.
   Edmond's co-defendants, who include an aunt, a sister, a brother
and several close friends, were found guilty of assisting him.
Prosecutors said at the trial that the drug ring accounted for up
to 30 percent of the District of Columbia's cocaine market.
   Richey did not immediately set a sentencing date.
   The verdicts ended a complex, courtroom drama in which
prosecutors depicted Edmond as the head of a vast and deadly drug
network that took in $2 million a week.
   The trial was unusual from the outset, when the judge ruled that
the names of jurors would be kept secret even from himself and
lawyers to protect them from possible reprisals.
   The home of one witness' mother was firebombed during the trial,
an informant was shot after being accidentally exposed by the
prosecution. The trial was conducted in a courtroom with a
bullet-proof plastic shield 1{ inches thick, and further protection
was provided by a metal detector set up for the trial outside the
courtroom in which the case was argued.
   At its peak last summer, prosecutors said, Edmond and his
cohorts moved up to 440 pounds of cocaine per week into Washington.
The city has experienced more than 400 homicides this year, most of
them attributed by police to drug activities.
   Edmond was described by prosecutors as a flashy entrepreneur who
lavished expensive gifts _ including luxury automobiles _ on
friends, family members and loyal lieutenants in his organization.
   Edmond's lawyers said the government had not proved its case
against him.
   In closing arguments last Thursday, defense attorney James
Robinson challenged the credibility of prosecution witnesses,
saying evidence against some of the co-defendants did not point to
Edmond as the leader of a drug enterprise.
   ``There was a lot of testimony from a lot of people who got
caught dealing drugs,'' Robinson said. ``The problem was ... making
a connection between that activity and Rayful Edmond III.''
   Edmond is charged with additional crimes _ including three
counts of first-degree murder and conspiracy counts _ and is
expected to face two more trials.
</TEXT>
