<FIRST>r a PM-FusionTenure     12-06 0253</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fusion Tenure,0258</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cold Fusion Defense May Affect Tenure</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some faculty members at Massachusetts Institute of
Technology are upset that a physicist who publicly supported
researchers' claims of achieving cold fusion may win tenure, a
newspaper reported today.
   At MIT, where millions of dollars have been spent on research
into conventional fusion as a potential energy source, many
scientists challenged a report of cold fusion energy, but Peter L.
Hagelstein defended it.
   Cold fusion was envisioned as a source of limitless energy last
spring when Utah researcher B. Stanley Pons and Martin Fleischmann
of Great Britain said their experiment fused hydrogen atoms without
the high temperatures believed necessary for such a reaction.
   At a news conference April 14, Hagelstein theorized that a
previously unknown nuclear phenomenon was involved in cold fusion,
and MIT filed for a patent on potential applications of his ideas.
   But other MIT physicists scoffed at the idea, and chemists said
Hagelstein did not understand that a chemical, rather than
physical, reaction might have occurred. Other laboratories were
unable to reproduce the Utah results.
   The Boston Globe said it was told by unidentified sources at MIT
that tenure for Hagelstein, 34, has support in his department of
electrical engineering but that the way he got MIT into the cold
fusion controversy has become an issue.
   Critics said it was not so much his theory as the way it was
presented _ through the news media rather than submitting it to
review by scientists, the Globe said.
</TEXT>
