<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-Airport     12-06 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Airport,0286</SECOND>
<HEAD>Radicals Arrested in Airport Protests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Riot police arrested four leftist radicals
Wednesday for throwing firebombs to protest the expansion of
Tokyo's international airport, officials said.
   Protesters hurled firebombs and bricks at riot police from four
50-foot towers erected at the site by the demonstrators. Police
eventually overpowered them with water cannons.
   Riot police lowered steel cages over the towers to prevent them
from hurling more projectiles.
   About 200 radical opponents of the airport rallied nearby to
protest the police action but did not clash with them, the official
said.
   Seven radicals have been arrested since Monday, when about 5,000
riot police began to remove one of 10 huts built illegally on the
site of the planned second runway of the New Tokyo International
Airport, 40 miles northeast of Tokyo, the Chiba Prefectural Police
said.
   Eight farmers own land on or near the planned expansion site,
refusing to yield it for construction of additional runways to ease
congestion.
   The airport handled 17.24 million passengers in 1988, 4 million
more than it was originally designed for, the airport authority
said.
   Forty-eight airlines from 37 countries use the $2.5 billion
airport, which opened in 1978 with just one runway.
   By next year, the government plans to build two more runways,
one of 8,250 feet and another of 10,560 feet.
   Anti-government radicals have been supporting the farmers in
their battle to keep their land from being taken from them for the
new runways.
   On Monday, Transport Minister Takami Eto became the first
government official to apologize for the state's failure to consult
adequately with farmers when the airport first was planned 23 years
ago.
</TEXT>
