<DOCNO> AP891206-0077 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-PX-12-06-89 1226EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Israel-Toll     12-06 0476</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Toll,0495</SECOND>
<HEAD>Uprising Takes Heavy Toll on Life, Economy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel-Analysis, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Palestinian uprising against Israeli
occupation of the West Bank and Gaza Strip has taken a heavy toll
in the past two years.
   Casualties on both sides have mounted as the ``intefadeh'' _
Arabic for uprising _ drags on without political solution.
   More than 820 people have died, according to a tally kept by The
Associated Press.
   They include 626 Palestinians killed by Israeli soldiers or
civilians and 154 Palestinians slain by fellow Arabs, most on
suspicion of collaboration with Israel. Forty-three Israelis have
died in the violence, including 11 soldiers.
   The Palestinian fatalities include 132 children, says the Israel
Information Center for Human Rights in the Occupied Territories.
   Thousands have been wounded.
   According to the U.N. Relief and Works Agency, which oversees
relief programs for Palestinian refugees, nearly 40,000
Palestinians have suffered injuries ranging from tear gas
inhalation to beatings and gunshot wounds. The army puts the
Palestinian injury total at 8,926.
   The army spokesman's office says 2,438 Israelis have been
wounded, including 1,635 soldiers.
   Sixty Palestinians have been deported and about 40,000 jailed in
the past two years. There are 9,142 in prison now, including 1,562
``administrative detainees'' held without charge or trial.
   Both sides have lost economically, too.
   Nahum Lev, chief economist at Bank Hapoalim, estimated Israel's
economic growth in 1989 was reduced by about one-half percent _
about $200 million _ because of business disruptions and trade
losses stemming from the uprising.
   The toll in the first year was about $600 million, Israeli
economists estimated.
   In the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip, the size of the gross
national product has shrunk by at least 25 percent, from about $1.5
billion in 1987 to about $1.125 billion now, Awartani estimated.
GNP is a measure of all goods and services produced in the economy.
   ``People are suffering,'' said Hisham Awartani, a leading
Palestinian economist. ``I'm not optimistic about 1990, either.''
   Lev believes the impact on Israel is decreasing because the
economy has more or less adjusted to new realities.
   He noted, for example, that many companies are hiring Israelis
to replace Palestinians, who often missed work because of strikes
or other uprising-related problems.
   ``The Israeli workers are more expensive, but they produce more
so output is rising,'' Lev said.
   In the West Bank and Gaza Strip, agriculture, construction and
service industries are suffering, Awartani said. The only bright
spot is industry.
   ``Hundreds of factories have sprung up,'' he said. ``Some are
cottage industries, but many are real factories employing 20 or 30
people.''
   The Palestinian factories are finding a ready market because of
the uprising boycott of Israeli-made goods. But Awartani said the
fledgling industries will have to worry about quality and price
competition if they are going to survive.
</TEXT>
