<SECOND>PM-US-Philippines, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0549,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Says Americans Free in Philippines</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: Top 7 grafs putting on record announcement that all Americans
freed; picks up at pvs 7th graf, ``We're still</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   All foreign citizens trapped by rebel fighting
in Manila hotels, including some 280 Americans, have been bused to
safety, the White House said today.
   ``The U.S. Embassy is working to help these individuals with
their travel plans,'' said presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater.
   He said the evacuations were completed without incident. ``All
Americans were reported safe and we have no reports of injuries,''
he said.
   ``I'm very encouraged about that,'' President Bush said earlier
when asked if all the Americans were safe.
   In Manila today, President Corazon Aquino declared a state of
national emergency, but it was unclear what additional powers her
government would wield with the declaration.
   Fitzwater declined to comment on the emergency declaration,
other than to say ``we will take a look at it and see if we have
any concerns.''
   State Department spokesman Mark Dillon said earlier today that
U.S. officials were trying to determine what the emergency
declaration specifically means.
   ``We're still getting reports on what the state of emergency
declaration includes,'' Dillon said, adding that there had not been
any additional requests for American assistance.
   On Tuesday, U.S. Embassy and Philippine authorities said 164
Americans were out safely, and that the evacuation appeared
complete.
   Consular officers met 30 buses at a reception center established
at a shopping center near the airport. Some 2,000 foreigners were
trapped for four days in hotels by the military coup attempt that
had killed at least 77 people.
   The U.S. response to the drama was decidedly low key Tuesday as
the administration sought to avoid language that could further
inflame tensions.
   The administration suggested the plight of the trapped
foreigners was not so much a hostage taking as it was the product
of the ongoing military revolt against Mrs. Aquino.
   To U.S. officials, the most disquieting aspect of the situation
were statements by some rebels that the Americans might not be
released to punish the Bush administration for its support for the
Aquino government.
   State Department spokesman Richard Boucher said there was no
indication that Americans had been singled out for mistreatment.
   Capt. Albert Yen, one of the insurgents, reflected the
sentiments of rebel hard-liners when he said, ``The intention is
not to release Americans.''
   ``U.S. meddling has caused the failure of the first wave of our
assault, so we hold them liable,'' Yen said. ``It is the
responsibility of the U.S. government if we take their nationals
hostage.''
   National security adviser Brent Scowcroft said Tuesday Mrs.
Aquino had not requested additional U.S. military support.
</TEXT>
