<FIRST>u i BC-Philippines-Excerpts     12-06 0468</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Philippines-Excerpts,0476</SECOND>
<HEAD>Excerpts of Aquino's Televised Speech</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Excerpts of President Corazon
Aquino's nationally televised speech Wednesday night. She spoke in
Tagalog and her remarks were translated into English by The
Associated Press:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   We must remember that the rebellion is not against the
government or the democratic process alone. This is a struggle
waged against the very people who had installed this leadership
when we established democracy in our country. The people too are
the intended victim. Although the government is prepared to deal
with this fierce strategy decisively, our people must join us in
giving the enemy the final blow. ...
   They just want to grab power. They do not think whether they
will inflict suffering on the Filipino people. How many innocent
civilians were killed? They did not think that lives of Filipinos
matter. The constant preoccupation is finding ways wherein they can
rule and have power.
   We still remember what martial law was like. Those people we
suspect are involved in what is happening now to our country, these
same peole believe they are the only ones who have power. During
martial law, we didn't have a duly ratified constitution. We didn't
have press freedom. During those times, when somebody wrote or said
something against the government, they were arrested and sometimes
even killed. ...
   I am telling you now that I have put so much at stake for
democracy. I have lost my husband. In 1983, he was killed. Many of
us suffered and until now we have put our lives at stake.
   You know what happened last Friday when rockets were fired at
Malacanang. What did these people want? It is very clear that these
people want to kill me, to eliminate me, so that they can rule our
land. What they have forgotten is that power is not theirs to take.
They cannot just grab power by killing people. They have to
understnd that power belongs to you, my beloved countrymen. Why did
I become president? That was because you believed in me. And in
spite of all of the coup attempts, you have stuck by me. And I know
that I owe my being president to you.
   I did not think of being president. I just wanted to serve you,
I just wanted to restore democracy. I want to respect your rights.
I am only asking you to help me. You are my only source of strength
to continue our reforms in government. I also depend on you to see
for yourself what these people are doing to us. ...
   Show our enemies that we, the Filipino people, love our coutnry.
We do not want these killings. We reject these people whose only
concern is their own interest. You, my beloved countrymen, I depend
on you.
</TEXT>
