<HEAD>Three Bodies Found, 2 Arrested in Apparent Burglary-Abductions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOPEKA, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two teen-agers were charged with murder
today after three bodies were found following an abduction that
involved an elderly couple checking on a neighbor, police said.
   Soldiers aboard a National Guard helicopter on Tuesday found the
bodies of Lester M. Haley, 87, and his 67-year-old wife, Nancy, in
a rural area about 10 miles east of Topeka, Douglas County District
Attorney Jim Flory said.
   A third body found early today in the same area was believed to
be that of Ida Dougherty, an elderly neighbor of the Haleys, police
said.
   A 19-year-old man and an 18-year-old woman were arrested
separately and booked on charges of murder, kidnapping, assault,
burglary and theft, police said. Authorities said they would
release the suspects' names and other information later.
   Police Lt. Bud Brooks said earlier that Haley and Verne Horne,
68, were checking Mrs. Dougherty's house Monday after seeing that a
newspaper had been left on the porch.
   They didn't find Mrs. Dougherty, but surprised a man with a gun
and were abducted, along with Mrs. Haley, who came to look for her
husband, Brooks said.
   He said the gunman dropped his captives off in a rural area, and
that Mrs. Horne got away unharmed, believing she was getting help
while the Haleys hid in woods. The bodies of the Haleys were found
in a field about two miles from where the gunman had dropped them
off, Flory said.
