<FIRST>r i AM-Philippines-Aquino     12-06 0373</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines-Aquino,0383</SECOND>
<HEAD>Strains Apparent As Aquino Begs For Support From Her People</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Philippines, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT H. REID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The strain of a six-day coup attempt
showed upon the face of Corazon Aquino as she appealed Wednesday
for her people to stand behind her in the gravest crisis faced by
her 3{-year administration.
   Mrs. Aquino made the appeal in her first nationally televised
appearance since Sunday, when she told military mutineers to
``surrender or die.''
   But on Wednesday, it was a different ``Cory'' Aquino. Gone was
the steely, uncompromising firmness that marked not only the Sunday
speech but other addresses she has delivered during five previous
coup attempts.
   This time, her eyes were swollen and her face was drawn. She
stared plaintively into the camera like a woman who had been
betrayed.
   ``I did not think of being president,'' Mrs. Aquino said. ``I
just wanted to serve you. I just wanted to restore democracy. I
want to respect your rights. I am only asking you to help me.''
   In previous crises, Mrs. Aquino delivered speeches in the crisp
monotone of a teacher lecturing an errant pupil. She prefers to
make speeches in English, an official language in the Philippines.
   On Wednesday, however, she spoke in Tagalog, a native language
better understood by ordinary Filipinos. Her choice of words and
the manner of speaking exuded more desperation than confidence.
   ``I am telling you now that I have put so much at stake for
democracy,'' she said, raising her arms slightly. ``I lost my
husband. ... Many of us suffered and until now we have put our
lives at stake.''
   Mrs. Aquino's husband, Benigno Aquino Jr., was slain in 1983 as
he stepped from a jet after arriving in Manila from the United
States to challenge the late President Ferdinand Marcos for
leadership of the country.
   Ordinarily, Mrs. Aquino reads speeches carefully crafted by her
staff. This time, she appeared to.be speaking extemporaneuosly, and
from the heart.
   ``Why did I become president?'' Mrs. Aquino asked. ``That was
because you believed in me. And in spite of all of the coup
attempts, you have stuck by me. And I know that I owe my being
president to you.''
</TEXT>
