<FIRST>r a PM-AlbanyAirport     12-06 0483</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Albany Airport,0496</SECOND>
<HEAD>FAA Says ``No'' to Private Albany Airport</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE HENDRICKS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A proposal to sell the Albany County Airport
to private bidders has been set back by the Federal Aviation
Administration, but proponents insist the deal is not dead.
   The negotiations to sell or lease the airport were viewed as the
possible beginning of a trend toward privatization of the nation's
municipal airports.
   James J. Coyne, the Democratic county executive who initiated
the proposal to sell the airport, said today that he felt misled by
the Reagan and Bush administrations after being told of the FAA's
disapproval.
   ``Here's an administration that has been very much a proponent,
at least verbally, concerning privatization,'' Coyne said.
   ``I feel we were misled by that administration.''
   Albany's airport and others run by cities and local governments
are increasingly beset with crowding and flight delays because
terminal expansion has failed to keep up with the growth in airline
travel. The last big airport to open was Dallas-Fort Worth's 15
years ago.
   Backers of private ownership say the profit motive would force
corporate operators to do a better job running airports than
governments do. Opponents contend private owners would raise the
fees they charge airlines, thus driving up ticket prices.
   The proposal is not dead. Coyne said he will work with
executives of British American Development Corp., of Latham, N.Y.,
and Lockheed Air Terminal Inc., of Burbank, Calif., as well as the
local bus authority, to explore ways to privatize the airport
without running into trouble with the FAA.
   ``I still feel the private sector is the best way to go,'' said
Coyne.
   FAA officials ruled earlier this week that airport revenue had
to be put back into the airport, rather than used for profits or to
repay debt raised to buy the airport.
   British American executives said the ruling was a setback, but
not a death blow to their bid.
   ``I think it has tremendous impact not only on the Albany County
Airport, but to every airport around the country,'' said Peter
Cornell, president of British American.
   ``If that stands up it is sending a signal all around the
country that we are not working toward privatization, but toward
nationalization of airports,'' Cornell said. ``Local governments
will just step away from running these airports and the federal
government will have to step in. I don't think that was the
intent.''
   One solution, Cornell said, would be to break the airport up
into segments, using revenues from operations not regulated by the
FAA, such as parking and car rentals, for profit and debt service,
while operating the airline segments separately under FAA
regulations.
   British American and Lockheed had combined to offer to buy the
airport for $30 million and run it for a profit. County officials
hoped to use the money to avoid raising taxes while financing
county operations.
</TEXT>
