<FIRST>u i AM-Germany-Stalinism     12-06 0481</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Stalinism,0497</SECOND>
<HEAD>Communists Break Taboos Of Hard-Line Past At Amazing Speed</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-East Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY CZUCZKA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EAST BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Under irresistible pressure from the
rank-and-file to cleanse itself, East Germany's Communist Party is
moving at top speed against the previously iron-clad taboos of the
Stalin era.
   The latest indication came Wednesday when the official party
newspaper urged a full investigation into the deaths of thousands
of German Communists killed in Josef Stalin's purges in the 1930s
and 1940s.
   On Tuesday night, East Berlin saw its first-ever concert and the
opening of an exhibition commemorating victims of the Soviet
dictator's repression.
   An emergency party congress Friday is expected to recast the
Communists' internal structure with the aim of building a
democratically run party.
   Such a move would respond to calls in several East German
newspapers Wednesday for abolition of ``Stalinist structures'' in
the party, including such instruments of uncompromising rule from
the top as the Central Committee and Politburo.
   ``Why do we need a Politburo if we want to turn the SED (East
German Communist Party) into a democratic party?'' asked the
official party newspaper Neues Deutschland.
   New party structures must prevent ``corruption, abuse of
official position or arrogance of power,'' Berliner Zeitung
newspaper said.
   Before the special classical concert in East Berlin's opera,
author Christoph Hein told the audience, ``Today a swamp of
incredible dimensions is emerging. It will stop instilling fear
when it is reclaimed.''
   Introducing Beethoven's Ninth Symphony, one speaker read a list
of victims of Stalinist repression in East Germany and paid tribute
to those killed during purges in the Soviet Union.
   Neues Deutschland, commenting on the death of thousands of
German Communists in Siberian labor camps between the world wars,
said: ``We have been silent too long about the fate of most of
them,'' and it asked how the official blind eye toward ``this sorry
chapter'' could be justified.
   East German party officials have already demanded access to
Soviet files allegedly listing the victims.
   Heinz Vosske, head of the party's central archives, suggested
that a plaque commemorating Communists killed in Stalin's time be
put up in East Berlin.
   Several leading intellectuals have been officially
rehabilitated, including the philosopher Ernst Bloch and physicist
Robert Havemann, a long-time dissident.
   The party was also considering the rehabilitation of two
journalists sacked for dissent in 1953, including a former chief
editor of Neues Deutschland.
   New Culture Minister Dietmar Keller, a Communist, recently said
the country is open for a range of opinions and the party will no
longer censor artists.
   At his first news conference, he appealed to exiled East German
cultural figures to resume ties with their native country despite
``the long shadows of history.''
   Officials have already announced that films banned in the 1960s
for questioning Stalinist policies will be be shown, some of them
for the first time.
</TEXT>
