<FILEID>AP-PX-12-06-89 1447EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Iran-Drugs     12-06 0663</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Drugs,0687</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iran Says 900 Drug Smugglers Face Gallows</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran said Wednesday that 900 suspected
drug smugglers face the gallows in a year-old narcotics crackdown
in which more than 1,000 men and women already have been executed.
   The official Islamic Republic News Agency, monitored in Cyprus,
quoted a senior official as saying that 14,000 people, including
569 Afghans, had been arrested since March for major drug offenses.
   ``Nine hundred of these are liable for the death penalty,'' said
Kiyumars Abu, director-general of the Islamic Revolutionary
Committees' anti-narcotics division.
   Iran's anti-drug campaign could eventually dam up what has
become a major narcotics pipeline into Western Europe and the
United States.
   Human rights organizations have condemned the large number of
executions in the ruthless crackdown, begun a year ago.
   But a campaign that cuts the volume of heroin flooding into the
West could help President Hashemi Rafsanjani's efforts to end
Iran's isolation and restore relations with the West.
   It also would coincide with the U.S. war on drugs and possibly
help foster a dialogue betwen Tehran and Washington, which severed
relations with Iran in 1979.
   An anti-narcotics law passed Jan. 21 stipulates the death
penalty for anyone found with even small amounts of heroin or
opium, the base for heroin.
   Iranian authorities have hanged in a single day as many as 80
people convicted of smuggling by Iran's non-jury Islamic courts.
   The bodies are often left dangling from makeshift gallows or
overhead road bridges for the day as a warning.
   The news agency quoted Abu as saying authorities had broken up
more than 140 smuggling gangs since March and seized more than 21
tons of narcotics. Scores of the heavily armed smugglers have been
killed in battles with security forces, it said.
   More than 41,000 addicts have been arrested and sent to labor
camps for rehabilitation, Abu said, adding that 10,000 had remained
off drugs.
   Officials have estimated Iran has 1 million addicts. But the
total is believed to be double that because addiction has soared
since the 1979 Islamic revolution and during the eight-year
Iran-Iraq war.
   The Iranians are trying to coordinate their crackdown with
neighoring Pakistan and Afghanistan, where much of the heroin,
opium and hashish originates, and with Turkey.
   Interior Minister Abdullah Nouri signed an accord with Pakistan
last month to work together on anti-narcotics operations along the
border.
   Earlier this year, Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto of Pakistan
declared war on the country's 40 drug mafias.
   But drug barons in Pakistan are deeply entrenched, and Western
drug enforcement officials say the lucrative smuggling operations
involve military and government officials.
   Stopping smuggling from neighboring Afghanistan to the northeast
is even more of a problem because of the civil war in that nation.
Moslem guerrillas fighting Afghanistan's Soviet-backed government
reportedly help bankroll their campaign by smuggling opium.
   Iran, Afghanistan and Pakistan have largely replaced southeast
Asia as the key producer of heroin following a U.S. crackdown in
the East in the past decade.
   A recent U.S. State Department report on narcotics said that
``opium production and heroin trafficking are deeply entrenched''
in Iran, Afghanistan and Pakistan.
   It said that between 200 and 400 tons of opium were produced in
Iran in 1987, 800 tons in Afghanistan and more than 200 tons in
Pakistan.
   The opium often is refined into heroin in secret laboratories in
Iran and smuggled into Turkey by truck.
   Other shipments are carried by mule trains through the mountains
of Kurdistan, which occupies southeastern Turkey, northwestern Iran
and northern Iraq. Kurdish guerrillas are said to help and use
their profits to buy weapons for their separatist campaigns against
Iran, Iraq and Turkey.
   Nouri has assigned tens of thousands of security forces backed
by helicopter gunships to hunt down the drug smugglers.
   The smugglers are armed with machine guns, rocket-propelled
grenade launchers and anti-aircraft weapons and there have been
scores of pitched battles along the rugged eastern borders over the
last year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
