<FIRST>r w AM-VA-RighttoDie     12-06 0548</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-VA-Right to Die,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Veterans Department Drafting Own `Right-to-Die' Rules</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Scotus-Right To Die, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While the Supreme Court weighs its first
``right-to-die'' decision, the Veterans Affairs Department is
drafting guidelines for dealing with those issues in its 276
medical centers and nursing homes.
   The VA currently follows the state laws such as the Missouri law
at the center of the case being reviewed by the high court. But the
department has determined that a state-by-state approach is
unworkable when both patients and doctors may transfer from
facility to facility nationwide.
   The issue has become especially critical to the VA because it
operates the nation's largest medical system and because of the age
of its clientele. Nearly half the 27 million veterans in this
country are older than 54.
   Unlike 32-year-old Nancy Cruzan, who other than her brain injury
was a healthy individual, VA patients often are old, terminally or
critically ill.
   VA actually began addressing such issues before 1983, when it
implemented a ``do-not-resuscitate'' policy on certain terminally
ill patients.
   Dr. Dorthy Rasinski, the VA physician and attorney in charge of
the ethics committee drafting the latest proposed guidelines, says
there is no conflict between the federal government arguing to
uphold the Missouri law while the VA is adopting nationwide
regulations.
   But ``there do appear to be some superficial inconsistencies,''
she acknowledged in an interview from her office at the Long Beach,
Calif., VA medical center, where she is assistant chief of staff
for education.
   On determining what a comatose patient would have wanted, the VA
is leaning toward putting the next of kin next in line, along with
the physicians, in making the decisions whether to withdraw
life-sustaining equipment, she said.
   In the Cruzan case, Ms. Cruzan's parents argued she had told
them that she would not want artificial means if ever rendered
incompetent. The Missouri Supreme Court said such statements fall
well short of the ``clear and convincing'' evidence needed to prove
her real intent.
   Rasinski said that the VA guidelines would not be so strict as
to require a ``clear and convincing'' proof _ which she interprets
as largely relying on written evidence.
   ``We would want something more than the unilateral recollection
of a single conversation,'' she said. Nurses, physicians, families
and friends would provide such evidence, she said.
   The VA realizes there are situations where the family member is
not in the best position to make the decision, she said, and there
are times when the physician has rejected a family member's
recommendation that life-support be withdrawn.
   She noted that in many cases a patient's wishes may be better
understood by someone else, such as in the case of AIDS patients
who have been alienated from their families because of
homosexuality. Also, she said, family members may be motivated by
the desire to collect survivors' benefits.
   But Rasinski says the centerpiece of the VA policy will be the
execution of a living-will document known as a ``durable power of
attorney,'' in which patients specify their representatives and
their wishes beforehand.
   At the Long Beach hospital, incoming patients are informed of
the California state law that provides for such living wills.
   The American Legion, a major veterans service organization, has
not addressed the issue.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
