<FIRST>u p PM-ElectionsRdp 3rdLd-Writethru a0563 12-06 0751</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Elections Rdp, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0563,0770</SECOND>
<HEAD>Official Denied Communion Wins; N. Dakota Rejects Proposals</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 14 grafs to UPDATE with Bentley conceding, quotes,
all North Dakota precincts reporting, no change in vote percentages. Picks
up 13th graf, `Gov. George....'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bishops-Politicians, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS J. ROWE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A Roman Catholic assemblywoman's opponent today conceded she
narrowly won a special California state Senate election that
attracted national attention after she was denied Communion because
of her abortion-rights ads.
   In North Dakota, voters rejected all eight proposals on their
ballot.
   With all 536 of the San Diego County precincts reporting,
four-term Democratic assemblywoman Lucy Killea led her Republican
opponent, freshman Assemblywoman Carol Bentley, by 1,528 votes.
   Although 2,500 to 3,000 absentee ballots remained to be counted
this afternoon, Bentley said at a news conference that she did not
think they would make a difference.
   Without those ballots, the totals were 60,012, or 51 percent,
for Killea, to Bentley's 58,484 votes, or 49 percent.
   Killea declined to say if Bishop Leo T. Maher's Communion ban
played a key role in the race.
   ``There's no way of really judging that,'' she said. ``I don't
know how you would figure it out other than get somebody to do some
polling and I'm not going to do that.''
   Bentley said the Communion ban and abortion issue were decisive
in the heavily Republican district.
   ``What this says is that my opponent's whole strategy was to
focus this race on abortion, so people wouldn't be looking at her
liberal voting record in the state Legislature,'' she said. ``The
bishop had an incredible impact on this race. In one letter, he
created an instant international celebrity and a martyr.''
   Kate Michelman, executive director in Washington, D.C., of the
National Abortion Rights Action League, called Killea's win ``a
stunning victory.''
   ``The bishop shot himself in the foot,'' said Michelman, who was
rasied as a Catholic. ``This is not the role for religion. They
should not be getting involved in politics. ... The voters there
really rose up against what the bishop was trying to do.''
   In Northern California, a four-year legal battle to boost
Hispanic representation on Watsonsville City Council ended with
Hispanics losing three of four seats they had sought. The election
was the first under a district-vote system. Council candidates
previously were elected at large.
   In deciding the most questions on a North Dakota ballot since
1919, voters soundly defeated proposals to raise the gasoline tax,
income tax and sales tax.
   With all precincts reporting, the closest margin was on the
proposal to raise the 5 percent sales tax by 1 percent. It lost 53
percent to 47 percent.
   Gov. George Sinner pondered budget cuts and a special
legislative session today after the proposed tax increases were
defeated.
   ``I've done my best to explain what we thought was at stake,''
said the Democratic governor, who had campaigned for the tax
increases. ``Now I have to do the best I can to make it work.''
   Tax opponents, led by Bismarck businessman Kent French,
celebrated.
   ``It's people power. The people of North Dakota have spoken
tonight,'' he said.
   More than 60 percent of voters also defeated a mandatory seat
belt law; a measure to legalize video gambling machines; and a
proposed health and sex education curriculum in public schools. The
seventh measure, a proposal to allow North Dakota legislators to
join the state Public Employees Retirement System, lost by 88
percent, the unofficial totals showed.
   And a constitutional amendment calling for reorganization of the
executive branch of state government lost by 71-29 percent.
   More than 230,000 North Dakotans _ 48 percent of eligible voters
_ thronged to the polls. Robert Valeu, deputy secretary of state,
said the turnout topped the record of 212,000 in a special ballot
in July 1939 that rejected a tax increase and liquor sales in
stores.
   In San Diego County's state Senate race, Killea is the first
U.S. public official to be denied Communion by the Roman Catholic
Church because of her support for abortion rights.
   Killea has said she will not change her stance on abortion.
   The special election was held to replace the incumbent, who was
made a municipal judge.
   Watsonville's election was originally scheduled for Nov. 7, but
was postponed after the Oct. 17 earthquake, which demolished more
than 300 homes in the farming community 95 miles south of San
Francisco.
   Housing and development, which were big issues before the quake,
took on even greater importance afterward.
</TEXT>
