<FIRST>u w PM-Israeli-Palestinian 1stLd-Writethru a0624 12-06 0481</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israeli-Palestinian, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0624,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Egypt Gives Nod To Baker Proposal on Peace Talks</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New material, editing throughout with further quotes, background.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Egypt has agreed to Secretary of State James
A. Baker's proposals for a direct dialogue between Israel and
Palestinian representatives provided certain conditions are met,
the State Department said today.
   Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler called the Egyptian
reply a ``step forward'' for the peace process. She raised the
possibility of a meeting among the Israeli and Egyptian foreign
ministers and the U.S. secretary of state early next year to work
on additional steps.
   However, it appeared there were still roadblocks to the start of
any direct talks among all the parties.
   Egypt has been working as the intermediary between the PLO and
Baker in the effort to get a dialogue under way. Its response
follows weeks of contacts between Egyptian and U.S. officials.
   Ms. Tutwiler indicated that Egypt, as Israel had done earlier,
set forth certain conditions that must be met if it is to continue
participating in the peace process.
   One such condition, based on statements over the weekend by
Palestine Liberation Organization representatives, is that the PLO
participate in selecting the Palestinian delegation for the
dialogue with Israel.
   Earlier, Israel had accepted the Baker plan on the condition
that no PLO representative take part. Israel also is demanding that
the talks be limited to Prime Minister Yithak Shamir's plan for
elections in the occupied territories. The PLO favors a dialogue
only if it deals with broader issues.
   In Israel, an adviser to Foreign Minister Moshe Arens said
Israel was waiting to see the Egyptian response in writing. Ms.
Tutwiler said Baker telephoned Arens this morning to brief him on
the response.
   ``We have now received from the government of Egypt a positive
response to Secretary Baker's five-point framework,'' Ms. Tutwiler
said.
   ``We will be working with the parties on steps needed to get to
a trilateral meeting in Washington as part of a process for
launching an Israeli-Palestinian dialogue,'' she said.
   The key element in a five-point Baker plan accepts Israel's view
that Israeli representatives will take part in the dialogue on the
basis of Shamir's election proposal.
   Under that proposal, the Palestinians would elect
representatives to open negotiations with Israel on limited
self-rule in the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   The Baker plan also makes a concession to the Palestinian side
in stating that Palestinian representatives at the talks would be
free to ``raise issues that relate to their opinions on how to make
the elections and the negotiating process succeed.''
   This raises the possibility, although not explicitly, of a more
open agenda in the talks than that favored by the Israelis, who
want to avoid discussion of points which are of high priority to
the PLO, such as the establishment of a Palestinian state.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
