<SECOND>AM-Health Hearings,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Panel Will Hold Week of Hearings in 5 States</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Labor and Human Resources Committee
will conduct public hearings and visit medical facilities in five
states next week to examine what some see as a national crisis in
health care, Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, the panel's chairman, said
Wednesday.
   ``Health care is the fastest failing business in America,'' the
Massachusetts Democrat said in announcing the schedule. ``The 1990
session of Congress offers the best opportunity in many years to
achieve fundamental and comprehensive reforms in all aspects of the
health-care system.''
   The first stop for the committee will be Monday morning in
Dorchester, Mass., where Kennedy, national drug policy coordinator
William Bennett and Gov. Michael Dukakis will review the
drug-education program at Lee School. The group also will tour
Women, Inc., a nationally recognized drug program for women with
young children.
   The remainder of the schedule:
   _Monday afternoon, a visit to the AIDS unit of Bronx-Lebanon
Hospital in New York and a public hearing in the hospital's
outpatient clinic.
   _Tuesday, Harbor-UCLA Medical Center in Torrance, Calif., for a
hearing on prenatal, infant and emergency-room care.
   _Wednesday, People's Health Center, St. Louis, for a hearing
featuring testimony from full-time workers who lack adequate health
insurance. The hearing will be followed by a visit to an auto plant
in Fenton, Mo., for a discussion of rising health-care costs.
   _Thursday, the Hancock County Primary Health Care Center,
Sparta, Ga., for a hearing focusing on rural health care.
