<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Quayle     12-06 0267</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Quayle,0275</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Spokesman Chides Quayle Attitude</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President Dan Quayle has a ``strange''
attitude toward the Soviet Union and appeared to be standing still
in a fast-moving world, a Foreign Ministry spokesman said Wednesday.
   Gennady I. Gerasimov, reacting to a Quayle interview in The
Washington Post on Tuesday, said the vice president resisted
adapting to the changes taking place in the Soviet Union.
   In the interview, Quayle said, ``You're still dealing with a
totalitarian government'' that wants to ``create instability'' in
other nations. ``I don't think they've changed much in foreign
policy,'' Quayle was quoted as saying.''
   Gerasimov said the Malta summit meeting between President Bush
and Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev had improved relations to
``a qualitatively new level.''
   Quayle, Gerasimov said, ``considers it to be a mistake to treat
the meeting as a sign of change in Soviet foreign policy.''
   Gerasimov said that despite the rapid changes taking place in
Eastern Europe and the Soviet Union, Quayle ``remains devoted to
his own beliefs.''
   ``A politician, if he is a realistically minded one, has to
assess changes in the world, to react to the new challenges of the
time,'' Gerasimov said.
   ``The remarks by the vice president, compared to other speeches
_ by the American president, the American secretary of state, the
president's assistant on national security and others _ sounded
strange,'' Gerasimov said.
   He compared Quayle to Kozma Prutkov, a character in Russian
literature who was stubbornly resistant to change. ``Like Kozma
Prutkov, this noble knight is in the same position, sitting on a
stone while the world is changing.''
</TEXT>
