<FIRST>u w AM-US-Nicaragua     12-06 0585</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Nicaragua,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>White House Says Contras Shouldn't Disband</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Contras ``have no alternative'' but to
stay together as a fighting force despite a regional peace accord
requiring the Nicaraguan rebels to disband this week, the White
House said Wednesday.
   White House Press Secretary Marlin Fitzwater said Nicaragua's
leftist government has failed to live up to terms of the pact under
which the Contras were to be voluntarily repatriated.
   Under the agreement signed in August by the presidents of
Honduras, Costa Rica, Nicaragua, El Salvador and Guatemala, the
Contras were to have disbanded by Tuesday, while the Nicaraguan
government was to make democratic reforms and promote safe
conditions for them to return home.
   The Contras do not intend to demobilize because ``the conditions
do not exist in Nicaragua'' for them to return, Contra spokesman
Bosco Matamoros said in a telephone interview on Wednesday.
   Fitzwater said they will continue to receive non-lethal
assistance from the United States under a bipartisan congressional
agreement that granted them a total of $47 million to last until
February, when Nicaragua is to hold national elections.
   Although the United States has cut off military aid, the Contras
have continued skirmishing with government troops, with the
fighting going on even before Nicaragua announced early last month
that it was ending a 19-month-old informal cease-fire.
   The peace plan signed by the five presidents in August at Tela,
Honduras, called for demobilization of the Contras by Dec. 5,
coupled with democratic reforms by Ortega's leftist government.
   The agreement also said Nicaragua would strengthen its internal
conditions for national reconciliation, which include elections
scheduled for Feb. 25, and would encourage repatriation of the
rebels.
   However, Fitzwater told reporters, ``The circumstances there do
not fulfill the conditions of demobilization as set forth in the
Tela accords.''
   ``Nicaragua was to provide the conditions that would be
conducive for voluntary repatriation. They have not met those
obligations. The Sandinistas have broken the cease-fire, have
sought to undermine the election process by harassing the
opposition.''
   Fitzwater also said Nicaragua had denied entry to observer teams
and congressional delegations that wanted to monitor election
preparations. While Nicaragua welcomed the observer mission headed
by former President Carter, the Sandinistas have not looked kindly
on some other would-be observers.
   Reps. Sonny Montgomery, D-Miss., J. Roy Rowland, D-Ga., Dana
Rohrabacher, R-Calif., and Chuck Douglas, R-N.H., were denied visas
last week. They were representing a 20-member commission named by
President Bush to observe election preparations. But the Sandinista
government said the group would not be admitted because it was not
independent.
   ``In view of this situation, the Contras have no alternative,''
Fitzwater told reporters.
   Cease-fire negotiations were suspended Nov. 21 after the Contras
refused to go along with a Sandinista demand for a partial
withdrawal of rebel forces to base camps in Honduras.
   The Contras declined to go beyond a pledge not to infiltrate
more troops from base camps in Honduras.
   The Sandinistas contend 2,300 Contras have infiltrated from
Honduras into Nicaragua over recent weeks.
   Their operation from base camps along the Honduran border, where
some 6,000 rebels are encamped, has been a bone of contention
between Honduras and Nicaragua.
   The Contras blamed the Sandinistas for suspension of the talks,
saying the rebels were willing to continue efforts to work out an
agreement. Matamoros underscored that offer on Wednesday.
   But Sandinista representatives maintained it was the consensus
of all sides involved in the talks that were held in Washington
that negotiations were at an impasse.
</TEXT>
