<FIRST>u i AM-Israel-Songs 1stLd-Writethru a0581 12-06 0452</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Songs, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0581,0466</SECOND>
<HEAD>Battle Over Effort to Ban Two Uprising Songs</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf and 10th graf to CORRECT translation of title
of song to ``The Flood Can Come After Us.''</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LOUIS MEIXLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Left- and right-wing politicians battled
Wednesday over whether to ban two songs by pop stars about the
Palestinian uprising from state-run radio and television.
   Right-wing members of the Broadcast Authority's administrative
committee pushed through a ban of ``A Kid Alone,'' by Chava
Alberstein, and ``The Flood Can Come After Us'' by Nurit Galron,
arguing the songs were ``PLO-like and could damage the morale of
the state.''
   But after the 4-2 vote Tuesday, the ban was delayed for two
weeks pending an appeal by left-leaning members of the committee,
said Vered Lyon, spokeswoman for Education Minister Yitzhak Navon.
The Broadcast Authority is part of the Education Ministry.
   Shlomo Kor, deputy chairman of the administrative committee, is
leading the fight for a ban. ``This is not just music, these are
political views,'' he said.
   ``These songs are against our nation, why do we have to
broadcast them?'' added Kor, a member of Prime Minister Yitzhak's
Shamir's right-wing Likud bloc.
   Aharon Harel, chairman of the committee, said the effort to ban
the songs ``marches the broadcast authority into the dark ages.''
Harel is, like Navon, a member of the left-leaning Labor Party.
   Ms. Lyon said Navon planned to hold a hearing on the songs in
two weeks and would bring the issuebefore the full Broadcast
Authority or the Parliament.
   Ms. Galron vowed to fight the ban, saying she believed it was
part of an effort to keep information about the uprising from the
public.
   ``In the beginning they tried to cover our eyes, now they are
trying to gag us,'' she told the daily Maariv.
   In ``The Flood Can Come After Us,'' already banned on Israel's
armed forces radio, Ms. Galron accuses Israelis of indifference to
the violence in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip:
   ``No, don't tell me about a little girl who lost an eye.
   ``It only makes me feel bad.
   ``I don't like hearing about people oppressed or tortured.
   ``I don't care what is happening in the territories.
   ``We will make love and live our lives. Tel Aviv is life.''
   Ms. Alberstein was overseas and unavailable for comment. Her
song ``A Kid Alone'' is a modern version of a traditional song
describing the oppression of the Jewish people.
   Alberstein sings the almost 1,000-year-old song in the original
Aramaic language and then adds in Hebrew:
   ``How long will the wave of violence continue,
   ``Chasing and chased, beating and beaten?
   ``When will this madness stop?''
</TEXT>
