<FIRST>u i AM-Escobar     12-06 0422</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Escobar,0435</SECOND>
<HEAD>Member of Medellin Drug Clan Arrested in Switzerland</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Colombia Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LUGANO, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Swiss police said Wednesday they were
holding Severo ``Junior'' Escobar, said to be among the top
Colombian drug traffickers.
   He is a nephew of Pablo Escobar Gaviria, alleged head of the
Medellin cartel, the most powerful drug gang in Colombia.
   His father, also named Severo, was given a 30-year prison term
in the United States in 1984 on conviction of smuggling 2,200
pounds of cocaine into the country.
   A police official, who would not let his name be used, confirmed
reports that the 30-year-old Colombian was arrested Nov. 29, but
would not provide details.
   Justice Ministry spokeswoman Ursula Riedel said Swiss
authorities had yet to receive extradition requests for Escobar,
described in news reports as the top Colombian trafficker in Europe.
   Escobar and four Colombian companions were arrested in a midday
raid on a hotel in Lugano, on the Swiss-Italian border, where they
had spent two months, the French-language newspaper Tribune de
Geneve reported.
   It said police seized 6.6 pounds of pure cocaine, described as a
sample of a planned delivery of 440 pounds destined for the Swiss
and Italian markets.
   La Vanguardia, a Spanish newspaper published in Barcelona, said
Severo Escobar's network brought huge loads of cocaine from Spain
for other European markets. It described his capture as a major
blow to the Medellin cartel.
   The police raid followed seven months of investigations in
Switzerland, Spain, the Netherlands and West Germany, Tribune de
Geneve said. Police confirmed that 12 people were arrested in those
countries.
   According to Tribune de Geneve, police seized nearly 1,000
pounds of cocaine with a street value of up to $75 million
   Mario Calderon, another key suspect in the Colombian cocaine
trade, was among those arrested, the paper said. Police declined
comment.
   Calderon was captured in September in connection with the
seizure of 825 pounds of cocaine Sept. 20 in Stuttgart, West
Germany, the paper reported. It said two Swiss policemen posed as
truck drivers and drove the drugs from Hamburg, the arrival port,
to Stuttgart.
   Five people were arrested Oct. 5 in Yverdon, western
Switzerland, Tribune de Geneve said.
   It also reported the arrests Nov. 29 in Madrid of a member of
the Cali cartel, another Colombian drug gang, and a Colombian who
allegedly helped amass several tons of cocaine in Spain.
   A spokesman for the Lugano prosecutor's office said Swiss
authorities had applied for the extradition of two Colombians held
in Spain. He refused to give details.
</TEXT>
