<FIRST>u w AM-Cranston     12-06 0585</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cranston,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cranston Demands FBI Find Source of Leak in Voter Registration Probe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Alan Cranston on Wednesday called on FBI
Director William Sessions to look for a government source for a
news story saying the bureau is investigating a voter registration
group operated by the senator's son.
   ``It makes my blood boil to see attempts to smear my son and
drag him into the mud,'' the California Democrat said in a
statement released at his office. He also urged an investigation of
a Republican-financed voter registration group.
   ``Leaks must not be tolerated among those who are responsible
for law enforcement,'' Cranston said. ``Leaks undermine our legal
system.''
   Cranston's statement came in response to a published report that
federal law enforcement authorities were investigating the Center
for Participation in Democracy, operated by Cranston's son, Kim.
   The investigation is aimed at determining whether the tax exempt
group sought to register more Democrats than Republicans, according
to the report which appeared in Wednesday editions of the New York
Times.
   Cranston said in his statement that his son ``has the highest
ethical standards I have ever known in anyone.''
   ``I know personally from Kim of the exquisite pains he took to
ensure that registration drives he was associated with were legal,
proper and bipartisan,'' said Cranston.
   Cranston and four other senators already were under fire for
intervening with federal regulators on behalf of Lincoln Savings
and Loan of California while receiving substantial campaign
contributions from Charles Keating Jr., who headed the institution.
Keating also contributed to Kim Cranston's voter group.
   Fred Reagan, a spokesman for the FBI in Los Angeles, refused to
comment on whether the bureau is conducting such an investigation.
   But documents released by the House Banking Committee, which
conducted hearings into the failure of Lincoln S&amp;L, show that
California officials turned over to the FBI material relating to
the voter registration groups.
   Richard Newsom, an examiner for the California Department of
Savings and Loan, provided the FBI office in Santa Ana, Calif.,
with copies of documents such as state forms declaring the Center
for Participation in Democracy a charitable trust.
   Meantime, Rob Giannangeli, a spokesman for the Internal Revenue
Service in Los Angeles, also said he could not comment on whether
there was an investigation of the voter registration groups.
   ``If in fact the FBI is investigating the Center for
Participation in Democracy, I suggest that it not limit is
investigations to groups alleged to be seeking to register
potential Democratic voters and that it look into
Republican-inspired registration groups as well,'' Cranston said.
   ``I also suggest the press likewise make its investigations
evenhanded and bipartisan,'' he added.
   He called for an investigation to determine ``what motivated Joe
Rodgers, who was chairman of the Reagan-Bush campaign in 1984, to
found Americans for Responsible Government, which in 1985 became
Vote America.'' He described the group as ``a Republican-supported
non-partisan voter registration organization.''
   ``How much money did he raise for Vote America or related
registration efforts? And from whom?'' Cranston asked.
   He also called for an inquiry into any connection between
``Republican-inspired registration drives'' and conservative groups
such as the Moral Majority, the American Coalition for Traditional
Values, the American Christian Voice Foundation, the American
Defense Foundation and the Responsible Government for America
Foundation.
   Cranston said his voter-registration efforts ``were motivated by
a simple principle: The health, indeed the very future, of our
democracy depends on the fullest possible voter participation by
all segments of our population.''
</TEXT>
