<FIRST>u a AM-RiotTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0676 12-06 0459</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Riot Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0676,0470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Miami Quiet As Deliberations Begin</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with jury adjourning for the day,
judge going on television to deny rumors of innocent verdict, other details;
picks up 4th graf, ``Innocent verdicts ...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jury deliberations began Wednesday in the
manslaughter trial of a Hispanic policeman accused of firing on a
motorcycle and killing two black men, setting off three days of
racial violence.
   Rumors swept the city that Officer William Lozano had been found
innocent or was about to be found innocent, court officials said.
Dade County's highest-ranking state judge went on live television
to deny them.
   The jury, which got the case after almost seven weeks of
hearings and testimony, adjourned for the day at 6 p.m. after
deliberating for nine hours. Deliberations were to resume Thursday.
   Lozano, 31, faces two counts of manslaughter in the deaths of
motorcycle driver Clement Lloyd, 23, and his passenger Allan
Blanchard, 24.
   The rumors caused some downtown office workers to leave work
early, court officials said.
   In the unusual live television appearance, Dade Chief Circuit
Judge Gerald Wetherington called for calm.
   ``There is no reason for concern on the part of anybody in the
community,'' Wetherington said. ``There is no indication there will
be any verdict tonight.''
   The judge revealed that the trial judge, Circuit Judge Joseph
Farina, may seal any verdict and delay announcing it for an
undetermined time.
   Innocent verdicts for police officers accused of killing Miami
blacks have touched off violence twice before in this decade.
   But Mayor Xavier Suarez and other officials expressed hope that
the presence of two blacks on Lozano's jury would demonstrate the
process was fair, whatever the verdict.
   Prosecutors say Lozano fired unnecessarily when Lloyd on his
motorcycle fled a police car after a traffic violation. Lozano said
he fired in self-defense when Lloyd tried to run him down.
   Deliberations were delayed for almost an hour after prosecutors
discovered a typographical error in jury instructions given Tuesday.
   The written copy in the jury's hands omitted the word ``or''
between two prosecution theories _ that Lozano committed an
intentional act or was guilty of culpable neglgence. The written
copy made it appear prosecutors had to prove both, not just one,
said Chief Assistant State Attorney John Hogan.
   The judge, over the objections of defense attorneys Roy Black
and Mark Seiden, agreed to insert the word in the jury's written
instructions, then denied Seiden's motion for a mistrial. The judge
said the defense had the option of appeal in case of a conviction.
   The courtroom was sealed so the jurors could deliberate there
because the extensive evidence would not fit in the small jury
chamber.
</TEXT>
