<FIRST>u a AM-PeaceCorps     12-06 0429</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Peace Corps,0446</SECOND>
<HEAD>Peace Corps Heads to Eastern Europe for First Time</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN K. PAULSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Peace Corps is heading to Eastern Europe for
the first time to help Hungary cope with rapid changes that are
creating a need for volunteer teachers, the agency's director said
Wednesday.
   The U.S. agency expects similar requests from other East bloc
countries, including Yugoslavia and Czechoslovakia, for instruction
on everything from health care to business administration, Director
Paul D. Coverdell said.
   Talks already are under way with Poland, he said.
   ``There's an enthusiasm that's almost unbridled about American
aid. It's almost euphoria,'' Coverdell said. ``There's an intense
desire to understand American institutions.''
   Coverdell said 65 Peace Corps volunteers will be sent to Hungary
to teach English. Poland has requested English teachers,
environmental instructors and help with small business
administration.
   Coverdell visited Poland and Hungary in October to discuss the
volunteer assistance. Peace Corps staff members will arrive in
Hungary in January, with volunteers expected in June after three
months' training in cultural affairs and language.
   Coverdell was in Denver to promote the agency's new World Wise
Schools program, which has former Peace Corps volunteers sharing
their knowledge with students about countries in which they've
lived.
   The Peace Corps, founded in 1961, relies on volunteers who spend
two years helping the people of other countries meet basic needs
for health care, food, shelter and education.
   Jim Flanigan, spokesman for the agency in Washington, said the
Peace Corps has 6,300 volunteers in 66 of the world's 170
countries, or about one-third.
   Coverdell said more than 2,000 people have signed up in recent
months for assignments in Eastern Europe.
   Volunteers in Hungary will have to subsist on $100 a month and
live the same Spartan lifestyle as Hungarians, Flanigan said.
   ``Once you get out of the facade of downtown Budapest, people
are living different lives,'' he said.
   Flanigan called the new assignments exciting and challenging.
And he said the Peace Corps does not fear ejection once in Eastern
Europe by any new governments that might be set up.
   ``We're on the crest of a wave,'' he said. ``It's important we
be there now and seize the moment.''
   Coverdell said East bloc countries are having a difficult time
adjusting to political reforms brought on by massive, pro-democracy
demonstrations in East Germany, Hungary, Czechoslovakia, Poland and
other countries.
   Problems that the Peace Corps can help with stem from a poor
infrastructure rather than a lack of knowledge, he said.
   ``The health delivery system infrastructure is suffering great
difficulty,'' Coverdell said.
</TEXT>
