<FIRST>u i AM-Czechoslovakia 3rdLd-Writethru a0675 12-06 0921</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czechoslovakia, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0675,0944</SECOND>
<HEAD>Communist Premier to Present New Opposition-Approved Government</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to include Slovak resignations, details.
Picks up 10th `Havel said' with editing thereafter to trim</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos PRA1,3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist premier agreed
Wednesday to name a new Cabinet including members suggested by a
popular opposition that rejects the current government. He said he
would quit unless the crisis is resolved.
   Opposition leader Vaclav Havel said Premier Ladislav Adamec
agreed to deliver a list of ministers Friday. The two had a long,
tough negotiating session Tuesday and a brief meeting Wednesday.
   Adamec, confronted by mass disapproval when he chose a new
government Dec. 3, said on television after Havel's news conference
he would resign if the political crisis continued. The opposition
has threatened a general strike Monday if he does not have a new
government.
   CTK, the official news agency, said Adamec accepted a list of
possible candidates from Civic Forum, the non-Communist opposition
group Havel leads, and would consult with other official political
parties.
   It quoted him as saying he probably would meet with Civic Forum
again Friday. Adamec said on television he had talked with Civic
Forum and other groups, ``but I don't know if we will reach
agreement as far as changes are concerned.''
   His television address indicated there had been tough bargaining
with the opposition. He said it was difficult to persuade
professionals favored by the opposition to join the Cabinet in a
fluid political situation where the public mood ``changes from day
to day and hour to hour.''
   Unless the situation calms and the government wins public
confidence, Adamec said, he would have no choice but to step down.
   ``If the government does not have these conditions, I cannot
take any responsibility for what happens,'' he said. ``In this
case, there is only one honest solution for me: to ask the
president of the republic to let me resign.
   ``I feel sorry that, in the event I resign as premier, I won't
be able to help the society to overcome the crisis,'' he added. He
did not give a time frame for deciding whether to stay in office.
   A CTK dispatch said the Politburo of the Slovak republic's
Communist Party resigned in advance of a special Slovak party
congress scheduled for Dec. 17. The Czech republic,
Czechoslovakia's other region, has a new government with a
non-Communist majority.
   Havel said Communist Party chief Karel Urbanek, who held a
75-minute meeting with him Wednesday, agreed with the opposition
that ``young, able people and experts who are not discredited''
should be brought into the government.
   Opposition leaders want such an ``interim government'' to create
the legal base for parliamentary democracy and hold free elections
in July.
   Czechoslovakia has moved rapidly toward democracy since brutal
police repression of a student demonstration Nov. 17 started a mass
pro-democracy movement and anti-government protests.
   In two weeks, the Communists have relinquished their 41-year
monopoly on power, reversed 21 years of hard-line policy on the
Prague Spring reforms of 1968 by condemning the Soviet-led invasion
that crushed them, and said free elections are likely next year.
   Adamec named a new Cabinet last Sunday, but included only five
non-Communists and left Communists in charge of key ministries.
   At his news conference, Havel refused to disclose details of his
negotiations with Adamec. Opposition sources said some form of
power sharing was envisioned, but whether that would lead to a
government led by non-Communists, as in Poland, was not clear.
   On Tuesday, the first government with a non-Communist majority
chosen in Czechoslovakia in 41 years was named to lead the Czech
regional administration. Communists retained the leadership and
deputy leadership of the government, along with the interior
ministry and key economic posts.
   Jiri Dienstbier, Civic Forum spokesman, called the new Czech
government ``a step in the right direction.''
   In Washington, the State Department said the latest developments
give reformers in the Communist Party ``a chance to demonstrate
statesmanship by working with Civic Forum and the Czechoslovakian
people to lay the foundation for political reform and a transition
to true democracy.''
   The Urbanek-Havel meeting was the first between the Communist
Party chief and the opposition leader, who only a month ago was a
banned, dissident playwright reviled in the official press. Havel
said Urbanek admitted his party faces ``deeply rooted mistrust''
and must change.
   Urbanek also assured the opposition the party paramilitary
force, the People's Militia, had been disarmed by the army and
probably would be absorbed into the armed forces.
   The opposition also wants the secret police disbanded. Havel
said Urbanek acknowledged the secret police ``has lost all its
purpose for internal matters,'' but whether it would be dissolved
was not clear.
   As the session ended, Urbanek was heard telling actor Milan
Knazko, the opposition leader in Slovakia: ``The most important
thing now is to calm people's emotions so that we don't have a food
rationing system tomorrow.''
   That indicated the Communists want to resolve the political
crisis before it affects the economy and supplies of consumer
goods, which are fairly plentiful compared with the rest of Eastern
Europe.
   On Tuesday, the opposition won another victory when a
parliamentary commission investigating the brutality Nov. 17 named
ousted party chief Milos Jakes and former Prague party boss
Miroslav Stepan as ``politically responsible'' for it.
   Naming those responsible was among the main opposition demands.
On Wednesday, the opposition also demanded new public prosecutors
be chosen for both the federal system and Czech region.
</TEXT>
