<FIRST>u a AM-MusicCenter     12-06 0568</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Music Center,0585</SECOND>
<HEAD>Music Center Celebrates 25th Anniversary With 25 Marching Bands</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN ANTCZAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Charlton Heston played Moses again, parting
the waters of a fountain, and 25 high school bands blared show
tunes as thousands of culture lovers celebrated the Music Center's
25th anniversary Wednesday.
   ``Who is on the Lord's side, let him come to me!'' the bearded
Heston thundered from a podium, holding aloft the ``real stick'' he
used to part the Red Sea in the classic film ``The Ten
Commandments.''
   The masses packing the Music Center plaza cheered as walls of
water rose up on either side of the plaza's central sculpture.
   ``It worked,'' Heston said.
   The birthday celebration was held exactly 25 years after the
Dorothy Chandler Pavilion opened on Dec. 6, 1964, with Zubin Mehta
conducting the Los Angeles Philharmonic and Jascha Heifetz as the
soloist.
   The $34 million center was completed in April 1967 with openings
of the Mark Taper Forum and the Ahmanson Theatre, giving a home to
performing arts in a city maligned by denizens of colder climes as
a cultural wasteland.
   The seven-acre center was built at the civic center with $20
million in private donations raised by Dorothy Buffum Chandler and
$14.5 million covered by a lease agreement with Los Angeles County.
   In contrast to the formal opening night years earlier, the
throng of noon revelers feasted on birthday cake and drank cartons
of milk under a brilliant 80-degree sky that Heston, in Moses tone,
took credit for.
   The round Mark Taper Forum was dressed like a birthday cake
complete with red candles sticking out of the roof. Visitors took
tours and the Mark Taper offered a free performance of Truman
Capote's ``A Christmas Memory.''
   The high school bands, led by a unit of the University of
Southern California band, played the title song from ``The Phantom
of the Opera'' and ``Seventy Six Trombones'' from ``The Music Man.''
   Actress Carol Channing, introduced to the strains of ``Diamonds
Are a Girl's Best Friend,'' presented her ``diamond awards'' to
Peter Schabarum, president of the county Board of Supervisors, and
Gordon Davidson, artistic director of the Center Theatre Group at
the Mark Taper.
   ``All good work is rewarded with diamonds,'' said Miss Channing.
   She recalled how she and the company of ``Hello Dolly'' broke
its original Broadway engagement to perform at the new Dorothy
Chandler Pavilion.
   ``It was one of the thrills of our lives,'' she said.
   The story triggered a memory for Carolyn Allen, a 10-year Music
Center employee in the crowd who had gone to that engagement of
``Hello Dolly.''
   ``I stood eight hours in line for a ticket. Then I sat on the
very top row of the balcony,'' she said, expressing disbelief it
had been so long ago.
   Construction began on the elegant, 3,197-seat Dorothy Chandler
Pavilion in March 1962, and was finished 2{ years later.
   The 742-seat Mark Taper opened on April 9, 1967, with ``The
Devils,'' starring Frank Langella and Ed Flanders. The 2,071-seat
Ahmanson opened three days later with Ingrid Bergman, Arthur Hill
and Colleen Dewhurst in ``More Stately Mansions.''
   In addition to the Philharmonic and Center Theater Group, which
develops experimental works at the Taper and classical dramas and
comedies at the Ahmanson, other companies are the Music Center
Opera, Joffrey Ballet LA-NY, Los Angeles Master Chorale and the
Music Center Education Division.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
