<FILEID>AP-PX-12-06-89 1924EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-AIDSCommission 1stLd-Writethru a0708 12-06 0864</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS Commission, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0708,860</SECOND>
<HEAD>AIDS Commission Urges Government To Fix Health Care System</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 4 grafs after 5th pvs, The commission, to add comment
from HHS spokesman, picks up 6th graf pvs, ``It is essential</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Commission on AIDS said the
nation's health care system needs urgent repair to deal with the
crisis and underscored that point Wednesday by sending its report
to the White House eight months early.
   ``A series of problems have resulted in a health care system
singularly unresponsive to the needs of HIV infected people,'' the
commission said in its report to President Bush.
   The commission said that because infection with the human
immunodeficiency virus, or HIV, appeared initially in ``groups
often shunned by the larger society,'' including homosexuals, the
poor, minorities and intravenous drug users, the national response
to the AIDS epidemic has been slow.
   The commission cited a lack of training support for primary care
physicians to treat people with HIV infection and AIDS, and
financial disincentives for physicians to treat Medicaid and other
poor patients.
   ``The commission believes it is time to match rhetoric with
action,'' said the report by the panel created by Congress to
advise the president and Capitol Hill on AIDS issues.
   Dr. Louis Sullivan, who as secretary of the Department of Health
and Human Services sits as a non-voting member of the commission,
did not participate in writing the report and a spokesman for
Sullivan took issue with the report's criticism of national
leadership it says is lacking.
   Spokesman Jim Brown said Sullivan has expressed concern about
some of the same issues addressed by the commission's report.
However, Brown said, ``there has been leadership from this
department and there will continue to be.''
   Brown cited among the department's AIDS activities education
programs, drug research at the National Institutes of Health and
federal funding under Medicaid to treat people with AIDS.
   But the report said more needs to be done.
   ``It is essential that everyone be afforded early intervention
and access to care,'' the report said.
   The report estimated that direct medical care for people with
AIDS in 1991 will cost from $2.5 billion to $15.1 billion. It notes
the range is from less than 1 percent to about 3 percent of total
health care spending in the nation, and adds, ``We simply must be
prepared to make these expenditures.''
   Dr. David Rogers, vice chairman of the commission, said these
costs are affordable. ``I think we've done a disservice to say
these are astronomical costs and that we can't handle them. Of
course we can,'' he said.
   The commission was required to draft its first annual report by
August 1990. But, in a letter to President Bush accompanying the
report, commissioners said testimony they heard at their public
hearings ``was so compelling we felt it is vital to write to you
now.'' Copies of the report were also given to leaders of the House
and Senate.
   Federal health officials say 112,241 cases of AIDS have been
reported in the United States since June 1981, and 66,493 of them
have died.
   More than 1 million Americans are believed to be infected with
HIV now, and the commission said that over the next four years,
AIDS is likely to claim 200,000 lives.
   ``The HIV epidemic is not just a New York City or a San
Francisco problem as some would like to believe,'' the report said.
   Though those cities continue to have a heavy load of AIDS cases,
by 1991, experts estimate that 80 percent of new AIDS cases will
come from outside those two cities, the report said.
   The epidemic is infecting a disproportionate number of blacks
and Hispanics and is expected to take an increasing toll on women
and children in coming years, the report said.
   While new drug treatments can prolong the lives of people with
HIV infection and AIDS, ``scientific breakthroughs mean little
unless the health care system can incorporate them and make them
accessible to people in need.''
   The commission cited a 1987 survey that showed nearly one
quarter of all AIDS patients have no form of insurance, private or
public.''
   Additionally, those on Medicaid run into barriers because low
reimbursement rates are a disincentive for physicians to treat
Medicaid patients, the report said.
   ``For example, a new patient intermediate office visit in New
York City is compensated by Blue Cross at $78, by Medicare at $80
and by Medicaid at $7,'' the report said.
   What's needed, the commission said, is ``frank recognition that
a crisis exists in many cities that will require extraordinary
measures to overcome.''
   The panel recommended creation of a ``flexible, patient-oriented
comprehensive system of care, closely linking hospital, ambulatory,
residential and home care.''
   The report also says the administration should consider creating
regional centers to provide back-up and consultation to primary
care physicians treating AIDS patients.
   It also calls for creation of units for treatment of HIV
patients who are also drug addicts. Commission members also
expressed ``surprise and disappointment'' that the White House
National Drug Control Strategy gives little attention to the
problem of AIDS spread by IV drug users sharing needles.
</TEXT>
