<FIRST>u i AM-Israel-Mideast     12-06 0666</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Mideast,0687</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rabin Says Egypt Acceptance of U.S. Plan Advances Peace Prospects</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Mideast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin described as a
``great step forward'' on Wednesday the acceptance by Egypt of a
Middle East peace plan offered by U.S. Secretary of State James A.
Baker III.
   Rabin said Baker and the foreign ministers of Israel and Egypt
should meet quickly to determine the composition of a Palestinian
delegation for peace talks with Israel and the agenda of such talks.
   ``I bless it. ... I see the positive Egyptian response as a
great step forward, toward the implementation of the Israeli peace
plan,'' Rabin said, speaking on Israel Television.
   The State Department announced Wednesday it had received a
``positive'' response from Egypt. Department spokeswoman Margaret
Tutwiler raised the possibility of a trilateral meeting in
Washington early next year to work on details.
   ``We will be working with the parties on steps needed to get to
a trilateral meeting in Washington as part of the process for
launching an Israeli-Palestinian dialogue,'' she said.
   Baker's framework calls for a preliminary dialogue in Cairo,
Egypt, between delegations of Israel and the Palestinians so as to
advance the Israeli-offered plan of elections in the occupied West
Bank and the Gaza Strip.
   In other Middle East developments Wednesday:
   _Kurt Waldheim, president of Austria and former
secretary-general of the United Nations, ended a three-day official
visit to Tunisia after brief talks with PLO Chairman Yasser Arafat
on the prospects for peace in the Middle East. Arafat's Palestine
Liberation Organization is headquartered in Tunis.
   _President Hafez Assad repeated Syria's support for a
U.N.-sponsored Arab-Israeli peace conference, despite U.S. and
Israeli efforts to arrange more limited negotiations. His comments
came in a meeting in Damascus with former U.S. Secretary of State
Cyrus Vance and former Undersecretary Richard Murphy, who are on a
study tour of the region.
   Rabin, of the left-leaning Labor Party, said of Egypt's
acceptance, ``The moment Egypt, in addition to Israel, gave a
positive reply, there is no obstacle, and we should not examine
their response as we won't agree to them examining our peace
initiative.
   ``The moment the answer is positive in principle, we should move
forward toward the meeting of three ministers who should determine
the composition of the Palestinian delegation and what will be on
the agenda.''
   His comments contradicted an earlier statement by Foreign
Ministry spokesman Yosef Amihud, who said Israel first wanted to
see a written version of the Egyptian response to examine it.
   The discrepancy could be explained by ideological differences
between Labor and the hard-line Likud bloc of Foreign Minister
Moshe Arens and Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir.
   Labor favors a territorial compromise with the Palestinians and
is ready to offer concessions. Likud views the occupied lands as an
integral part of Israel.
   Rabin, contrary to Likud's stand, indicated he did not oppose an
indirect PLO role in the process, saying:
   ``Today there are three partners to the move, Egypt, Israel and
the United States. Whomever one of them talks to, it's their
business.''
   Rabin expressed hope Likud would not torpedo the negotiations.
   Many problems remained unresolved even after Egypt's acceptance
of Baker's peace framework.
   Ms. Tutwiler indicated that Egypt specified some conditions, as
Israel had done earlier. She said that ``in their responses, both
Egypt and Israel have conveyed certain views and positions on this
process.''
   Israel accepted the Baker plan but sought U.S. guarantees the
PLO _ viewed by Israel as a terrorist group _ would play no role in
the peace process.
   It also wants the agenda limited to Israel's elections proposal,
which says negotiations would be held with elected representatives
on limited autonomy for 1.7 million Palestinians in the occupied
territories.
   The PLO wants a broader agenda so Palestinian demands for
independent statehood can be raised. It also wants to take part in
selecting the Palestinian delegation for the dialogue with Israel,
and the Egyptian response also apparently contained such a
condition.
</TEXT>
