<FIRST>u w AM-US-Philippines 2nd-LdWritethru a0742 12-06 0704</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Philippines, 2nd-Ld Writethru, a0742,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Official Casts Doubts on Aquino's Long-Term Political Survival</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Philippines, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 4th graf: ``The official,'' with news from Manila that
troops to return to barracks; material from a0751 et. seq.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Philippine President Corazon Aquino's ability
to survive politically is in doubt and may depend on how seriously
she takes the lessons of the coup attempt against her, a senior
Bush administration official said Wednesday.
   ``She's been hurt, there's no question about it,'' said the
official, who briefed a small group of reporters on the condition
he not be named.
   It was the first time since the military rebellion began Friday
that the Bush administration had voiced concerns about the mutiny's
long-term effects on Aquino's future.
   The official spoke a little more than an hour before news came
from Manila that rebel troops holding a downtown district had
agreed to return to their barracks.
   The administration official, in an apparent attempt to send a
clear signal to Aquino, said the United States must now ``reassess
what all this means'' in terms of U.S. assistance to her government.
   He did not elaborate.
   But the official called the insurrection a ``serious'' attempt
to topple Mrs. Aquino and said she should regard it as such.
   He called on Mrs. Aquino to seek to ``eliminate the sources of
discontent which helped lead to the coup'' as she struggles to
reassert control.
   Asked if Aquino could survive politically if she succeeds
militarily in putting down the rebel forces, the official said:
   ``That's a tough one.
   ``There has been a lot of criticism of her from the army'' for
not giving military leaders more of a free hand in cracking down on
the leftist New People's Army and for ``ignoring the military,''
the official said.
   ``I don't know if it's justified or not. It is what they
believe,'' he went on, adding that the criticism is ``a symptom of
feelings. And, as a political leader, she has to deal with it.''
   It is elements of Aquino's own army that are rebelling against
her now. The U.S. official noted that the restiveness in the
military gave Col. Gregorio Honasan, a leader of the coup attempt,
far more support over the last week than he had when he led a
previous effort to oust Mrs. Aquino.
   Earlier, U.S. officials praised as ``careful and effective'' a
Philippine evacuation that freed 280 Americans and other foreigners
from the Manila hotels where they had been trapped by gunfire in
the six-day-old rebellion.
   ``We commend the Aquino government for organizing and carrying
out this operation,'' said State Department spokeswoman Margaret
Tutwiler, applauding the ``careful and effective manner in which it
dealt with the situation in the Makati commercial district and the
efforts it took to safeguard American citizens and others who were
in the area.''
   The evacuation followed negotiations between the Aquino
government and the rebels ``into the early hours'' of Wednesday to
reach a cease-fire, she said, but declined to comment on restraint
shown by the rebels. U.S. officials had no contact with the rebels,
she said.
   ``It's unfortunate that the rebels caused this situation,'' Ms.
Tutwiler said. ``We are obviously not going to get out here in a
position and applaud the rebels. We are applauding the Aquino
government.''
   All those trapped in the hotel district were freed without
injury, she said, and were taken by bus to processing centers set
up by the U.S. Embassy to help them contact relatives and make
lodging and travel plans.
   ``While the situation has improved, we continue to urge American
citizens to exercise caution,'' Ms. Tutwiler said.
   Aquino's declaration of a state of national emergency was
``totally, legally what she has done under their constitution,''
Ms. Tutwiler said, declining further comment on the Philippine
government's response to the week-old rebellion.
   At the White House, spokesman Marlin Fitzwater also declined
comment on the emergency declaration other than to say, ``We will
take a look at it and see if we have any concerns.''
   Some 2,000 foreigners had been trapped for four days in hotels
by the military coup attempt that had left at least 79 dead and 570
wounded since Friday.
</TEXT>
