<FIRST>r a AM-ChowchillaKidnapper     12-06 0390</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chowchilla Kidnapper,0401</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chowchilla School Bus Kidnapper Denied Parole</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN LUIS OBISPO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of three men who commandeered
a school bus and held the driver and 26 children underground in a
$5 million ransom plot was denied parole Wednesday for the sixth
time.
   The California Board of Prison Terms refused James Schoenfeld's
latest bid for freedom after a 2{-hour hearing at the prison where
he is serving a life sentence in the 1976 kidnapping.
   The denial was based on Schoenfield's crime, ``which was carried
out in an especially heinous, atrocious, cruel and callous manner
which exhibits a disregard for the life or suffering of another,''
said Phyllis Scott, a spokeswoman for the three-member board.
   Schoenfeld, 37, who was sentenced in 1978, will be eligible for
parole again in December 1990, Ms. Scott said.
   Schoenfeld, his brother, Richard, and Frederick Woods were
convicted of the July 15, 1976, abduction of the Chowchilla school
bus driver and 26 children headed home from summer school. The
children ranged in age from 5 to 14.
   The kidnappers placed the youngsters and bus driver in a moving
van buried at a rock quarry near Livermore, almost 100 miles west
of Chowchilla, which is 240 miles northwest of Los Angeles.
   ``The prisoner and crime partners kidnapped at shotgun point 26
youngsters and their school bus driver and transported them 100
miles away to a buried van,'' Ms. Scott said.
   The youngsters and driver escaped after 17 hours in the
sweltering van, 28 hours after their abduction. The van was
equipped with a single air vent to allow the group to breath
underground.
   The Schoenfeld brothers and Woods were members of prominent San
Francisco Peninsula families and said in pre-sentencing reports
that they planned to seek $5 million ransom.
   They were thwarted in telephoning their ransom demands to
authorities in Chowchilla because the telephone lines were tied up
constantly by law enforcement officials and reporters the day after
the kidnapping.
   The board also denied parole based on a psychological evaluation
of Schoenfeld in September, Ms. Scott said. She would not provide
details of the evaluation.
   During the hearing, the panel commended Schoenfeld for his good
behavior and his excellent work record as a vocational drafting
clerk, Ms. Scott said.
   Richard Schoenfeld and Woods also received life terms and have
been denied parole periodically.
</TEXT>
