<FIRST>u i AM-Salvador-American     12-06 0321</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador-American,0328</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Hold American Overnight</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas on Wednesday
released an American helicopter mechanic they had held prisoner
with his thumbs tied behind his back for 22 hours, the U.S. Embassy
confirmed.
   Rebels of the Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front, or
FMLN, had reported on their clandestine radio what they described
as the brief detention of a U.S. citizen. The insurgents identified
the man as Jack Cooper and said he was a U.S. military adviser.
   Embassy spokesman Jeff Brown said the man's surname is not
Cooper, but declined to identify him, citing the privacy act. He
also said the man is not an adviser, describing him as a civilian
helicopter mechanic under contract to the 55 U.S. military advisers
based in El Salvador.
   The rebels said on Radio Venceremos they detained the American
late Tuesday at a guerrilla roadblock on the capital's western
edge, in the affluent Escalon neighborhood.
   Escalon has been the scene of sustained combat twice since Nov.
11, when the insurgents launched their largest offensive of the
10-year-old civil war. Both times, after invading the neighborhood
for several hours, they retreated up the San Salvador volcano that
looms over the capital's northwestern sector.
   The guerrillas said the man and a Salvadoran woman companion
were briefly questioned and released.
   Brown said the man was indeed detained in upper Escalon, but was
held from 7:30 p.m. Tuesday until 6 a.m. Wednesday. He said the
man's car was stolen and he was forced to stand for ``several
hours.'' His thumbs were tied behind his back while he was held, he
said.
   The rebels have reiterated repeatedly in recent months they do
not consider non-military U.S. personnel objectives in their war
against the government. Guerrillas occupied the houses of several
American families last week during an incursion into Escalon, but
called a truce to permit their evacuation.
</TEXT>
