<FIRST>u a AM-ShipFire 2ndLd-Writethru a0739 12-06 0205</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ship Fire, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0739,0207</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fire on Ship in Portland Injures Five</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with fire contained, 450 people on board,
sted 150, 30 pieces of equipment used, sted 20, two trapped crew members
rescued, the injured suffering smoke inhalation.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A five-alarm fire broke out Wednesday on a
cruise ship moored for repairs near downtown Portland, injuring
five people before it was contained, the harbormaster said.
   About 450 people were on the 618-foot Bermuda Star moored at
Swan Island when the fire broke out shortly after 1 p.m. in an area
where welders were working, said Harbormaster Mell Pittmon.
   The fire was contained by 3 p.m., he said.
   The blaze quickly went to four alarms, and a fifth alarm was
issued about an hour later, fire officials said. At least 100
firefighters and 30 pieces of answered the alarm.
   Two crew members trapped in a lower deck were rescued from the
ship, and five crew members suffered smoke inhalation and were
taken to area hospitals, Pittmon said.
   The 14,208-ton ship arrived at the Port of Portland on Tuesday
to undergo $25 million worth of repairs.
   Those on board included 250 repair workers and 200 crew members,
Pittmon said.
</TEXT>
