<FIRST>u a AM-ElectionsRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0779 12-06 0712</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Elections Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0779,0731</SECOND>
<HEAD>Official Denied Communion Elected, N.D. Voters Reject Tax Hikes</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 14th graf, ``In North ...,'' to UPDATE number that voted.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bishops-Politicians, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JONATHAN W. OATIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Roman Catholic Assemblywoman Lucy Killea was narrowly elected to
California's Senate because the church made a ``martyr'' out of the
Democrat by denying her Communion for supporting abortion rights,
her GOP opponent said Wednesday.
   Killea disputed Assemblywoman Carol Bentley's analysis of
Tuesday's special election, saying her stance hurt her as much as
it helped.
   In North Dakota, Gov. George Sinner proposed $98 million in
spending cuts after voters Tuesday rejected three proposed tax
increases, two of which had already gone into effect after approval
by the Legislature.
   Five other referendums, including one requiring seat belt use
and another mandating a statewide sex education curriculum, and a
proposed constitutional amendment were also defeated.
   ``People were in the mood to vote `no,' and once they started
voting no, they just kept going,'' said state Rep. Tish Kelly of
Fargo.
   In Northern California, a four-year legal battle to boost
Hispanic representation on Watsonsville's city council ended with
Hispanics losing three of four seats they'd sought under a new
election system. Seven seats had been up for grabs.
   Killea's margin over Bentley in the San Diego County election
was razor thin. She got 61,860 ballots, or 50.97 percent of the
vote, to 59,496 for Bentley, or 49.03.
   Bentley, a freshman from La Mesa, said at a news conference that
Bishop Leo Maher ``had no choice'' but to deny Holy Communion to
Killea three weeks ago, making her the first U.S. elected official
to be so sanctioned.
   But, Bentley added, ``The bishop's action created an
international celebrity and martyr.''
   ``I don't see that,'' Killea said at her post-election news
conference. ``We got an awful lot of people who opposed me because
of the bishop's decision. I think it worked both ways. ... I don't
think we'll ever know.''
   Maher reiterated his displeasure with Killea, saying he made an
example of her because she had the responsibility as a Roman
Catholic elected official to follow church teachings in the public
arena.
   ``It is to be noted that no popular vote or public opinion can
change in any way the divine law that directs and guides
humankind,'' Maher said in a statement.
   Killea replaces an incumbent who resigned to become a municipal
judge.
   In North Dakota, 253,439 people, or 53 percent of those
eligible, cast ballots. The seven referendums were the most on a
ballot since 1919.
   About 60 percent of the voters rejected proposed increases in
income and motor fuel taxes, and a proposed raise in the sales tax
lost 53 percent to 47 percent.
   ``I am very disappointed, obviously, in the outcome,'' Sinner
said in proposing $34 million in cuts for elementary and secondary
education, $24 million for higher education and $21 million for
social services.
   Some attributed the defeat to years of drought and a decade of
economic hardship. ``North Dakota people are short of money and
hurting,'' said state Sen. Geraldine Meyer.
   The state Tax Department told merchants to immediately lower the
sales tax from 6 percent to 5 percent. State income taxes dropped
from 17 percent to 14 percent of a federal tax bill. The gas-tax
hike never took effect.
   In addition to the seat belt and sex education referendums,
voters rejected proposals to legalize video gambling and put state
lawmakers in the public employee retirement system.
   The defeated constitutional amendment would have limited the
number of state agencies under the governor's control to 14. More
than 100 now fall under gubernatorial jurisdiction.
   Watsonville's court-ordered election was the first under a
district-vote system. Council candidates previously were elected at
large.
   The election was originally scheduled for Nov. 7, but was
postponed after the Oct. 17 earthquake, which demolished more than
300 homes in the farming community 95 miles south of San Francisco.
   One Hispanic candidate blamed her defeat on the disaster. ``We
just didn't have the money, or whatever it took, to beat an
earthquake,'' community organizer Cruz Gomez said at a glum
post-election gathering.
   The only Hispanic to win a seat on the council was Oscar Rios,
the charismatic leader of a 19-month cannery strike.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
