<DOCNO> AP891206-0161 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-06-89 0109EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-AMA     12-06 0226</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AMA,0232</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Medical Association Strengthens Pro-Choice Stand In Abortiton</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American Medical Association took a strong
pro-choice stand on abortion here Tuesday, saying ``the early
termination of pregnancy is a medical matter between the patient
and the physician.''
   The AMA's House of Delegates voted to reaffirm the association's
policy statement that abortion should be peformed only by a
licensed physician in conformance with state laws, and that no
physician should be required to perform an abortion in violation of
good medical judgment or his or her personal moral principles.
   The delegates then adopted, on a voice vote, the pro-choice
amendment offered by the California delegation. However, the ``no''
votes were nearly as strong as the affirmative votes.
   Delegates from some states argued that the amendment would run
counter to positions taken by their state associations.
   The delegates also consdered a proposed policy statement on
maternal-fetal conflict, but referred the matter to the Board of
Trustees for further study before the the next annual meeting in
June 1990.
   Physicians are wrangling with legal and moral issues arising
when a pregnant woman refuses medical treatment that would benefit
the health of her fetus.
   Also referred back to the trustees for further study was a
proposed patient bill of rights, which stated that patients should
have the right to basic and essential medical care.
</TEXT>
