<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     12-06 0821</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0862</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Business Machines Corp. announced
it would cut 10,000 U.S. jobs and repurchase $4 billion of its own
stock in a two-pronged plan to reduce costs and please shareholders.
   The world's biggest computer company also said Tuesday it would
set aside $2.3 billion from its pre-tax profit to pay for the job
cuts and related steps. That will give IBM a net loss in the fourth
quarter and guarantee a decline in 1989 earnings compared to 1988.
   IBM is being squeezed by sluggish spending by its customers,
increasing competition and the personal computer revolution, which
is cutting into sales of the big mainframes and minicomputers that
account for most of its profits.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Domestic automakers reported a 9.3 percent
decline in late-November vehicle sales, extending a slide that
began when they introduced more expensive 1990 models a few months
ago.
   The eight major automakers with U.S. assembly plants reported
Tuesday they sold cars and light trucks at an average daily rate of
37,059 during the Nov. 21-30 period this year, compared with a rate
of 40,843 during the same time last year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration began looking for a
successor to savings and loan regulator M. Danny Wall while the
chairman of the House Banking Committee said hearings that led to
Wall's resignation were ``just the beginning'' of the investigation.
   The administration wants a professional regulator to head the
Office of Thrift Supervision, rather than an appointee whose chief
qualifications are political connections, according to an industry
source, who spoke Tuesday on condition of anonymity. Wall announced
his resignation Monday.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   American Airlines, the nation's largest carrier, has decided to
match an increase in MaxSaver fares, the most deeply discounted
advance-purchase fares.
   Following a move a week ago by Pan Am Corp., American said
Tuesday it plans to raise its MaxSavers by $10 round trip on
flights of less than 1,000 miles and $20 on longer trips. The new
fares take effect Dec. 16.
   Spokesmen for other major carriers, including United Airlines
and Continental Airlines, said late Tuesday they were still
studying the issue after a week of deliberation.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Equimark Corp. became the third institution in
recent weeks to delay previously announced buyouts of insolvent
Texas banks.
   Pittsburgh-based Equimark said Tuesday it would be sometime in
the next three months before it completes its purchase of San
Antonio-based National Bancshares Corp. of Texas. Originally, the
deal had been expected to close by the end of the year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WHEELING, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wheeling-Pittsburgh Steel Corp. probably
will remain profitable despite a downturn in the steel industry
next year, but the company sees no immediate end to its federal
bankruptcy status.
   James L. Wareham, Wheeling-Pitt president and chief operating
officer, blamed the expected downturn on lower steel prices
throughout the industry.
   William J. Scharffenberger, Wheeling-Pitt board chairman and
chief executive officer, told shareholders Tuesday legal
constraints would prevent the steelmaker from emerging from U.S.
Bankruptcy Court protection before June 1990. The company filed for
Chapter 11 protection on April 16, 1985.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense attorneys have introduced telephone
records in the GAF Corp. stock manipulation case that apparently
contradict key government testimony about calls discussing the
alleged fraud.
   The new evidence, introduced Monday, indicates no calls were
placed on long-distance WATS lines from the Jefferies &amp; Co.
brokerage to GAF or its vice chairman, James T. Sherwin, during
times in October 1986 when the government alleges the manipulation
was discussed.
   The defense rested its case Tuesday after actress Liv Ullman
testified on Sherwin's behalf as the final witness in the
seven-week criminal trial in Manhattan federal court. Closing
arguments were to begin Wednesday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Georgia-Pacific Corp. extended its $3.6 billion
offer to buy rival paper-maker Great Northern Nekoosa Corp. for one
week, but officials of the target remained opposed to the deal.
   The $63-a-share bid, originally set to expire at midnight EST
Monday, was extended Tuesday by Georgia-Pacific until midnight Dec.
11.
   Officials of Norwalk, Conn.-based Great Northern have refused to
discuss the proposed merger with Georgia-Pacific.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mellon Bank Corp., continuing its rebound
from hard financial times, said it had agreed to pay buy 54 local
branches of PSFS, the nation's oldest mutual savings bank.
   Meritor Savings Bank, which owns PSFS, is expected to get about
$335 million from Mellon for the branches. The move disclosed
Tuesday is the latest in an asset-paring restructuring that Meritor
started in 1987.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market slumped Tuesday as the Dow Jones average of 30
industrials dropped 11.95 points to 2,741.68.
   The dollar fell against most major currencies.
   Bond prices finished little changed.
   Copper futures prices fell sharply; precious metal futures
rebounded from Monday's selloff; grain, soybean, livestock and
energy futures rose and hog futures closed mixed.
</TEXT>
