<FILEID>AP-NR-12-06-89 0209EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-IBMCuts-History     12-06 0208</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-IBM Cuts-History,0214</SECOND>
<HEAD>Latest Job Cuts Are Fourth Program Since 1986</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Computer Slump, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a history of job-cutting programs at
International Business Machines Corp. since 1986.
   September 1986: IBM announces retirement incentives that add
five years to the age and five years to the length of service of
eligible employees for purposes of calculating retirement benefits.
By the end of 1987, 15,000 employees accept the incentives,
including 13,000 in the United States.
   June 1988: IBM announces separation incentives aimed at
manufacturing and development employees in Tucson, Ariz., and Boca
Raton, Fla., and at headquarters employees across the United
States. About 7,000 U.S. employees accept.
   September 1989: IBM announces separation incentives to employees
in selected skill groups in Owego and Endicott, N.Y., Lexington,
Ky., and Manassas, Va. The company expects 600 to 1,000 to accept
by the end of 1989.
   December 1989: IBM announces it will offer separation incentives
aimed at cutting 10,000 U.S. employees, mainly in staff and support
functions. Employees who accept will receive one week's salary for
each six months of service, up to a maximum of 52 weeks of salary.
The company says most of the employees are expected to leave in the
first half of 1990.
</TEXT>
