<DOCNO> AP891206-0172 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-06-89 0209EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-BrokerTV     12-06 0411</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Broker TV,0425</SECOND>
<HEAD>Subscription TV Network Planned for Financial Professionals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A subscription television network that will
carry training and information programs for investment
professionals is scheduled to debut in January, the developers of
the service announced.
   The Financial Satellite Network is being marketed to
stockbrokers, bankers, insurance agents and financial planners, and
22 clients with about 240 offices have already signed up, said John
Drossos, chairman and chief executive of the parent company of the
network, Drossos Financial Inc. of San Antonio, Texas.
   Starting Jan. 2, he said, the network will carry four hours of
programs that will be delivered every business day via satellite to
subscribers.
   The subscription cost is $545 a month per site. The network
operators will provide a satellite dish for each site and connect
the dish to all of the televisions in each office. There will be no
advertising on the network.
   Drossos said Tuesday the service is designed to keep brokers and
other financial professionals abreast of the latest market trends
and enhance their sales skills without having to leave the office
for seminars.
   The network will offer 15 rotating series of programs on topics
such as financial planning techniques, legal issues facing brokers
and telemarketing techniques as well as interviews with market
movers, discussions of the latest financial instruments and trading
strategies and motivational lectures.
   The material will be produced by the company, Drossos said. The
network will operate between 12:30 p.m. and 4:30 p.m. Eastern time
each weekday so employees can watch parts of the program on breaks
or lunch hours.
   Drossos declined to say how much had been invested in the launch
of the network, but said that he hopes to have 1,500 to 2,000
subscribers by the end of the first year.
   Tim Harrington, the president and chief operating officer of
Drossos Financial, said the breakeaven point is about 825
subscribers. He founded Westcott Communications, a satellite
network company that offers subscription networks for automobile
dealers and law enforcement personnel.
   One of the charter subscribers to Financial Satellite Network is
D.A. Davidson &amp; Co., a full-service brokerage in Great Falls, Mont.
   Gerry Meyer, a Davidson vice president, said the main attraction
of the network is that it will expose Davidson brokers to the
latest commentary from some of the country's top investment
professionals.
   ``When you are in Great Falls, Montana, you can't just jump in
cab to go listen to some of these people,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
