<DOCNO> AP891206-0173 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-06-89 0212EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-BerlinWallAds Bjt   12-06 0703</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Berlin Wall Ads, Bjt,0724</SECOND>
<HEAD>Berlin Wall Will Be a Popular Symbol in Commercials</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Along with East European freedom seekers, the
Berlin Wall is attracting American admakers.
   In the month since the historic opening of the border between
East and West Germany, admakers for Pepsi-Cola Co., American
Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co. and the fragrance marketer Quintessence
have filmed commercials at the wall.
   They said their ads, which will be running through ther holiday
season, are designed to celebrate the exhilaration and emotion of
newly won freedom.
   Pepsi-Cola, the soft drink arm of Pepsico Inc., said Tuesday its
commercial features a documentary-style montage of people
approaching the wall about 10 days after the border was opened in
early November.
   Its admakers tried to ``blend in with the news crews that were
there'' to capture genuine, unscripted moments that exemplified the
joys of freedom, said Pepsi spokesman Tod MacKenzie.
   In the 30-second commercial that was scheduled to debut next
Tuesday night and run repeatedly on network television through Jan.
1, MacKenzie said a young woman is shown handing a flower to a
border guard and a group of young children use small hammers to
chip at the wall. No actors were used in the ad.
   ``In this season of giving, the gift of freedom is the greatest
gift of all,'' a narrator says. The Pepsi-Cola name appears at the
end of the spot but it makes no specific product pitch.
   Admakers for AT&amp;T interviewed people at the wall and near the
border crossing points in Berlin in which they recalled what they
did when the border was opened and how it made them feel.
   A number of those interviewed told how they called friends and
relatives with the news. Those interviews will be intercut with
interviews being shot now in the United States of people who have
relatives in East or West Germany.
   One-minute and 30-second versions of the ad will be made for use
on television starting Dec. 17, according to the admakers.
   ``The idea was that we can help people share their thoughts and
feelings,'' said David Robertson, division manager of advertising
for AT&amp;T in Basking Ridge, N.J.
   The Quintessence ad tells the story about an elderly East German
man crossing the border into West Berlin, evidently to be reunited
with his family and a grandson he may have never seen.
   As the man passes through a checkpoint, his grandson runs toward
him and they embrace. An East German border guard picks up a teddy
bear that the older man dropped and hands it to the youngster.
   The commercial was designed to acquaint people with the name of
the privately-held fragrance company, formerly Beecham Cosmetics,
whose brands include Jovan Musk and Adidas for Men, according to
President Joseph Aramanda.
   ``It is a holiday message that says peace on earth,'' he said.
   The commercial, filmed in late November in West Berlin, debuts
Dec. 12 on network television during a broadcast of CBS' ``Beauty &amp;
The Beast.''
   Victor Zast, senior vice president for marketing at the
Chicago-based Quintessence, said the ad included five West Germans
and 18 East Germans, who were offered the equivalent of $55 to
appear in the ad _ the same as East Germans were getting as a
welcoming gift from the West German government upon arriving in
that nation in the first days after the border was opened.
   ``Crowd control was something of a problem,'' Zast said. But he
said the admakers were ``blessed with a snowstorm'' the morning
they started shooting the ad _ a fitting start to a holiday
commercial.
   In another move marking changing East-West relations, Coca-Cola
Co. this week is airing a slightly altered version of its ``General
Assembly'' commercial for Coca-Cola Classic, which features more
than 1,000 young people from many nations singing a song in 16
languages.
   The song's message, ``Promise us tomorrow, and we'll build a
better world for you,'' marked the 1987 Reykjavik Summit between
former President Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev.
   The version airing this week carries these words on the screen
at the end: ``Today, as barriers between people come down,
Coca-Cola celebrates the hope of a better tomorrow.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
