<DOCNO> AP891206-0174 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-06-89 0213EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-GAFTrial     12-06 0592</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-GAF Trial,0613</SECOND>
<HEAD>Key Phone Records Contradict Government; Liv Ullman Testifies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense lawyers in the GAF Corp. stock
manipulation trial have introduced newly obtained telephone records
that appear to contradict pivotal government testimony about calls
discussing the alleged fraud.
   GAF attorney Arthur Liman called the records, which previously
were thought to be nonexistent, ``obviously very crucial,
extraordinary.''
   The new evidence indicates no calls were placed on long-distance
WATS lines from the Jefferies &amp; Co. brokerage to GAF or its vice
chairman, James T. Sherwin, during times in October 1986 when the
government alleges the manipulation was discussed.
   The defense rested its case Tuesday after actress Liv Ullman
testified on Sherwin's behalf as the final witness in the
seven-week criminal trial in Manhattan federal court.
   GAF, two subsidiaries and Sherwin are charged with allegedly
trying to boost Union Carbide Corp.'s share price in 1986 shortly
before selling a large block of the stock after a failed takeover
bid. They also were charged with securities fraud, wire fraud and
conspiracy.
   The case is in its third trial after two mistrials earlier this
year.
   Jefferies &amp; Co. trading director James T. Melton has testified
he called Sherwin between 4:30 p.m. and 5 p.m. on Oct. 29, 30 and
31 in 1986 _ shortly after the Pacific Stock Exchange closed _ to
discuss actions taken those days to close the stock above $22 a
share, as allegedly ordered by Sherwin.
   Other calls to Sherwin to discuss the scheme allegedly were made
while he was at his doctor's office and at Standard &amp; Poor's Corp.
   But American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co. records introduced Monday
indicate that no calls were made during the half hour in question
on any of Jefferies &amp; Co.'s 15 WATS lines to GAF or Sherwin or to
the other offices.
   Liman said the records contradicted testimony by Melton and his
trading assistant, Maureen O'Connor, who said Melton called Sherwin
``within moments'' of the market's close.
   Defense lawyers said privately they believe the new information
shows that the calls to Sherwin never were made. No records of the
calls appeared on Jefferies &amp; Co.'s regular long-distance telephone
bills either.
   The defense called an AT&amp;T supervisor who retrieved the records
and a private investigator who analyzed them on the witness stand.
Assistant U.S. Attorney Carl H. Loewenson Jr. did not attempt to
rebut the testimony.
   The purpose of the alleged stock manipulation was to maximize
profits after a failed takeover attempt by Wayne, N.J.-based GAF of
much larger Union Carbide. GAF, a specialty chemicals company, held
10 million shares of Union Carbide after the failed bid and sold 5
million in November 1986 for $23 a share.
   Ullman testified she has known Sherwin 10 years through work on
a refugee settlement organization, the International Rescue
Committee. Ullman is a vice president of the group and Sherwin is
chairman of its executive committee.
   ``I would say he is, from my heart, the most honorable, moral
man I have ever met,'' the Norwegian film star said under
questioning from Sherwin's lawyer, Stephen Kaufman.
   Ullman, who has appeared in such films as director Ingemar
Bergman's ``Cries and Whispers'' and ``Scenes From a Marriage,''
testified for about 10 minutes about her career, extensive human
rights work and association with Sherwin.
   Afterward, she talked briefly with Sherwin and kissed him on the
cheek before leaving the courthouse.
   Closing arguments in the trial were expected to last two days
and the case could go to the jury for deliberations Friday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
