<DOCNO> AP891206-0176 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-06-89 0215EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-ProgramTrading     12-06 0576</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Program Trading,0594</SECOND>
<HEAD>Strategy Down Sharply in Early November After Backlash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Program trading activity dropped sharply in the
first two weeks of November after a backlash against the
controversial strategy, which is blamed by some for causing market
turmoil.
   New York Stock Exchange figures released Tuesday showed a steep
decline in index arbitrage, the main form of computerized program
trading, reflecting an exodus by large brokerages from the strategy
after it came under fire following the sharp stock market drop of
Oct. 13.
   Index arbitrage accounted for 38.7 percent of program trades
from Nov. 6-10 and 25.7 percent from Nov. 13-17, down from 53.8
percent in all of October, the Big Board said in its first weekly
reports on program trading.
   The NYSE is releasing the data as part of a series of moves to
control stock market volatility implemented after the sudden
190-point market decline on Friday the 13th and an 80-point rise
Oct. 24.
   The new figures also indicated a large jump in program trading
compared with the rest of the week during a sharp intraday decline
on Nov. 6, when the Dow Jones industrials average fell 30 points
from the previous day's close at 11:15 a.m.
   The Big Board said program trading accounted for 13.6 percent,
or 1.94 million shares, of 14.3 million shares traded from 11 a.m.
to 11:30 a.m.
   As part of its weekly report, the NYSE said it will profile
program trading activity for half-hour periods when the Dow drops
30 points from the previous day's close or moves 30 points in a
single direction.
   Since the NYSE does not break down program trading daily, it is
not possible to determine whether the amount of program trading in
the half-hour period on Nov. 6 exceeded program trading the rest of
the day.
   Overall in the first weekly report, program trading strategies
accounted for 6.7 million of an average daily NYSE volume of 148.8
million shares, or 4.5 percent. Buy programs totaled 3.0 million
shares and sell programs 3.7 million, the exchange said.
   For the second week, the trading totaled 7.9 percent of an
average daily volume of 147.7 million shares, or 11.6 million
shares a day. Buy programs accounted for 7.7 million shares and
sell programs for 3.9 million shares.
   The Big Board defines program trading as any order for the
simultaneous purchase or sale of 15 or more stocks. Index arbitrage
involves rapid trading of stocks in New York and stock-index
futures in Chicago to profit from momentary price discrepancies
between the two markets.
   Critics say index arbitrage exaggerates market movements,
triggering waves of selling and sometimes buying. Defenders say the
strategy helps stabilize trading by linking the two markets,
pulling prices closer together.
   The new NYSE figures showed a drop in program trading from
October, when the strategies accounted for 9.7 percent of daily
NYSE volume of 182.4 million shares, or 17.7 million shares a day.
   The exchange began compiling program trading volume on a monthly
basis in August 1988. The lowest monthly total to date was 7.6
percent last April.
   Morgan Stanley &amp; Co., which ceased index arbitrage for its own
account but continues it for customers, was the leader in the
trading, with 10.9 million shares for Nov. 6-10 and 23.2 million
shares Nov. 13-17. Salomon Brothers Inc. was a distant second with
4.9 million shares traded the first week and 4.5 million the second.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891206-0177 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-06-89 0219EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-AutoSales Bjt   12-06 0590</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Auto Sales, Bjt,0610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sales Slump Continues; One Analysts Blames New Models</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Auto Sales-Table</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 9.3 percent decline in late-November sales of
North American-made cars and light trucks continues a downward
trend that one analyst says reflects boredom among consumers over
the new model lineup.
   The eight major automakers with U.S. assembly plants reported
Tuesday they sold vehicle at an average daily rate of 37,059 during
Nov. 21-30, compared with 40,843 a day on average during the same
time last year.
   Car sales were down 12.5 percent and light truck sales were off
3.8 percent.
   The slump during the 10-day period continues a decline that
began in early October, just as the 1990 model year got under way.
   ``There's not a lot of excitement left in the industry,'' said
auto analyst Paul Kleinaitis of Duff &amp; Phelps Inc. in Chicago.
``Everybody's got sort of the same cars.''
   General Motors Corp., Ford Motor Co. and Chrysler Corp., which
make up more than three-quarters of the North American-produced
auto market, reported their combined car and truck sales fell 14
percent during the period this year compared with last year.
   For the month of November, with imported cars and trucks counted
in, vehicle sales fell 11.9 percent, with car sales dropping 13.5
percent and light truck sales off 8.5 percent.
   Through the first 11 months of this year, domestic and import
car and truck sales were running 4.5 percent behind last year's
pace, with car sales down 5 percent and light truck sales off 3.2
percent.
   GM said sales of its North American-built cars fell 24 percent
and light truck sales declined 15.1 percent.
   ``Since about the first of October, we've had less traffic,''
said Frank DeBartolo, general sales manager of Celozzi-Ettleson
Chevrolet-Geo in Elmhurst, Ill. ``The last quarter has taken quite
a bite out of us.''
   Last summer, automakers were faced with swollen new-car
inventories, prompting them to lay on incentive packages to move
the vehicles out of showrooms. The incentives, coupled with news of
pending price increases when the 1990 models began rolling into
dealer lots in early October, forced some people to buy 1989 models
rather than 1990s.
   That resulted in some fourth-quarter sales being stolen by the
third quarter.
   ``What we're seeing now, however, is more than payback for the
pull-ahead,'' said Ford's sales Vice President Robert Rewey. ``Some
prospective buyers are deferring purchases due to uncertainty about
the economic outlook.
   ``More than anything else, that uncertainty is fueled by high
interest rates.''
   DeBartolo said he expected the 1990 sales slump to end in a
month or two, mainly because he sees no long-term economic downturn.
   ``As far as the economy goes, everything is stable,'' he said.
``There's nothing drastic that's going to happen.''
   GM's combined domestic car and truck sales were down 21.1
percent in late November this year compared with last year. For the
entire year, GM's car and truck sales were down 5.5 percent.
   Ford said its late-November vehicle sales were 6.1 percent
behind last year's pace, as car sales dropped 8.7 percent and light
truck sales fell 2.6 percent.
   Through November of this year, Ford's car and truck sales were
running 2.6 percent lower than during the first 11 months of last
year.
   Chrysler said its late-November car sales fell 15.7 percent but
its truck sales during the period rose 1.6 percent, combining for a
7 percent decrease. Year-to-date sales of Chrysler cars and light
trucks were running 6.4 percent below last year's pace.
</TEXT>
