<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Markets     12-06 0313</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0327</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stocks Hit Another Record High, Dollar Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange's key index closed at a
record high today for the 10th time in the last 11 trading days,
while the dollar rose marginally against the Japanese yen.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 160.12 points, or 0.43
percent, closing at 37,654.29. It had gained 190.30 points on
Tuesday in its current record-setting run, which paused only Friday.
   Today, the index dipped in early trading on selling to take
profits, but Daiwa Securities dealer Kazuyuki Suzuki said
investors' buying incentives were much stronger than their concerns
over the rapid increase in share prices.
   ``It seems the index just could not stop rising,'' he said,
adding that it probably will reach 38,000 by the year's end.
   On the first section, an estimated 1.2 billion shares changed
hands, down from Tuesday's 1.3 billion. Among gainers were
electrical, housing and chemical shares.
   In currency dealings, the dollar closed at 143.75 yen, up 0.07
yen from Tuesday's close of 143.68 yen. It opened at 143.72 yen and
stayed in a narrow range between 143.65 yen and 143.76 yen. The
dollar now has climbed 0.85 yen in the last four days.
   ``The range is just getting narrower and narrower,'' Mitsui Bank
trader Yoshitsugu Hanada said, attributing this to a lack of fresh
market-affecting news.
   Spot trading totaled $3.1 billion, down from Tuesday's $4.1
billion.
   The dollar also moved little against the West German mark
despite traders' expectations that the U.S. currency would weaken
against the mark, Hanada said.
   ``It didn't work that way here because Japanese investors still
have strong demand for the dollar,'' he said.
   He added that recent currency rates were influenced more by
investors' supply and demand, rather than economic trends.
   Thus Friday's announcement of U.S. unemployment figures for
November will have little impact on the market, he said.
</TEXT>
