<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market was mixed in relatively subdued
early trading today.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was down 2.35 points to
2,739.33 at 10 a.m. EST, a half-hour after the opening.
   Advancing issues narrowly outnumbered decliners on the New York
Stock Exchange, with 472 issues up, 447 down and 549 unchanged.
   Big Board volume came to 19.39 million shares.
   Analysts said many investors are cautious ahead of Friday's jobs
report, which they hope will provide a clearer picture of the
economy's direction. Data suggesting a further slowdown in economic
growth likely will be positive for the market, analysts say,
because it would raise expectations that the Federal Reserve will
continue easing interest rates.
   ``There's a lack of direction. People don't know what to do,''
said Hildegarde Zagorski, analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities
Inc. ``They're sitting around waiting for Friday's report.''
   Later this morning the Labor Department reports third-quarter
productivity and the Federal Reserve issues its ``beige book,'' a
summary of economic conditions in the country prepared ahead of the
central bank's policy meetings.
   Analysts said they expect both to confirm existing data pointing
to slower growth.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was
up 0.07 to 193.26.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index was up
0.10 to 374.98.
   On Tuesday, the Dow Jones industrial average fell 11.95 points
to 2,741.68.
   Losing issues outpaced gainers by about 9 to 7 on the NYSE, with
831 issues down, 656 up and 506 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board totaled 154.64 million shares, up from
150.36 million in the previous session.
