<FILEID>AP-PX-12-06-89 1141EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-BankEarnings 2ndLd-Writethru   12-06 0574</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bank Earnings, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0588</SECOND>
<HEAD>Banks Lost $744 Million in Third Quarter This Year</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New material, editing to trim, throughout</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's commercial banks lost $744
million in the third quarter this year, the first loss in more than
two years, the government said today.
   The bulk of the red ink was concentrated in several large banks
that set aside new reserves for expected losses on loans to Third
World nations, as well as in rising real estate loan problems in
the Northeast and Arizona, the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. said.
   FDIC Chairman L. William Seidman also said the insurance fund
protecting deposits at 12,824 U.S. banks likely will record the
second loss in its history this year. The fund declined by about $4
billion in 1988 and will shrink by an additional $250 million to
$500 million this year, he said.
   Bank failures, totaling 192 so far this year, likely will
approach but not exceed last year's record of 211, Seidman said.
Based on a fall in the number of problem banks from 1,394 at the
start of 1989 to 1,134 at the end of September, he predicted the
failure rate would decline next year.
   Seidman said banks should approach commercial and development
real estate lending more cautiously. Although bank profits overall
likely will bounce back in the final three months of 1989, the
number of sour real estate loans will continue to rise, he
predicted.
   ``I don't want to Scrooge up Christmas ... but I'm afraid the
fourth quarter will show a continuation of the (real estate) trends
we see here,'' Seidman said.
   The loss in the July-September period compares with profits of
$7 billion in the second quarter and $7.3 billion in the first
quarter. Last year banks earned a record profit of $25.2 billion.
   Commercial banks last recorded a loss in the second quarter of
1987. Red ink totaled $10.6 billion and was attributed to losses on
developing country lending.
   Some of the nation's largest banks again took writedowns in the
third quarter on their loans to developing countries. J.P. Morgan &amp;
Co. increased its loss reserves by $2 billion, Chase Manhattan
Corp. by $1.3 billion and Manufacturers Hanover Trust Corp. by $950
million.
   Analysts attributed the writedowns to banks' recognition that
Treasury Secretary Nicholas F. Brady's debt strategy will require
them to accept more losses.
   Brady's plan, launched in March, emphasizes debt reduction as
well as new lending to developing countries. However, critics of
the plan worry that banks will be reluctant to make new loans after
recognizing big losses.
   Commercial real estate lending problems, common in the Southwest
since the mid-1980s, are spreading elsewhere. In August, Moody's
Investor Service warned that involvement in real estate lending
makes large banks vulnerable to rising interest rates or a
recession.
   In a speech Tuesday, Seidman called real estate lending is ``an
emerging area of concern'' and said his agency was studying real
estate markets nationwide.
   ``Over the last 12 months, real estate loan growth has accounted
for nearly two-thirds of all bank asset growth, and now comprises
almost one-fourth of all commercial bank assets,'' Seidman told a
meeting of the National Council of Savings Institutions in New York.
   Delinquent real estate loans constitute almost half of all sour
loans nationally, he said. In the Northeast, the percentage of
delinquent real estate loans has doubled in the past year, he said.
</TEXT>
