<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0374</SECOND>
<HEAD>Corn and Wheat Prices Grain on Expectation of Increased Exports</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and futures were higher in early trading
today on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Wheat prices climbed as traders reacted to news that the
Agriculture Department has targeted China for 1 million metric tons
of wheat under the export bonus program.
   Prices also were expected to get a boost from continued dry
conditions in the winter wheat crop area.
   Follow-through buying by commercial houses gave corn prices some
support, said analyst Martyn Foreman of AgriVisor Service Inc. in
Bloomington, Ill.
   Foreman said traders also were encouraged by optimistic
pronouncements by negotiators attending the U.S.-Soviet grain talks.
   Despite opening higher, analysts say soybeans looked weak
because of a lack of export business, and news that Argentine
farmers are enjoying adequate soil moisture and are moving ahead
with soybean planting.
   In early trading, wheat was 1\ cents to 3} cents higher with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.06\ a bushel; corn was {
cent to 1\ cents higher with December at $2.35 a bushel; oats were
\ cent to { cent higher with December at $1.44} a bushel; soybeans
were \ cent to 1{ cents higher with January at $5.76 a bushel.
   Livestock futures were lower and pork futures mixed in early
trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Light beef demand at the retail level was a drag on cattle
futures, as were lower cash prices.
   Hog futures were pressured by mixed pork product prices,
although support came from an announcement that the Commodity
Credit Corp has accepted offers in its latest weekly tender for
1.48 million pounds of bellies.
   Live cattle were .20 cent lower to .18 cent higher with December
at 75.50 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .22 cent lower to .08
cent higher with January at 82.75 cents a pound; hogs were .05 cent
to .15 cent lower with December at 51.12 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .02 cent lower to .45 cent higher with February at
55.45 cents a pound.
   Livestock futures settled higher and pork futures were mixed in
Tuesday's trading.
