<FIRST>r f BC-ControlData     12-06 0269</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Control Data,0276</SECOND>
<HEAD>Control Data Elects Perlman CEO</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BLOOMINGTON, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Control Data Corp. President Lawrence
Perlman has been named to the additional position of chief
executive officer, the computer services company said Wednesday.
   Perlman succeeds Robert M. Price, who will remain chairman of
the board, Price said in a prepared statement. Perlman begins his
new duties Jan. 1.
   Price said Perlman has shown ``the kind of exceptional strategic
vision and managerial prowess that was essential in helping to turn
this company around ... and I have every confidence that he is the
right man to lead Control Data forward.''
   Perlman was named president and chief operating officer of
Control Data in December 1988. Previously, he had been president of
Control Data's disk drive operation. In that capacity, he
transformed what was an ailing division into a profitable
operation, Price said.
   In October, Control Data credited extensive restructuring for
third-quarter earnings of $9.8 million, compared with a $2.4
million earnings loss in the same 1988 period. For the first nine
months of this year, the company reported a loss of $484 million,
compared with earnings of $14.5 million for the 1988 period.
   A $497 million loss in the second quarter of this year was
forecast by the company in April when it shut down the ETA Systems
supercomputer subsidiary and cut 3,100 jobs. Closing the St.
Paul-based ETA cost Control Data around $335 million. The balance
of the charges came from shrinking the Cyber mainframe division,
paying severance to cover corporate staff layoffs and the company's
departure from the training and education business, the company
said then.
</TEXT>
