<TEXT>
   Stock prices were narrowly mixed in moderate
trading today. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was down
3.41 points to 2,738.27 at noon EST. The blue-chip indicator was up
0.64 point an hour earlier.
   Advancing issues narrowly outpaced decliners on the New York
Stock Exchange, with 657 issues up, 619 down and 568 unchanged.
   Big Board volume came to 72.74 million shares.
   Trading in IBM stock dominated the market for the second day
after the announcement Tuesday of a massive restructuring.
Investors were selling IBM stock in early trading today after
Tuesday's gains.
   ``Overall the market is moving with IBM,'' said L. Crandall
Hays, equities analyst with Robert W. Baird &amp; Co. ``People don't
know what IBM is going to do.''
   Analysts also attributed the market's weakness to investor
skittishness ahead of Friday's jobs report. Data suggesting a
further slowdown in economic growth likely will be positive for the
market, analysts say, because it would raise expectations that the
Federal Reserve will continue easing interest rates.
   ``There's a lack of direction. People don't know what to do,''
said Hildegarde Zagorski, analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities
Inc. ``They're sitting around waiting for Friday's report.''
   The Labor Department reported today that productivity in the
non-farm sector of the economy improved at an annual rate of 2.5
percent in the third quarter. Despite the gain, the report showed
that the hours worked grew at a slower 1.3 percent, a sign of
slackening demand for goods.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was
up 0.01 at 193.20.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index was up
0.58 to 375.46.
   Among actively traded issues on the NYSE, IBM was down 1 to 98|,
First Interstate Bancorp was off 1| to 51| and Wells Fargo had lost
2} to 71\.
   General Electric, meanwhile, was up ] to 63}, Chrysler was up {
to 19{ and Chevron was unchanged at 70}.
