<FIRST>r f BC-Renault-Volvo     12-06 0242</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Renault-Volvo,0253</SECOND>
<HEAD>Say Renault-Volvo Merger Talks Stall, No Partnership Seen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Merger negotiations have nearly collapsed between
the state-owned Renault automaker and Sweden's Volvo, and both
companies are seeking other possible partners.
   French Industry Minister Roger Fauroux disclosed the stalled
negotiations Tuesday, leaving the two automakers vulnerable in the
face of intensifying competition in Europe.
   ``No one should expect a large-scale operation or a global
linkup in the coming weeks,'' he told a news conference. ``That
would be an illusion.''
   The companies have been talking for several months on
collaboration that might eventually have led to a full merger of
their car and truck building activities.
   One possible outcome would have given Renault control of Volvo's
car activities while the Swedish group would have been given
responsibility for Renault's RVI truck division.
   Fauroux told reporters that although the talks have entered what
he called a less active phase, ``This does not mean that we cannot
arrive at a partial solution.'' He did not elaborate on what a
partial solution might mean.
   French auto industry analysts said it now appears that the two
groups have limited the scope of their negotiations to possible
technical or commercial cooperation. They said the Swedes
apparently balked over the idea of such a large chunk of Swedish
industry coming under the French national flag.
   Volvo and Renault already have a joint venture that manufactures
car engines, while Volvo acts as Renault's distributor in Sweden.
</TEXT>
