<FIRST>u f BC-ChryslerMoves     12-06 0250</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Chrysler Moves,0259</SECOND>
<HEAD>Automaker Considers Selling Aircraft, Defense Electronics Operations</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: AMs planned</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HIGHLAND PARK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. wants to sell its
Gulfstream business aircraft and defense electronics operations to
cut costs and focus on the increasingly fierce car and truck
marketing fray, Chairman Lee A. Iacocca said Wednesday.
   ``We intend to go head to head with the Toyotas and Hondas of
the world as well as anybody else in the market,'' Iacocca said.
   Allen E. Paulson, chairman of Chrysler's Gulfstream Aerospace
unit, said he was resigning from Chrysler's board and taking a
leave of absence to consider bidding for some or all of the
operations of Gulfstream's parent company, Chrysler Technologies
Corp.
   Chrysler Technologies includes Gulfstream Aerospace, maker of
business aircraft including the Gulfstream IV jet; and Electrospace
Systems and Airborne Systems, makers of communications, control and
intelligence systems for planes, ships and ground installations.
   Chrysler said it intends to concentrate its resources on its
core car and truck operations and related financial business,
Chrysler Financial Corp.
   First Boston Corp. has been engaged to advise on the proposed
sale of Chrysler Technologies, though no timetable has been set,
the company said.
   ``The car and truck market is going to be fiercely competitive
in the years ahead,'' Iacocca said. ``The only way to succeed in
this kind of environment is to concentrate all our energies and
resources ....''
   Chrysler, the third-largest U.S. automaker behind General Motors
Corp. and Ford Motor Corp., reported 1988 revenue of $35.5 billion.
</TEXT>
