<SECOND>BC-Norway-Oil,0130</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Companies Drop Planning of Midgard Offshore Field</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil company Saga Petroleum AS said Wednesday
that development planning for its $1 billion Midgard offshore field
has been shelved until buyers are found for its natural gas
reserves.
   Plans for Midgard, in the Haltenbanken province off mid-Norway,
hinged on selling enough natural gas to Sweden and eastern Norway
to justify building a $2.2 billion pipeline.
   Lengthy negotiations with Sweden on sales showed that the
pipeline would be unprofitable, said the Norwegian company in a
press release. Migard is one of several fields under consideration
at Haltenbanken.
   Midgard is owned by Saga; the Norwegian state oil company
Statoil AS; AS Norske Shell; Arco Norge AS; and Deminex Norge AS.
