<FIRST>r f BC-Iran-Petrochemicals     12-06 0175</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Iran-Petrochemicals,0183</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iran To Invest 3.4 Billion Dollars In Petrochemicals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran's minister of economy and finance
said Wednesday the government has earmarked some $3.4 billion in
credits for petrochemical projects in the next five years.
   The Islamic Republic News Agency, monitored in Nicosia, reported
Mohsen Nourbakhsh as saying that the investment is geared toward
self-sufficiency in petrochemicals. He said surplus production
would be exported.
   The large investments in petrochemicals are designed to cut an
annual $2 billion and to generate foreign exchange through exports.
   Speaking to a group of senior banking officials, Nourbakhsh said
the banks should invest in petrochemical, water and soil projects
in the five-year plan.
   The five-year development plan was launched in March, but after
his election in July, Iranian President Hashemi Rafsanjani
announced some major changes in the program.
   The changes are subject to approval by the 270-member
Parliament, or Majlis. Debate on the changes began in the Majlis
Wednesday.
   The Majlis is dominated by hardliners who oppose Rafsanjani's
pragmatic policies and his ambitious economic plans.
</TEXT>
