<FILEID>AP-PX-12-06-89 1710EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Britain-WaterPrivatization     12-06 0454</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Water Privatization,0470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investors Rush to Beat Deadline to Buy Water Shares</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of thousands of investors rushed to beat
the Wednesday deadline for applying to buy shares in Britain's
water industry under the government's $8.2 billion privatization of
the business.
   There had been concern the sale would attract little interest
because of the British stock market's recent sluggishness. The
privatization also has been strongly opposed by critics who say
such a vital utility should remain in state hands for security
reasons and to protect consumers from rate hikes.
   But a line stretched for some 250 yards outside National
Westminster Bank in the City of London financial district as the 10
a.m. deadline approached.
   Geoff Taylor, privatization manager for Natwest, said the bank
had handled previous sell-offs of government industries and ``I
don't think we have ever had a queue as long as this.''
   Environment Minister Michael Howard said, ``It is a
reaffirmation of popular capitalism, and I am very pleased with
that. It is obviously a very enthusiastic response.''
   Some investors said their desire for profit outweighed any
opposition they had to the sell-off. On the unofficial ``gray''
market, the share price is trading at a 27 percent premium to the
government's offering price.
   ``I am not politically in favor of privatizing water, but if
it's going to happen I may as well have a bit of it,'' said
electrician Edward Sutton, who applied for 2,500 shares.
   The government has structured the 140 pence-a-share sale so that
investors put down 100 pence _ the equivalent of about $1.57 _ a
share and pay the rest in installments spanning 20 months.
   Schroders PLC, the investment firm advising the government in
its latest privatization, said the sale of the 10 English and Welsh
water authorities was ``well-subscribed.''
   The offer is expected to be oversubscribed, but Schroders said
exact information on the demand would not be available until later
in the week, because hundreds of thousands of application forms
were handed in at the last minute.
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's Conservative government has
sold off billions of dollars worth of state-owned companies in the
past decade.
   The government also is planning to sell Britain's electricity
industry by mid-1992, in what could be the biggest sale yet at an
estimated $31 billion.
   Most sales, of such companies as Jaguar PLC and British Airways
PLC, have been successful. However, the government's sale of its
remaining one-third stake in British Petroleum Co. PLC flopped
because it coincided with the October 1987 stock market crash.
   When the government announced the price of the 2.183 million
water shares last month, critics said the shares were priced too
cheaply to attract buyers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
