<DOCNO> AP891206-0199 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-PX-12-06-89 1520EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   12-06 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0305</SECOND>
<HEAD>Expectations of Increased Exports Send Prices Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed higher in
active trading Wednesday on the Chicago Board of Trade as traders
reacted to prospects of increased export activity.
   Wheat led the way in the rally, with buying spurred by news that
the U.S. Department of Agriculture has targeted China for 1 million
metric tons of wheat under the department's Export Enhancement
Program.
   Under EEP, private exporters can sell U.S. commodities at
reduced prices to meet foreign competition in selected overseas
markets and then collect free government surpluses of grain or
other commodities as bonuses, or subsidies.
   ``There is speculation that the Soviet Union will be next'' to
benefit from the program, said analyst Ted Mao of Shearson Lehman
Hutton Inc. in New York.
   U.S. and Soviet negotiators are trying to hammer out a new
long-term grain pact. The current grain pact will expire next year.
   Corn futures were higher due to speculative demand resulting
from the strong surge in wheat prices, Mao said.
   The same held true for soybeans, which also drew support from
slow farmer selling and reports of barge delays on the Mississippi
River.
   Analysts said prices were held back by a lack of export
business, and news that Argentine farmers are enjoying adequate
soil moisture and are moving ahead with soybean planting.
   At the close, wheat was 2\ cents to 6 cents higher with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.08{ a bushel; corn was 1\
cents to 2 cents higher with December at $2.35{ a bushel; oats were
} cents to 1\ cents lower with December at $1.43{ a bushel;
soybeans were 2} cents to 6\ cents higher with January at $5.79{ a
bushel.
</TEXT>
