<FILEID>AP-PX-12-06-89 2117EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Saatchi     12-06 0501</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Saatchi,0519</SECOND>
<HEAD>Saatchi Posts Big Loss For Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Saatchi &amp; Saatchi Co. PLC, the world's largest
advertising and marketing services company, reported Wednesday it
lost 58.5 million pounds, or $92 million, for its fiscal year, due
to high costs and troubles with its consulting business.
   While the loss was larger than many analysts had expected, they
said that it resulted largely from management decisions to take
some unusual writedowns.
   The loss for the 12 months ended Sept. 30 contrasted with a net
profit of 75.1 million pounds, which is about $118 million, or 44.5
pence a share, in the previous year.
   Revenue totalled 973.5 million pounds, or $1.5 billion, up 13
percent from 862.2 million pounds a year earlier.
   Saatchi said its pre-tax profits sank 48 percent to 61.3 million
pounds, or $96 million, from 117 million pounds, or $184 million, a
year earlier.
   The company reported unusual costs of 39.5 million pounds, or
$62 million, to cover potential rental costs of surplus office
space and the cost of a reorganization and redundancies in the
communications division, which includes advertising agencies.
   It also had an extraordinary cost of 22 million pounds, or $35
million, arising from its consulting business.
   Communication revenue rose 7.6 percent to 725 million pounds, or
$1.1 billion, while consulting revenue rose 32 percent to 248.5
million pounds, or $390 million.
   ``The major problem this year has been costs rather than
revenues,'' Saatchi said.
   Saatchi has embarked on a number of changes in recent months,
refocusing its business strategy away from consulting and adding
several senior personnel. In October, Robert Louis-Dreyfus was
appointed chief executive of the group.
   Emma Hill, who follows the advertising agency business for
Wertheim &amp; Co. in New York, said, ``The significance of this report
is that the new CEO seems to be cleaning house and forcing a hard
look at the business.''
   The company reportedly is having difficulty in getting the price
it wants for its consulting businesses, which it bought for about
250 million pounds, or $393 million. Saatchi hopes to raise up to
350 million pounds, or about $550 million, from the sales. It has
already sold three consulting businesses _ Gamma, MDK and Cleveland
Consulting Associates _ for $25 million.
   It said in Wednesday's earnings announcement that it has also
agreed to sell its interest in Information Consulting Group to
McKinsey &amp; Co. for $12 million.
   James Dougherty, an analyst with County NatWest Securities USA
in New York, said Saatchi had invested about $30 million in that
operation, which was created about a year ago by a group that
included some top-ranking executives from Arthur Andersen and other
accounting firms.
   He said the operation had been a drain on Saatchi's earnings.
   Saatchi noted that its remaining consulting operations ``have
strong brand names'' and said it ``is not prepared to give up these
valuable assets for less than their market value.''
   The company didn't break out quarterly or half-year results. It
isn't required to under British law.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
