<DOCNO> AP891206-0203 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-PX-12-06-89 2121EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-CanadianBank     12-06 0269</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Canadian Bank,0277</SECOND>
<HEAD>Canada's Largest Bank To Move Into Buffalo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Canada's largest bank announced Wednesday
it plans to open a branch in Buffalo to serve companies taking
advantage of the new U.S.-Canada free trade agreement.
   The Royal Bank of Canada would become the first Canadian bank
with a branch in Buffalo, and James M. Walker, general manager of
its U.S. operations, said it would be the first Canadian bank
branch anywhere in the United States aimed specifically at taking
advantage of the free trade pact.
   Buffalo, astride the main routes between Canada's industrial
heartland near Toronto and the eastern United States, was the
obvious place to locate such a venture, Walker said at a news
conference.
   ``It is a natural gateway for business interests on both sides
of the border,'' he said. ``And clearly, it is a pivotal point for
the largest volume of two-way trade between any two trading
partners anywhere in the world.''
   The Royal Bank of Canada, with assets of about $97 billion in
U.S. dollars, is the largest bank in Canada and the fifth largest
in North America. Its nine existing U.S. offices serve primarily
large multinational companies, but the new branch will focus on
smaller firms as well, Walker said.
   The new branch is expected to open in February after receiving
approval from the U.S. Comptroller of the Currency, he said.
   The bank will provide corporate clients with loans, currency
exchange, letters of credit, help with international mergers and
acquisitions and advice on exploiting Canadian markets, Walker
said. He said there are no plans to expand into retail banking.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
