<FILEID>AP-PX-12-06-89 2122EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-ForeignLanguages     12-06 0274</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Foreign Languages,0285</SECOND>
<HEAD>Business, Educators Urge More U.S. Language Education</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Davydd in 4th graf is cq</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government should promote the
study of foreign languages and countries by establishing an agency
to address American shortcomings in the field, 165 business and
teaching groups said Wednesday.
   The groups, organized as the Coalition for the Advancement of
Languages and International Studies, said the United States is the
only major power that does not require its diplomats to know a
foreign language.
   The United States also is among a few countries in which a
student can graduate from college without studying a foreign
language, the coalition said.
   Davydd Greenwood, who heads the Center for International Studies
at Cornell University, said 40 percent of 99 U.S. companies he
surveyed believed a lack of competence in foreign languages had
hurt profitability. Two-thirds foresaw the need of more competence
to succeed in the future.
   The coalition also called for:
   _More U.S. government support for international exchanges of
students and professionals.
   _New language requirements and performance standards to be set
by state and local authorities, which have the major voice in U.S.
education.
   _Collaboration between business and schools on increasing
Americans' knowledge of the rest of the world.
   Robert Atwell, president of the American Council on Education,
said many universities have dropped language requirements over the
past 20 years.
   Stanley N. Katz, president of the American Council of Learned
Societies, said he drafted a bill for the Congress suggesting a
choice between a government-funded ``National Endowment for
International Education and Competence'' and a private corporation
with a government charter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
