<FILEID>AP-PX-12-06-89 1624EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     12-06 0251</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sharp spike upward in heating oil prices
helped carry energy futures higher on Wednesday.
   The contract for January delivery of wholesale No.2 heating oil,
which had been down as much as .70 cent in early trading, rose .41
cent to close at 64.46 cents per gallon on the New York Mercantile
Exchange.
   Other contract months posted even larger gains, continuing the
week's upward trend. The January heating oil contract gained 0.26
cent on Tuesday.
   Among other refined products traded on the New York Merc,
wholesale unleaded gasoline for January delivery, which gained 0.32
cent on Tuesday, climbed another .33 cent to finish at 53.17 cents.
   The January contract for West Texas Intermediate, the main grade
of U.S. crude oil, rose 13 cents to close at $20.47 per 42-gallon
barrel. The contract had gained 9 cents on Tuesday. Longer-term
contracts posted slightly smaller gains.
   Chris McCormack, a vice president at Drexel Burnham Lambert
Inc., noted that heating oil ``continued to be a driving factor
behind higher prices.'' Unseasonably cold weather in many parts of
the country has increased the demand for fuel.
   McCormack noted, however, the December typically is a weak month
for heating oil contracts. Buying begins in November in
anticipation of cold weather but usually abates until winter really
sets in, usually in January, he said.
   McCormack also said bullishness in the European energy market
spilled over into U.S. trading and helped feed the optimism over
higher prices.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891206-0208 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-PX-12-06-89 1737EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     12-06 0561</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0582</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Lower, Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON-BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar declined against most major foreign
currencies in worldwide trading Wednesday as dealers kept their
buying interest focused on West German marks.
   Gold prices edged slightly higher in the United States after
turning in a mixed performance overseas.
   On the New York Commodity Exchange, gold for current delivery
ended at $404.90 a troy ounce, up $1.40 from late Tuesday. Republic
National Bank of New York quoted a troy ounce of gold bullion at
$404.60 as of 4 p.m. EST, up $1.10 from Tuesday's late bid.
   Currency dealers received an incentive to sell dollars from
reports that a U.S. Treasury official said the dollar's recent
decline against the mark was not alarming, said Thomas Palladino,
an assistant vice president in the Amsterdam Rotterdam Bank's New
York office.
   The remark attributed to David Mulford, Treasury undersecretary,
was interpreted to mean the U.S. government would not intervene
aggressively in foreign exchange markets to stem the dollar's slide
against the mark.
   ``It seems everybody is looking for a lower dollar,'' Palladino
said. ``It's more of a mark-driven market than a dollar-driven
market.''
   Some dealers said the strength of the West German economy
justified the rise in the mark's value.
   Demand for marks has surged as the borders between East and West
Germany have crumbled. The assumption is that liberalizations in
East Germany and elsewhere in Eastern Europe could make the West
German economy boom, possibly leading to higher interest rates in
that country.
   Higher West German interest rates would tend to increase returns
on mark-denominated investments.
   The dollar began its trading day in Tokyo by rising to a close
of 143.75 Japanese yen from 143.68 yen on Tuesday. In London late
Wednesday, the dollar traded at 143.85 yen. Later in New York, the
dollar was quoted at 144.025 yen, up from 143.70 yen late Tuesday.
   In London, the British pound rose to $1.5765 late Wednesday from
Tuesday's $1.5715. Later in New York, the pound rose to $1.5765
from $1.5700.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Tuesday's quotes, included: 1.7660 West German marks, down from
1.7775; 1.5890 Swiss francs, down from 1.5915; 6.0325 French
francs, down from 6.0670; 1,303.25 Italian lire, down from
1,309.00; and 1.16115 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1630.
   Late rates for the dollar in Europe compared with Tuesday's late
rates included: 1.7648 West German marks, down from 1.7790; 1.5875
Swiss francs, down from 1.5910; 6.0315 French francs, down from
6.0675; 2.0010 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0100; 1,301.15 Italian
lire, down from 1,307.00; and 1.1602 Canadian dollars, down from
1.1640.
   Precious metals prices were mixed and gold lost ground on
several world markets as dealers sold to collect profits amassed
during the recent surge in gold prices.
   Gold bullion prices dropped in London, the major market, but
were higher in Zurich, ranging between $400 and $405 a troy ounce.
Gold closed in London at a bid of $402.25 a troy ounce, down from
$404. The closing price in Zurich was $403.75, up from $403.50.
   Earlier in Hong Kong, gold closed at a bid of $400.95 an ounce,
down from $402.95.
   Silver bullion traded late in London at a bid of $5.56 a troy
ounce, down from $5.60. On New York's Comex, silver for current
delivery closed at $5.555 a troy ounce, up from Tuesday's $5.533.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891206-0209 </DOCNO>
