soil moisture and are moving ahead with soybean planting.
   Sugar futures climbed dramatically on New York's Coffee, Sugar &amp;
Cocoa Exchange as traders reacted to news that a Brazilian judge
has banned the import of methanol to alleviate a shortage in fuel
alcohol.
   The ban could divert sugar cane earmarked for export to the
domestic fuel-alcohol industry, analysts said.
   Brazil's 4 million automobiles operate on a mixture of methanol,
ethanol _ sugar-based alcohol _ and gasoline.
   Brazil is committed to export about 640,000 metric tons of
sugar, and by importing methanol, sugar cane was freed for foreign
markets. That could now change, analysts said.
   Sugar was .31 cent to .77 cent higher with January at 14 cents a
pound.
   Gold and silver futures were higher on New York's Commodity
Exchange as the dollar eased against foreign currencies.
   Underpinning precious metals is the belief interest rates are
easing and the unstable situation in eastern Europe remains
unstable, said analyst Betty Raptopoulos of Prudential-Bache
Securities Inc. in New York.
   She noted that the December gold contract, which will cease
trading on Dec. 27, held above the $400-an-ounce mark, an
indication of market strength.
   Gold was $1.20 to $1.40 higher with December at $404.90 a troy
ounce; silver was 1.9 cents to 2.2. cents higher with December at
$5.555 a troy ounce.
   Energy futures rose on the New York Mercantile Exchange, helped
along by the strength in heating oil prices.
   Chris McCormack, a vice president at Drexel Burnham Lambert
Inc., said unseasonably cold weather in many parts of the country
has increased the demand for fuel.
   McCormack also said bullishness in the European energy market
spilled over into U.S. trading and helped feed the optimism over
higher prices.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil was 10 cents to 13 cents
higher with January at $20.47 a barrel; heating oil was .05 cent to
.57 cent higher with January at 64.46 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .33 cent to .57 cent higher with January at 53.17
cents a gallon.
   Livestock and pork futures were mixed on the Chicago Board of
Trade.
   Live cattle were .18 cent lower to .20 cent higher with December
at 75.42 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent lower to .10
cent higher with January at 82.92 cents a pound; hogs were .27 cent
lower to .25 cent higher with December at 51.32 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .33 cent lower to 1.20 cents higher with
February at 56.45 cents a pound.
</TEXT>
