<FILEID>AP-PX-12-06-89 1758EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-McGraw-HillCutbacks     12-06 0747</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-McGraw-Hill Cutbacks,0772</SECOND>
<HEAD>Plans Restructuring to Eliminate 1,000 Jobs, Take $220 Million Writedown</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Publishing and information services giant
McGraw-Hill Inc. said Wednesday it was eliminating more than 1,000
jobs, or 7 percent of its fulltime positions, and taking a big
charge in a restructuring to cut costs.
   The company said it would take one-time pretax charges of $220
million, or $152 million after taxes, in the fourth quarter for
writing down the value of assets, closing its General Books unit
and setting up a reserve for employee severance payments.
   Analysts said the job cuts were overdue and that the writedowns
fit a pattern of recent refiguring of asset values in the
publishing business.
   But investors sent McGraw-Hill's stock down following the
announcement, in apparent disappointment at the company's
projection of earnings for 1990 despite the charges being taken
this year.
   In New York Stock Exchange trading, McGraw-Hill closed down $2 a
share at $61.50.
   The company did not specify where the job eliminations would be,
but indicated many would be corporate positions rather than in
operating units, which include Business Week magazine and Standard
&amp; Poor's debt rating service.
   ``The effort to improve productivity and make the organization
leaner is a step in the right direction,'' said Peter Appert, media
analyst for C.J. Lawrence, Morgan Grenfell Inc. But he said the
company should do more.
   ``Operating margins in some of their units are low by industry
standards,'' Appert said, citing TV station operations and some
information services units.
   He said the stock market's negative reaction to the announcement
would do nothing to improve the company's position as a frequent
subject of takeover speculation.
   Bruce Thorp, media analyst for Provident National Bank in
Philadelphia, called the announcement ``one of the more decisive
things'' McGraw-Hill has done. ``They have done a lot of fiddling
with operations in the past,'' he said.
   But he said Chairman Joseph L. Dionne's statement that next
year's earnings excluding non-recurring gains would be within a
range of $3.50 to $4 a share surprised analysts who follow
publishing companies.
   ``It's a sign that business isn't really good,'' he said,
referring to McGraw-Hill and the overall industry.
   ``The outlook was a lot worse than anybody expected,'' said Bert
Boksen, who follows McGraw-Hill for Raymond James &amp; Asscoaites in
St. Petersburg, Fla. ``It indicates a softer than expected outlook
for the school publishing business and a general slowing of the
economy.''
   Several publishing companeies recently have taken writedowns,
including Harcourt Brace Jovanovich Inc. and Paramount
Communications Inc.,which owns Simon &amp; Schuster. Time Warner Inc.
recently agreed to sell its Scott Foresman &amp; Co. for less than it
paid for the unit three years ago and expects to take a pretax
charge of $175 million on the deal.
   McGraw-Hill said the charges include a $145 million asset
writedown, including the shutdown of General Books and writedowns
at the Data Resources economic forecasting unit. The company
declined to provide figures on the size of the book unit, which
sells general interest books.
   It also said it would establish a $75 million reserve for
severance payments connected with the staff cuts.
   The company said it planned to scrap its current internal
structure of three operating companies _ publishing, financial
services and information services _ and have all operations report
to one of two new corporate executive vice presidents reporting to
Dionne.
   One new executive vice president is Harold W. McGraw III,
great-grandson of the company's founder and now in charge of
overseeing the financial services, Business Week, broadcasting,
aerospace and defense groups. He had been head of financial
services.
   The other, Walter D. Serwatka, will be responsible for the
construction, education, professional publishing, legal and
computers and communications groups. He had headed information
services.
   ``Adopting this streamlined corporate structure eliminates an
entire layer of staffing and related expenses associated with the
three operating companies,'' Dionne said in a statement.
   The rest of the jobs being eliminated will result from the
previously-disclosed plans to automate delivery of the F.W. Dodge
Group reports on the construction industry and from corporate staff
reductions, spokesman Stewart Trisler said.
   McGraw-Hill currently employs about 13,700 people, meaning the
reductions would amount to a 7 percent cut in staffing.
   The company earned $54.97 million, or $1.13 a share, on revenue
of $507.4 million in the fourth quarter of 1988. It earned $185.5
million, or $3.83 a share, on revenue of $1.82 billion for all of
1988.
</TEXT>
