<FIRST>u f AM-AlleghenyInternational 1stLd-Writethru   12-06 0433</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Allegheny International, 1st Ld-Writethru,0445</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Approves $6.25 Million Settlement of Shareholder Suits</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with judge approving $6.25 million
settlement of shareholders' lawsuits; picks up 4th graf pvs, The proposal
....</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Allegheny International Inc. said Wednesday a
federal judge has approved a $6.25 million settlement of
shareholders' lawsuits from 1986 that accused some officers and
directors of violating securities laws.
   The settlement of derivative and class-action lawsuits will be
funded by the officers and directors' liability insurance of
Allegheny International. The Pittsburgh-based small appliance
manufacturer will not be required to spend any of its own money to
satisfy claims.
   Under terms of the settlement approved by U.S. District Judge
Gustave Diamond, the company will receive $1 million. Decatur
Income Fund Inc. will receive $337,428 to settle its claim, and all
legal expenses and legal fees will be deducted from the gross
amount.
   The rest of the fund will be divided among investors who bought
Allegheny International common stock, preferred stock and
subordinated debentures between Aug. 1, 1985, and April 18, 1986.
   Class members are eligible to receive compensation if they have
not excluded themselves from the class and file timely proofs of
claims.
   Unsecured creditors, meanwhile, have filed a competing
reorganization plan in U.S. Bankruptcy Court for the financially
troubled company.
   The plan marks the first time any group other than the company
has filed a reorganization plan since Allegheny International lost
its exclusive right to do so in June.
   Allegheny International has operated under Chapter 11 of U.S.
bankruptcy laws for almost two years. During that time, the company
proposed nine reorganization plans, the latest of which was
submitted last week.
   The proposal does not specify whether assets should be sold,
although the unsecured creditors previously have called for the
sale of the company's flagship Oster-Sunbeam small appliance unit.
   Like the company's most recent proposal, the creditors' plan
would repay most of Allegheny International's $740 million in debts
with new stock. Its plan would issue virtually no cash to anyone
other than trade creditors, however, while the company's plan would
distribute $200 million in cash, most of it to bank lenders.
   Those lenders would get only notes and stock under the unsecured
creditors' proposal.
   Unsecured creditors would become the company's majority
stockholders and gain the right to name most directors. Most
creditors would get between 48 and 75.5 shares of common stock in
the reorganized company for each $1,000 they are owed.
   Current shareholders would get only 1.5 percent of the
reorganized company's shares, the same as envisioned in the
company's plan.
</TEXT>
