<FIRST>u f AM-Shell-PlatformRig     12-06 0385</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shell-Platform Rig,0397</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shell Announces $1.1 Billion Oil Development in Gulf of Mexico</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shell Oil Co. unveiled a plan Wednesday to build
the deepest-water oil and natural gas production platform in the
world at a cost of about $1.1 billion.
   The company said it was soliciting bids to build and install a
tension leg platform in the Gulf of Mexico in 2,860 feet of water,
which is more than half a mile deep. Shell said it would be a world
water-depth record.
   The tension leg platform, which employs a relatively new type of
technology, will be in the Gulf about 255 miles southeast of
Houston.
   Last month, a tension leg platform built by Conoco Inc. in the
Gulf in 1,760 feet of water was declared operational. It is the
world's deepest oil and natural gas production platform in
operation.
   Houston-based Shell, a wholly owned subsidiary of Royal Dutch
Shell in The Netherlands, said the cost of the ``Auger'' project,
estimated at $1.1 billion, will include fabrication and
installation of the platform, development drilling, complete
production facilities and pipelines.
   ``The Auger TLP (tension leg platform) represents another giant
step toward narrowing the gap between the industry's ability to
explore and its ability to produce,'' said Frank H. Richardson,
president of Shell Oil. ``This project exemplifies Shell's
continuing commitment to develop the technology necessary to
produce our nation's frontier oil and gas reserves.''
   Shell said the platform will be the first Gulf of Mexico tension
leg platform to support a drilling rig and complete production
facilities.
   Initial development will begin about mid-1990, and the drilling
rig and production facilities will be installed in 1993. The rig
will have 32 well slots.
   The facility will be able to drill 15,000 to 20,000 feet
sub-sea, Shell officials said.
   Production is expected to begin in 1993 and will increase to a
projected peak rate of 40,000 barrels of oil per day in 1995, and
150 million cubic feet of gas per day in the year 2001.
   A tension platform rig floats at the surface of the water and is
connected to a foundation template on the sea floor by tubular
steel tendons. The buoyancy of the platform creates an upward force
that puts the tendons in tension, eliminating vertical motion and
holding the platform in place.
</TEXT>
