<FIRST>r f AM-Sears-Travel     12-06 0289</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sears-Travel,0302</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sears' Entrance In Travel Industry Stirs Mixed Emotions Among Competitors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sears, Roebuck &amp; Co. plans to offer vacation
packages next year to its retail customers, a step that has caused
mixed reaction among travel industry professionals.
   Sears plans to test-market the vacation packages next fall with
a mailing to its charge-card customers in a few major metropolitan
areas yet to be selected, Sears spokeswoman Kathy Gucfa said
Wednesday.
   The packages would likely include air and hotel accommodations
to about 20 destinations including Walt Disney World in Orlando,
Fla., the Caribbean and Mexico, Miss Gucfa said.
   ``We are constantly on the alert to meet the needs of our
customers,'' said Mary Jean Houde, another Sears spokeswoman. ``We
consider travel a growth industry.''
   Voit Gilmore, president of the American Society of Travel
Agents, said that Sears might stimulate business for its
competitors by popularizing certain destinations and boosting
overall demand.
   Travel agents aren't likely to view Sears as a big threat,
Gilmore said. ``The travel market has so much growth potential that
the entry of Sears would not frighten a good professional travel
agent anywhere,'' he said.
   Others said they weren't sure Sears knows the territory.
   ``Personal service is the thing,'' said Cliff Johnson, Midwest
chapter president of ASTA. ``You've got to know the product.''
   ``In an free enterprise service we welcome anyone to come in,
but you can't sell a $3,000 travel product like a pair of shoes or
jeans,'' said Johnson, who is also the president of Johnson Travel
Service, in Oak Park, Ill.
   Joanne Del Debbio, Chicago-area manager of Horizon Travel &amp;
Tours Inc., was blunt in her assessment.
   ``Sears should stick to dry goods...and let travel agents sell
travel,'' she said.
</TEXT>
