<FIRST>r f BC-Argentina-Inflation     12-06 0176</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Argentina-Inflation,0184</SECOND>
<HEAD>November Rate an Unsettling 6.5 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The cost of living rose 6.5
percent in November, indicating inflation is heating up at a time
the government had promised it would be stamped out.
   The monthly hike was the second-lowest this year, but it was
higher than the 5.6 percent tallied in October, reversing a trend
that had been downward since July.
   President Carlos Menem, who took office on July 8, pledged that
a 54 percent devaluation and massive hikes in public service rates
he implemented on July 9 would result in inflation of only 2
percent in December.
   The cost of living so far this year has soared by 3,486 percent,
including a hyperinflationary 197 percent in July. For the 12-month
period through November, it rose by 3,731 percent.
   With Argentina's currency, the austral, trading on the black
market at about 33 percent below its official value, newspapers in
the capital Buenos Aires speculated Wednesday that another
devaluation was imminent.
   The government has denied it is considering a devaluation.
</TEXT>
