<FIRST>u f AM-Champion-Buffett     12-06 0479</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Champion-Buffett,0496</SECOND>
<HEAD>Buffett Strikes Again, Buying Stock in Paper Company</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL ARABAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Warren E. Buffett extended his
stock-picking prowess to Champion International Corp. on Wednesday
as his Berkshire Hathaway Inc. bought 300,000 shares of preferred
stock for $300 million.
   Berkshire bought a new series of convertible stock that gives
the Omaha, Neb.-based company about 8 percent of shareholders'
voting rights in Champion, a paper products company with $5.1
billion in sales last year.
   Berkshire will have voting rights with the preferred stock
``because that's how it's negotiated,'' said Champion spokesman
Robert W. Turner.
   ``We are delighted to place this issue with a long-term investor
who has such an outstanding reputation,'' said Andrew C. Sigler,
Champion's chairman and chief executive officer.
   Buffett is famous for buying stock in companies that turn out to
be good long-term investments. His picks include Salomon Brothers
Inc., Coca-Cola Co., Gillette Co. and Capital Cities-ABC Inc.
   ``The big thing about Buffett is he's in for the long term,''
Turner said, ``and that has been what our chairman, Andy Sigler,
has been saying for years and years _ that to be competitive
worldwide you must make capital investments over the long term.''
   Stamford-based Champion makes paper primarily for copiers,
magazines, catalogs and newspapers. The company owns 6.4 million
acres of timberland in the U.S. and also makes plywood and lumber.
   It is a leader in an industry that has enjoyed record profits in
the last few years. But some analysts have predicted a 6-month to
two-year downturn in the industry because of overcapacity and a
corresponding drop in prices.
   For the three quarters ended Sept. 30, Champion had net income
of $329.4 million on sales of $3.896 billion, down from a profit of
$336.5 million on sales of $3.814 billion in the first three
quarters of 1988.
   Berkshire had a profit of $285.7 million on sales of $2 billion
last year.
   Champion issued the shares at $1,000 each, with each share
guaranteed a dividend of 9.25 percent, or $92.50 per year, Turner
said.
   The stock is convertible to common stock, which can reap higher
profits but is riskier because it is not guaranteed a dividend.
   ``The board of directors has the authority from time to time to
issue preference stock, as opposed to common stock,'' Turner said.
``We have not done that very much but it's being done on a
series-by-series basis.''
   He said each preferred share carries about 26.3 votes, or a
total 7.5 million votes, on all issues submitted to shareholders.
That gives Berkshire about 8 percent of the voting rights, based on
91 million to 92 million shares of outstanding common stock.
   Berkshire agreed to limit its ownership in Champion to 18
percent for the next 10 years unless Champion's board approves an
increase. Berkshire also agreed to certain restrictions on
reselling the shares.
</TEXT>
