<FIRST>u f AM-UAL     12-06 0326</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UAL,0340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Employee Buyout Plan Presented to Flight Attendants</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials of UAL Corp. presented their revised
proposal for an employee buyout of the parent of United Airlines to
leaders of the Association of Flight Attendants on Wednesday,
officials said.
   The presentation of the new buyout offer came at what was to be
the opening session of a new round of contract negotiations between
flight attendants and United.
   United's flight attendants have been working without a contract
for two years. The airline's management has been seeking salary and
work rule consessions from the attendants, union officials said.
   Patricia Friend, outgoing president of United's flight
attendants union, refused to comment on Wednesday's talks, only to
confirm that a revised employee buyout plan had been presented.
   Joe Hopkins, a UAL spokesman, also refused to comment on the
talks.
   Analysts believe the management buyout plan will value the
company at $210 to $240 a share, or a total of $4.75 billion to
$5.42 billion.
   It is believed officials of the Chicago-based company are
seeking ironclad commitments from lenders and the company's three
major unions before publicly announcing any buyout offer.
   The previous buyout effort, led by United's management, pilots
and British Airways PLC, failed in October when lenders refused to
finance it.
   The lenders cited the strong opposition of the Machinists union,
which represents about 25,000 of UAL's 70,000 employees.
   Officials of the United chapter of the Air Line Pilots
Association and the Machinists union have refused to comment on the
latest buyout proposal.
   Meanwhile, the New York investment group Coniston Partners has
threatened to oust 13 of UAL's 15 directors and create a
five-member board dominated by the group if the current board fails
to sell or restructure UAL.
   This week Coniston announced it had increased its stake in the
company to 11.8 percent, up from 9.7 percent. UAL stock closed
Wednesday at $176.50 a share, down $5.75, in consolidated New York
Stock Exchange trading.
</TEXT>
