<FIRST>u f AM-Shearson-Perelman 1stLd-Writethru f0288 12-06 0607</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shearson-Perelman, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0288,0622</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Revlon's Perelman May Invest in Shearson</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with report that Shearson considering
$1 billion securities offering and revised deal involving Perelman. Picks
up 13th graf pvs, `On Oct. 30. ...</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   .
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The possible emergence of a third major outside
investor in Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. could be a thorn in running
the troubled investment firm but Chairman Peter Cohen doesn't have
much choice, analysts said Wednesday.
   ``He's got to go somewhere to get some more capital and when you
need more equity capital you've got to pay the price,'' said
securities industry analyst Perrin Long of Lipper Analytical
Services.
   Revlon Inc. Chairman Ronald O. Perelman reportedly is
negotiating to invest hundreds of millions of dollars in Shearson
in exchange for a large stake in the brokerage firm. At the same
time, the brokerage reportedly is preparing to raise up to $1
billion through a new securities offering.
   Perelman would invest $250 million in exchange for a stake in
the company of about 9.9 percent, The New York Times reported in
Thursday editions.
   On Wednesday, the Times reported that Perelman would be able to
obtain about 20 percent of Shearson's stock, or 17.5 million
shares, if he exercised all of his stock options under the deal as
originally proposed. The Times said in Thursday editions that the
planned transaction was altered to make it less complex, according
to the unidentified sources it cited.
   Shearson spokesman Michael O'Neil and Revlon spokesman Jim
Conroy declined to comment on the report in Wednesday's Times.
   Any such deal would provide needed capital for Shearson, which
is 61 percent owned by American Express Co. About 13 percent of
Shearson's stock is owned by Nippon Life Insurance Co. of Japan,
with the rest publicly traded.
   But Long said that further dividing the ownership of Shearson
among three large outsiders could prove to be a headache for
executives under pressure to turn around the firm's slumping
profits.
   A number of Wall Street observers have been waiting for Perelman
to make a move. He had been divesting some operations and amassing
a warchest of hundreds of millions of dollars for some time.
   Perelman was rebuffed two years ago in an effort to buy a block
of stock in Salomon Brothers Inc. and some say he still wants to
obtain a position of authority at a brokerage firm.
   Shearson also was said to be considering other deals, such as
obtaining more capital from American Express in exchange for
selling certain of the brokerage's assets, the Times said. The
Times said as many as seven investors had expressed interest in
buying into the firm.
   On Oct. 30, Moody's Investors Service Inc. said it was mulling a
possible credit rating downgrade for Shearson's bonds and
commercial paper, due to the firm's Shearson's exposure in
debt-financed takeovers and a general slowdown in the securities
industry. Shearson has been trying to raise capital to prevent such
a move, which would raise its borrowing costs.
   A general slump in brokerage activity also has led Shearson to
realign its top management and begin a round of 800 layoffs in an
attempt to increase profitability and cut costs.
   American Express has long said it wants to cut its Shearson
holding to less than 50 percent to limit its exposure to the
vagaries of Shearson's earnings.
   Any deal involving the sale of Shearson shares could be slowed
or blocked by Nippon Life, which holds two seats on Shearson's
board and is its largest shareholder. The deal with Perelman would
make him the second-largest Shearson shareholder other than
American Express.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
